1. e4 e5 { This is a move that not many people are happy to see. Everyone always struggles to find the perfect reply to } ( 1... e5 { , but after this course } ) ( 1... e5 { will be your favorite move to see! } ) 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3e5][%csl Re5,Gf3]Our opponent does not yet know our lethal intentions. } 2... Nc6 { [%cal Gc6e5]By far the mainline. } 3. d4 { [%cal Gf1a6,Gc1h6][%csl Gd4,Re5]White strikes in the center. Now both of White's bishops are opened up. It looks like White is headed for the Scotch game. } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 $3 { [%cal Gc4f7][%csl Gc4,Rf7]The classical move of the Scotch gambit! White prioritizes development and the initiative instead of material. Here I will give you an overview of the lines: } 4... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]The historical mainline that characterizes the Scotch gambit. } ( 4... Bb4+ { is a rare move/sideline that is recommended by the computer. If our opponents are greedy they can play this way - we are fully ready to sacrifice material with } 5. c3 { . } ) ( 4... d6 { is a very passive move where White simply recaptures the pawn with } 5. Nxd4 $146 { . } ) ( 4... Be7 { is another passive developing try. Here too we simply recapture the pawn with } 5. Nxd4 $146 { . These sidelines on move 4 - 4...Bb4+, 4...d6 and 4...Be7 \- are dealt with in chapter 1 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) ( 4... Bc5 { is my personal favorite line to meet in the course! We have a surprise waiting for Black. } 5. c3 { The move ...Nf6 is now more or less forced. } 5... Nf6 $146 { The typical counter-attack in the center. } 6. cxd4 Bb4+ { Black gives a check while the e4-pawn is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $3 $146 { An old line that we revive with a very modern twist! This is my personal favorite variation in the course and is covered in chapters 2-4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). Be sure to check them out! } ) 5. e5 { [%cal Ge5f6][%csl Ge5,Rf6]Here all the fun begins in the Scotch gambit! } 5... d5 { At this point Black has two important alternatives to } ( 5... d5 { , namely } ) ( 5... Ng4 $146 { and } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { . Especially } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { is quite a trendy move. I'll cover both these options in chapter 5 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 6. Bb5 Ne4 ( 6... Nd7 $146 { is another pretty popular sideline. This one is popularized by the fact that it's approved by today's strongest engines! We discuss } ) ( 6... Nd7 $146 { in chapter 6 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 7. Nxd4 Bd7 { Slowly we are getting to the mainline of 4...Nf6! First, here on move 7 Black has an alternative in the aggressive } ( 7... Bc5 $2 { , which sacrifices a pawn or sometimes even more. Check out chapter 7 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 { The mainline of the classical 4...Nf6 Scotch gambit is } ( 9... Bc5 { , which is analyzed in chapter 9 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). But there are two other moves, } ) ( 9... c5 { which is not as good and } ) ( 9... Be7 { which is quite solid. These two other moves are discussed in chapter 8 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } ) 1-0 

