[Result "*"]

{ I know you are biting your nails and are ready to dive into the theory and finish the course ASAP, but before we get into the meat of the course, we should understand the key themes of the Scotch gambit! [--] In the Scotch gambit, we play with passion, fire, and the initiative! There are several recurring themes in this opening, and we should get well acquainted with the Spirit of the Scotch gambit! That way we can let the moves flow from our intuition, from deep within our soul. [--] The Scotch gambit is not for the cowards or for the weak of heart; it is for the warriors and the swashbucklers who come looking for a fight, who want to kill Black's King right from the start and are ready to go for the kill without hesitating. We are not here for boring chess, we are here to fight and win! } * 

[Event "The Fast and Furious Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "1. Playing with the Initiative"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Playing with the Initiative"]
[Black "Key Themes of the Scotch Gambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppnbppp/2n5/1B1pP3/3p4/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the Scotch gambit, the initiative is our best friend! You may ask: what is the initiative? [--] The initiative is about controlling the pace and direction of the game. When we have the initiative we are the ones who are attacking, we are the ones making the threats and Black just sits back and defends as we smile and carry out our plan. [--] In the Scotch gambit, we start with the initiative, we immediately put Black under many threats, and we must keep on doing so throughout the game. How can we do this? With every move we should look to create threats. We keep playing with tempo, we attack Black when we can. All of this will also lead to Black falling under psychological pressure as everyone loves to attack, but no one loves to defend! In this position (which is a critical position in the theory section (See the corresponding variation from the PGN)), Black has just played 7...Be7 \- and now the traditional mainline continues with } 8. c3 $3 { [%cal Gc3d4,Gd4c3,Gb1c3,Gd1d5,Gb5e8][%csl Rd5]White now wants to take on d4 with the pawn, which would give us a rock-solid center of d4+e5. In essence, White gambits a pawn so that the b1-knight quickly comes into the game on c3. [--] This is what we are talking about, the initiative! We keep Black busy and pose questions! We keep jamming down on the gas pedal while Black's car hasn't even started yet. } ( 8. Bxc6 { followed by } 8... bxc6 9. Nxd4 $146 { . However, I recommend a move that keeps the initiative and forces a reaction out of Black, giving them no time to breathe! } ) * 

[Event "The Fast and Furious Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "2. Rapid development"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Rapid development"]
[Black "Key Themes of the Scotch Gambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppppnppp/5n2/3P4/2B5/8/PP1N1PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the Scotch gambit we bring out all of our forces as soon as possible and seek to wreak havoc on Black! In the theory section, you will see that we sacrifice pawns all the time just to have our pieces come quicker into the game. The whole idea of the Scotch gambit is that (after 3.d4 exd4) we leave Black's pawn on d4 for the moment to focus on completing our development. Black is often fumbling to complete their own development in the Scotch gambit. The quicker we bring out our forces, the more pressure we can exert on Black before they escape to safety. [--] This position is featured in the theory section and here I propose a novelty! Black's bishop is still sleeping on c8 and their king is yet to castle. However, Black wants to take our d5 pawn. What should we do? } 11. b4 { [%cal Gc1b2,Gb2g7][%csl Gb4,Rf6]POW. A dynamic move to speed up our development, with our bishop coming to b2 quickly on the next move! This position is analyzed in more detail in the course (See the corresponding variation from the PGN). } * 

[Event "The Fast and Furious Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "3. Central Control"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Central Control"]
[Black "Key Themes of the Scotch Gambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/1bBPn3/5N2/PP1N1PPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the Scotch gambit the battle revolves around the center! In the 4...Nf6 Scotch gambit line, the advanced e5-pawn gives us great central control and more space, enabling us to put most of our pieces on the Kingside. [--] Meanwhile, in the 4...Bc5 line, we usually get a strong central pawn on d5 which cramps Black and gives us much more freedom for our piece. Black remains with a lack of space to maneuver while our central control grants us freedom and easily allows us to bring our pieces into the attack. [--] Central control is very important! Whichever player controls the center controls the game! [--] In this position White plays d5, establishing dominance in the center! } 8. d5 { [%cal Gd5c6][%csl Rc6,Gd5]The d5-pawn cramps Black in the center, severly restricting their pieces. What is beautiful to me is that White is down a pawn, yet Black struggles so much due to our strong pawn on d5! Central pawns are very powerful. } * 

[Event "The Fast and Furious Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "4. Tactical Playground"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Tactical Playground"]
[Black "Key Themes of the Scotch Gambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/ppppnppp/8/2b1n1N1/2B1P3/2P5/P4PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the Scotch gambit tactics flow left, right and center! You better be working on your tactics, because in this repertoire you will get a huge amount of opportunities to unleash your tactical prowess. Why is the Scotch gambit a Tactical Beast? Because Black's position is often loose, their pieces are undeveloped, and their king is unsafe. [--] Try this one: White to play. } 9. Nxf7 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gf7d8,Gf7h8,Gf7e5][%csl Rd8,Gf7,Rh8]POW! Unleashing a deadly blow on f7. } ( 9. Bxf7+ { is also possible. } ) 9... Nxf7 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qh5+ { [%cal Gh5f7,Gh5c5][%csl Rc5,Rf7]White wins back the piece with Black's King now being out in the open. } * 

[Event "The Fast and Furious Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "5. King Safety"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. King Safety"]
[Black "Key Themes of the Scotch Gambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p1pbbppp/2p5/2npP3/3N1P2/8/PPP3PP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the Scotch gambit, King safety is one of the most important themes! Usually our King is safe and Black's King is not. Black always has to worry where to put their King and how to defend. [--] Take a look at this example. } 12. f5 $1 { [%cal Gf5f6,Gc1h6,Gb1c3,Gd1h5][%csl Ge5,Gf5,Rg8]Black has just castled Kingside, but their King is no safer on g8 than on e8 really! The e5 and f5-pawns are coming for the King! Flip the board and see how comfortable you would feel as Black. [--] In the Scotch gambit we practically never have to worry about our own King, while Black is always kept on their toes. } * 

[Event "The Fast and Furious Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "Final Thoughts"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Final Thoughts"]
[Black "Key Themes of the Scotch Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now that you are familiar with some key themes of the Scotch gambit, I hope this will make learning the repertoire a lot easier and more natural for you! In each line we put pressure on Black's position - we go for the kill and we are not afraid to sacrifice material to get rapid development or the initiative! We have a strong central pawn presence giving us central control, and are always ready to go for Black's King while our own monarch smiles safely at home. [--] Now you are ready to become a true Scotch gambit warrior! } * 

[Event "The Fast and Furious Scotch Gambit"]
[Site "4...Bc5 with 7...d5 #1"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 with 7...d5 #1"]
[Black "Quickstarter"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 { An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... d5 { [%csl Gc4,Rd5,Ge4]Black is too cowardly to accept the pawn! This move indicates that our opponent has been shocked by our opening choice and is simply looking for a solid and risk-free game. They are in for a great surprise, as we will take the fight to them! } ( 7... d5 { is a very logical move by its nature. I would expect this move by the most unprepared opponents, and it should be studied very carefully. } ) 8. exd5 { We accept the isolated pawn with no regrets! } 8... Nxd5 9. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8,Gc6d4][%csl Rb4,Gc4,Gd4,Rd5,Re8]A move that requires no explanation. White gets the King out of the center and is ready to become active. } 9... O-O { [%cal Gf3e5,Gd2e4,Gc4d5,Gh2h3,Gc8g4][%csl Gc5,Rc6,Gd4,Rd5,Ge5,Rg4]Black follows. We now have a critical position on the board. It is very important for us to understand this position before trying to memorize any moves. [--] White has an isolated d-pawn which is a static weakness but also a dynamic strength. This pawn gives our pieces outposts on c5 and e5 and greatly helps in the central fight. [--] White also has a very strong Bishop on c4 and meanwhile, the Knights can think about coming to e4 or e5. The Black Knight on c6 is actually a bit misplaced - they would prefer to have the c-pawn there. [--] This position requires dynamic and quick play. If we give Black time to consolidate all of their forces, we would lose our advantage. We must keep up the initiative and pressure on Black's position. Always try to play actively in these types of positions. } 10. a3 $1 { [%csl Rb4]Immediately questioning the Bishop! Will Black give up the Bishop pair or not!? This move is very useful as we can also expand with b4 in the future, putting pressure on the Queenside. } 10... Be7 $5 { A very logical move. Black keeps the Bishop pair. We can expect our opponent to play like this. } 11. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e7][%csl Re7]Because of the isolated pawn we have open e- and c-files, so we better use them! } 11... Bg4 { [%cal Gg4d1,Gc6d4][%csl Rd1]} 12. h3 { [%cal Gh3g4,Gg4f3,Gd2f3,Gc1h6][%csl Rg4]The Bishop is an uninvited guest. We immediately ask it to leave! } 12... Bh5 13. Ba2 $14 { [%cal Gd1b3,Gd5b6,Gd4d5][%csl Gb3,Gb6,Rb7,Rd5]A very important prophylactic move. We avoid ...Nb6 and now we have a huge threat of Qb3, attacking Black's b7-pawn and d5 Knight! [--] There are many other ideas in this position if Qb3 does not work. For example, we have ideas such as g4 to kick the Bishop and then improve our Knight to e4. We have the simple Nf1 to open our c1-Bishop and think of Ne3 or Ng3 in the near future. It is a very rich position, and you should always be on high alert and compare different ideas! } 13... Nxd4 $2 { A blunder! } 14. g4 $18 { [%csl Rh5,Rd5][%cal Gd4f3,Gd1f3,Ga2d5,Gf3d5,Ge1e7]Black loses a piece. } * 

