1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 { An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... d5 { [%csl Gc4,Rd5,Ge4]Black is too cowardly to accept the pawn! This move indicates that our opponent has been shocked by our opening choice and is simply looking for a solid and risk-free game. They are in for a great surprise, as we will take the fight to them! } ( 7... d5 { is a very logical move by its nature. I would expect this move by the most unprepared opponents, and it should be studied very carefully. } ) 8. exd5 { We accept the isolated pawn with no regrets! } 8... Nxd5 9. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8,Gc6d4][%csl Rb4,Gc4,Gd4,Rd5,Re8]A move that requires no explanation. White gets the King out of the center and is ready to become active. } 9... O-O { [%cal Gf3e5,Gd2e4,Gc4d5,Gh2h3,Gc8g4][%csl Gc5,Rc6,Gd4,Rd5,Ge5,Rg4]Black follows. We now have a critical position on the board. It is very important for us to understand this position before trying to memorize any moves. [--] White has an isolated d-pawn which is a static weakness but also a dynamic strength. This pawn gives our pieces outposts on c5 and e5 and greatly helps in the central fight. [--] White also has a very strong Bishop on c4 and meanwhile, the Knights can think about coming to e4 or e5. The Black Knight on c6 is actually a bit misplaced - they would prefer to have the c-pawn there. [--] This position requires dynamic and quick play. If we give Black time to consolidate all of their forces, we would lose our advantage. We must keep up the initiative and pressure on Black's position. Always try to play actively in these types of positions. } 10. a3 $1 { [%csl Rb4]Immediately questioning the Bishop! Will Black give up the Bishop pair or not!? This move is very useful as we can also expand with b4 in the future, putting pressure on the Queenside. } 10... Be7 $5 { A very logical move. Black keeps the Bishop pair. We can expect our opponent to play like this. } 11. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e7][%csl Re7]Because of the isolated pawn we have open e- and c-files, so we better use them! } 11... Be6 { [%csl Gd5,Ge6,Ge7]A very logical move, completing development and adding extra protection to the d5 Knight. } 12. Ne4 $5 { [%cal Ge4g5,Gc1g5,Gf3g5,Gd1c2,Gc4a2]Simple chess - improving our Knight and opening the Bishop! We have ideas such as Ng5 or Qc2 next. } 12... Ne3 $5 { [%cal Ge3d1,Ge3c4,Ge6c4][%csl Rc4,Rd1]Black tries some sly tactics! } 13. Bxe3 Bxc4 14. Rc1 { [%cal Gc1c4][%csl Rc4]White brings his last piece into the game. Although Black has the Bishop pair, White is very active and is keeping up the pressure! } 14... Bd5 15. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3d5][%csl Rd5]Pressuring the Bishop on d5. } 15... Re8 { Bringing the Rook into the game and defending the Bishop. } 16. Bf4 $14 { [%cal Gh2h3,Gf4c7,Gc3d5,Gc1c7,Ge1e7][%csl Rc7]White now threatens Nxd5 followed by Bxc7. White is very active and Black is under pressure. } * 

