1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 { An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... d5 { [%csl Gc4,Rd5,Ge4]Black is too cowardly to accept the pawn! This move indicates that our opponent has been shocked by our opening choice and is simply looking for a solid and risk-free game. They are in for a great surprise, as we will take the fight to them! } ( 7... d5 { is a very logical move by its nature. I would expect this move by the most unprepared opponents, and it should be studied very carefully. } ) 8. exd5 { We accept the isolated pawn with no regrets! } 8... Nxd5 9. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8,Gc6d4][%csl Rb4,Gc4,Gd4,Rd5,Re8]A move that requires no explanation. White gets the King out of the center and is ready to become active. } 9... O-O { [%cal Gf3e5,Gd2e4,Gc4d5,Gh2h3,Gc8g4][%csl Gc5,Rc6,Gd4,Rd5,Ge5,Rg4]Black follows. We now have a critical position on the board. It is very important for us to understand this position before trying to memorize any moves. [--] White has an isolated d-pawn which is a static weakness but also a dynamic strength. This pawn gives our pieces outposts on c5 and e5 and greatly helps in the central fight. [--] White also has a very strong Bishop on c4 and meanwhile, the Knights can think about coming to e4 or e5. The Black Knight on c6 is actually a bit misplaced - they would prefer to have the c-pawn there. [--] This position requires dynamic and quick play. If we give Black time to consolidate all of their forces, we would lose our advantage. We must keep up the initiative and pressure on Black's position. Always try to play actively in these types of positions. } 10. a3 $1 { [%csl Rb4]Immediately questioning the Bishop! Will Black give up the Bishop pair or not!? This move is very useful as we can also expand with b4 in the future, putting pressure on the Queenside. } 10... Bxd2 { Black parts with the Bishop and looks for concrete action next! } 11. Bxd2 Bg4 { [%cal Gg4d1][%csl Rd1,Rf3]A very direct and aggressive approach. Black is fighting hard against our isolated pawn! } 12. h3 { [%cal Gh3g4][%csl Rg4]Kicking out the uninvited guest! } 12... Bh5 { [%cal Gh5d1][%csl Rd1]Maintaining the pin. } 13. g4 $1 { [%csl Gg4,Rh5]White is not afraid to break the pin by weakening the Kingside. Again we see this thematic recurring idea. The pin simply cannot be tolerated. At the moment Black has no pieces near the White King, so White has nothing to worry about. } 13... Bg6 14. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e8]Taking the open file. As we know already, the isolated pawn gives us the open c- and e-files! } 14... Nb6 $5 { Black directly goes after the d4-pawn! } 15. Bb3 { [%cal Gd1e2]The Bishop on b3 here is more useful than on a2. As we will see in the following endgame, it may help to support the a4 move. If Black does not take the d4-pawn, we can consider continuing development with moves such as Qe2. } 15... Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 17. Bb4 $1 { [%cal Gb4f8,Gb3f7][%csl Rf7,Rf8]Forcing the trade of Queens! } 17... Qxd1 18. Raxd1 Rfe8 $6 19. Be7 $16 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gd1d8,Ge7d8,Gb6d5,Gb3a4,Gb3d5,Gb6d7][%csl Ra4,Rb6,Rd5,Rd7,Rd8,Gg6]White is down a pawn but Black is dominated here. White is ready to continue with with f4 going for the Black Bishop. Black is very cramped and short of space for the pieces. } 19... a5 20. a4 { [%csl Ga4,Gb3,Ra5]Stopping Black's a-pawn in its tracks. } * 

