1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 { An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Bxd2+ $5 { [%csl Rd2]A move that seems weird, as Black willingly gives up the Bishop. However, things are more concrete. This is a serious line which we should be aware of. Unless they specifically prepared it, though, I do not expect your opponent to know this move. } ( 7... Bxd2+ { is the third most popular move, with } ) ( 7... d5 { being second and } ) ( 7... Nxe4 $146 { the main move. } ) 8. Bxd2 Nxe4 { [%csl Re4]Black bites the bullet and accepts the 'free' pawn. } 9. d5 { [%csl Rc6,Gd5]Putting a bone in the throat of Black's position. The d5-pawn will cramp Black! } 9... Ne7 10. Bb4 $1 { [%cal Gb4e7][%csl Gb4,Re7]Not giving Black the chance to grab our Bishop anymore! The Knight on e4 will soon come under fire. It is not welcome on our side of the board. } 10... d6 { [%cal Gd6b4][%csl Rb4,Gd6]A smart move, immediately blunting our Bishop. } 11. O-O { [%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7,Gf1e1,Gd5c6,Gd5e6][%csl Rc7,Gd5]White finishes development and it is essential to understand this position. First, White is down a pawn so Black has a material advantage. White has no direct attack against the Black King; the compensation is in a much more positional form. White has the open c-file to pressure Black, and the e-file can be used as well. Because of the d5-pawn, Black is feeling very cramped. White also has the Bishop pair which could become a great asset when the position is opened. } 11... O-O 12. Re1 $1 { [%cal Ge1e7][%csl Re4,Re7]White immediately questions the Black Knight and forces a decision! } 12... a5 { [%cal Ga5b4,Ga8a5,Ge1e4][%csl Rb4,Re4]Black attacks our Bishop while their Knight is hanging. } 13. Bxa5 $1 { [%cal Ge1e4][%csl Ra5,Re4]Regaining the pawn while the Knight is still hanging! } 13... Rxa5 14. Rxe4 $14 { [%csl Ge4]Material is equal again and Black is still cramped. } * 

