1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 { An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Nxe4 { [%cal Ge4d2,Gb4e1][%csl Rd2]The most popular move and the most correct move. Black was offered a pawn, takes an important central pawn and waits for White to prove the compensation! } 8. d5 $1 { [%csl Rc6]Establishing a bone in the throat of Black's position and kicking away the Knight. } 8... Ne7 { Black retreats the Knight without making any exchanges. } 9. O-O { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Re4]} 9... Nxd2 { Black seeks to trade pieces to relieve some pressure. } 10. Nxd2 $1 { [%cal Gb4e1][%csl Gc1]We take back with the Knight in order not to allow Black to trade off the Bishop pair! } 10... O-O 11. a3 { [%cal Ga3b4][%csl Rb4]Going after the Bishop. We are like the hunter in the forest hunting our prey at every turn. } 11... Ba5 { Black is now ready to continue with ...d6 and finish the development while being up a pawn. White has to do something! } 12. d6 $1 { [%csl Rc8,Rd6,Re7]A very powerful move, keeping the Bishop buried on c8. } 12... cxd6 13. Ne4 $14 { [%cal Ge4d6,Gc4f7,Gd1d6][%csl Rc8,Rd6,Ge4,Rf7]White greatly improves the Knight and is ready to take back on d6! } 13... d5 $1 { [%cal Gd5e4,Gd5c4][%csl Gc8,Rd5]Black plays very smartly! They are immediately trying to open the c8-Bishop, even at the cost of giving back both pawns. } 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gd5a5][%csl Ra5]} 15... d6 { [%cal Gc8h3][%csl Gc8,Rd6]Finally the Bishop is free! } 16. Bg5 { [%cal Gg5d8][%csl Rd8]Our own Bishop comes out with deadly effect. Black has to remain on their toes! } 16... Qc7 $4 { Black seemingly moves the Queen away from danger. } 17. Bf6 $3 { [%cal Gd5g5][%csl Gf6,Rg8]A deadly blow aimed at the Black King! Black's position immediately collapses after this. } 17... gxf6 18. Nxf6+ { [%cal Gf6g8][%csl Rg8]} 18... Kh8 19. Qh5 $18 { [%csl Gf6,Gh7,Ra5][%cal Gc7c2,Gh5a5]Black can only defend against mate by playing } 19... Qc2 { , but this drops the Bishop on a5 to } 20. Qxa5 { . } * 

