1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 { An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Nxe4 { [%cal Ge4d2,Gb4e1][%csl Rd2]The most popular move and the most correct move. Black was offered a pawn, takes an important central pawn and waits for White to prove the compensation! } 8. d5 $1 { [%csl Rc6]Establishing a bone in the throat of Black's position and kicking away the Knight. } 8... Ne7 { Black retreats the Knight without making any exchanges. } 9. O-O { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Re4]} 9... Nxd2 { Black seeks to trade pieces to relieve some pressure. } 10. Nxd2 $1 { [%cal Gb4e1][%csl Gc1]We take back with the Knight in order not to allow Black to trade off the Bishop pair! } 10... O-O 11. a3 { [%cal Ga3b4][%csl Rb4]Going after the Bishop. We are like the hunter in the forest hunting our prey at every turn. } 11... Bc5 { Grandmaster Sam Shankland recommended the move in his Berlin LTR. There's no need to fear this move though. We will pose all the faithful followers of Mr. Shankland great issues! To be noted this move was also recommended by IM Piotr Nguyen in his course 'From Berlin to Rio'. } 12. Ne4 { [%cal Ge4c5][%csl Rc5,Ge4]Hitting the Bishop on c5. } 12... d6 { [%cal Gc8h3][%csl Rc5]Mr. Shankland was very happy with this move. To him there seems to be no trouble for Black after we take on c5. Black then wants to brings the Knight via f5 to d6 and 'the extra pawn should tell'. Is that really so? } 13. Nxc5 { We happily capture the strong Bishop. } 13... dxc5 { [%cal Gc8h3,Gc1h6][%csl Gb2,Gc4,Rc8,Gd5,Re7]At the moment Black is up a pawn and Mr. Shankland stops his analysis here. However, we will analyze further and leave his followers in deep and dark waters. We will shank the Shankland supporters with the power of our Bishop pair. [--] White is down a pawn for the moment, but if there is anything that you will learn from this course, is that we don't mind sacrificing a pawn for active play and the initiative. [--] Black has less space for the pieces and not much room to maneuver. We have very simple play while Black has to proceed carefully. } 14. b4 $5 { [%cal Gc5b4,Ga3b4,Ga1a7,Gc1b2,Gb2g7][%csl Ra7,Rg7,Rg8]The most forcing move! White is moving fast and with urgency, which is how we roll in the Scotch Gambit! We do not care about undoubling Black's c-pawns. We want to activate our a1-Rook and put our Bishop on the monster diagonal. [--] The Shankland followers are already stumped. IM Nguyen covers this move in his course, he has done his research! Note that this position has been reached in only 2 games! } 14... cxb4 { Played in both games. Black undoubles their pawns. } 15. axb4 { [%cal Ga1a7,Ga1a3,Ga3g3,Gg3g8,Gc1b2,Gb2g7][%csl Ra7,Rg7,Rg8]} 15... Bf5 { [%cal Gf5b1,Ge7c8,Gc8d6]This move is suggested by IM Nguyen in his course, developing the Bishop and keeping the idea of Nc8-Nd6 in mind. Here he only covered } 16. Bb2 { [%cal Gb2g7][%csl Gb2,Rg7]We bring our Bishop onto the powerful diagonal. } ( 16. Qd4 { , but we will deviate. } ) 16... Nc8 { Black tries to immediately regroup the Knight to d6. } 17. Qd4 { [%cal Gb2g7,Gc4f7][%csl Rg7][%cal Gc8d6,Gd5d6]The White Queen and Bishop menacingly look to give mate! Black is now forced to play } 17... f6 { when White will play } 18. d6+ { with check and then take on c7. White will still be down a pawn, but Black will have new weaknesses, and the Knight on c8 would be blocking the coordination of Black's Rooks. Our Bishop on c4 cuts the light squares and our f1 Rook is ready to come into the game. White has very active and easy play. } * 

