1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 { An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Nxe4 { [%csl Ge4]The brave move. Black accepts the challenge but we have a surprise waiting for him! } 8. d5 { [%cal Gd5c6][%csl Rc6,Gd5]Kicking the Knight back and establishing a bone in the throat of Black's position. } 8... Nxd2 $5 { It is not the most played move but the mainline. Black seeks to trade pieces while having less space to relieve some pressure. After all Black is up a pawn, so the more pieces that they trade is favorable for them. We have a nasty surprise waiting for Black, though. Your opponent will likely be totally clueless here and have no idea what is waiting for them. Get ready to blow your opponent off the board! } 9. Bxd2 { [%csl Rc6,Gd2,Gd5]Simply recapturing. } 9... Bxd2+ { Continuing the exchanges. The critical position soon arrives! } 10. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge1a1,Ge1h1][%csl Rc6,Rc8,Gd2,Gd5]On the surface White is down a pawn. However, we are greatly ahead in development, the Black Bishop is still on c8 and White has a great d5-pawn which still cramps Black. Nevertheless, since Black has traded quite a few pieces, the space disadvantage is not as greatly felt. We can still use our lead in development and central space to stir up a great initiative against the Black King, though. } 10... Ne7 11. h4 $3 { [%cal Gh4h7][%csl Re8,Gh4]The new idea in this position! Traditionally most players have played } ( 11. d6 { , which always fizzles out into a boring draw. The move } ) ( 11. h4 { is completely supported by the engine and gives us a very dynamic game where, if Black is not fully aware, they can lose very easily. [--] The move with the h-pawn signifies war! It shows our intentions very clearly that we are going after the Black King. This move should be made with vigor and strength - we are in our comfort zone and are coming out for the opponent. I am very sure our opponent will be completely shocked and likely has never seen this position in their life! [--] Remember our mindset here: we have the initiative and have to play fast and dynamic, and always pose questions to our opponent. Our advantage is not a static advantage, it requires us to always be proactive and put pressure to Black, in the great style of Garry Kasparov. } ) 11... O-O $6 { Only a madman would castle here, as Black walks into the attack. I would not expect this move from our opponent. } 12. h5 { [%cal Gh5h6,Gh1h7][%csl Rf8,Rg8,Gh5]The h-pawn is ready to go all the way to expose the Black King! } 12... h6 { Black stops the White pawn in its tracks. } 13. g4 $1 { [%csl Gg4,Rg8]A barbaric caveman move, but the best one! White directly goes after the Black King, as we can castle long and proceed with mating the Black King. } 13... d6 14. Rg1 { [%cal Gg1g8,Gg1g5,Gg4g5][%csl Rg7][%cal Ge1c1]With g5 coming next, Black should start praying. } * 

