ces that they trade is favorable for them. We have a nasty surprise waiting for Black, though. Your opponent will likely be totally clueless here and have no idea what is waiting for them. Get ready to blow your opponent off the board! } 9. Bxd2 { [%csl Rc6,Gd2,Gd5]Simply recapturing. } 9... Bxd2+ { Continuing the exchanges. The critical position soon arrives! } 10. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge1a1,Ge1h1][%csl Rc6,Rc8,Gd2,Gd5]On the surface White is down a pawn. However, we are greatly ahead in development, the Black Bishop is still on c8 and White has a great d5-pawn which still cramps Black. Nevertheless, since Black has traded quite a few pieces, the space disadvantage is not as greatly felt. We can still use our lead in development and central space to stir up a great initiative against the Black King, though. } 10... Ne7 11. h4 $3 { [%cal Gh4h7][%csl Re8,Gh4]The new idea in this position! Traditionally most players have played } ( 11. d6 { , which always fizzles out into a boring draw. The move } ) ( 11. h4 { is completely supported by the engine and gives us a very dynamic game where, if Black is not fully aware, they can lose very easily. [--] The move with the h-pawn signifies war! It shows our intentions very clearly that we are going after the Black King. This move should be made with vigor and strength - we are in our comfort zone and are coming out for the opponent. I am very sure our opponent will be completely shocked and likely has never seen this position in their life! [--] Remember our mindset here: we have the initiative and have to play fast and dynamic, and always pose questions to our opponent. Our advantage is not a static advantage, it requires us to always be proactive and put pressure to Black, in the great style of Garry Kasparov. } ) 11... d6 { [%cal Gc8h3][%csl Gd6]The most natural and obvious reply. Black opens the scope of their Bishop and keeps an eye on the g4-square. } 12. h5 $1 { [%csl Rg7,Gh5]We are ready to advance the h-pawn and destroy the Black King's cover. Black must be very careful now. } 12... h6 { The most logical move. Black stops the h-pawn in its tracks. } 13. O-O-O $1 { White castles long. We show our aggressive caveman-like intentions. This is how chess should be played, and this line reminds me of the Romantic era of chess - of all the gambits where White would be very aggressive and go all in! However, this line has all of that and is at the same time engine approved! } 13... O-O 14. Rdg1 { [%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5]A self-explanatory move. White is ready to play g4 and go for mate. When was the last time that you got a position like this? Flip the board for one second and you will see how scary it is for Black! } 14... b5 $5 { [%csl Gb5,Rc4]Played by GM Nakamura against GM Caruana. Black tries to open up the Queenside immediately and get counterplay. } 15. Bb3 $5 { [%cal Gg2g4]A smart move, keeping the Queenside closed. } 15... Bg4 { [%csl Rf3,Rg2,Gg4]Black physically stops g4, but White is not deterred! } 16. Nh4 $1 { [%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4][%csl Rg4]White is ready to push the pawns forward with f3 next to kick the Bishop! } 16... c5 $2 { A blunder, played by GM Nakamura. Now let us see how we take down a 2700 world class Grandmaster! } 17. f3 { [%csl Gf3,Rg4]Kicking away the uninvited guest! } 17... Bxh5 18. g4 { [%csl Gg4,Rh5]We get through with brute force! } 18... Bg6 19. Nf5 $18 { [%csl Re7,Rh6,Rg7][%cal Gg1g7,Gh1h6]Caruana 2792 vs Nakamura 2736, 2022. Grandmaster Caruana made easy work of Grandmaster Nakamura here in this winning position. } * 

