1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]The traditional Scotch gambit! This gambit goes all the way back in time. For some reason unknown to me, it went out of fashion for a very long time, but I think it is time to bring it back! [--] The traditional Scotch gambit is just what we need: it's very dynamic, aggressive, cuts to the point, and goes for the full point. The engine has found many ways for Black to 'equalize', but I have found many ways to pose problems to Black, for instance with a very creative novelty that we will see in one of the mainlines. [--] Let us bring back the Romantic era of chess. No more boring slow Italians or Ruy Lopez, but let us play fighting chess! You have a very aggressive, swashbuckler's repertoire in front of you that is also backed by the strongest engines! Be ready for a journey and get ready to unlock your inner dragon, bringing out the fire on the board! } 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]Posing a very crucial question to Black. Now } 5... Ne4 { A very modern move! We must be well aware of this possibility and can expect this move from younger players who work with engines. However, we still will pose Black a great challenge! } ( 5... d5 { has always been the most popular move, while } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { has risen greatly in popularity in recent years and is a very solid try to equalize. I believe that it is even stronger than the traditional } ) ( 5... d5 ) 6. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2e4][%csl Ge2,Re4]Immediately challenging the e4-Knight! } 6... Nc5 7. c3 $5 { [%cal Gc3d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4]A typical move in Scotch gambit style! White is ready to give a pawn to speed up the development, and Black has to be very careful! } 7... Ne6 $6 { [%cal Ge6d4,Gc6d4][%csl Rd4]Black firmly holds onto the pawn. This suspicious move has been played 2 times by 2700 Grandmaster Andrey Esipenko. } 8. cxd4 { Clarifying the situation in the center. } 8... Nexd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qe4 $1 { [%cal Ge4d4][%csl Rd4,Ge4]Centralizing the Queen and forcing the Knight back! } 10... Ne6 { The Knight looks very solid and stable on e6. } 11. O-O $14 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf1d1,Gb1c3,Gc4e6,Gd7d6][%csl Re6]A very logical and called for move. We are ready to develop next with moves such as Nc3 and get our attack going. In some cases we can consider rolling over Black by moving our f-pawn forward. If Black plays } 11... d6 { , the move } 12. Rd1 { is very strong, creating a pin. } * 

