1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]The traditional Scotch gambit! This gambit goes all the way back in time. For some reason unknown to me, it went out of fashion for a very long time, but I think it is time to bring it back! [--] The traditional Scotch gambit is just what we need: it's very dynamic, aggressive, cuts to the point, and goes for the full point. The engine has found many ways for Black to 'equalize', but I have found many ways to pose problems to Black, for instance with a very creative novelty that we will see in one of the mainlines. [--] Let us bring back the Romantic era of chess. No more boring slow Italians or Ruy Lopez, but let us play fighting chess! You have a very aggressive, swashbuckler's repertoire in front of you that is also backed by the strongest engines! Be ready for a journey and get ready to unlock your inner dragon, bringing out the fire on the board! } 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]Posing a very crucial question to Black. Now } 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5,Ge5,Rf6]This has been the mainline for a very long time. Black strikes back in the center, gaining a tempo on our Bishop! } ( 5... d5 { has always been the most popular move, while } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { has risen greatly in popularity in recent years and is a very solid try to equalize. I believe that it is even stronger than the traditional } ) ( 5... d5 ) 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8][%csl Gb5,Rc6]On b5 the Bishop exerts great pressure on the c6-Knight, which is defending the Black d4-pawn and keeping an eye on e5. In most cases, we will later eliminate this Knight. } 6... Nd7 $5 { [%cal Gb5c6,Gb7c6,Gd7e5,Gc6e5,Gc6d4,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Re8]A very interesting move! Black is preventing us from immediately taking on d4 and claims that their Kingside Knight is much better on d7 rather than e4, where it can become exposed at times. Black is inviting us to take the c6-Knight after which they will accept doubled pawns, which can be used as a dynamic asset. [--] The older classical players most likely won't know this move - I would expect this move from the younger generation of players, as they believe that they are surprising us with this move. However, lucky for you, International Master Alan-Safar Ramoutar is a seasoned openings veteran and leaves no stone left unturned... } 7. O-O $1 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Rd4,Ge5]Development is key in the Scotch! Always remember the principles of the Scotch gambit: development, active play, not being afraid to give some material for the initiative and going for the kill! } 7... Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8]Black hurries to finish development and castle. They are waiting for us to take on c6. } 8. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gb1c3][%csl Gc3,Rd4]The most aggressive idea and my suggestion. I do not like the mainline with } ( 8. Bxc6 { as Black gets very good play and it is not clear for us in many variations. I have always found the arising positions very hard to play. Now } ) ( 8. c3 { This is a move in real Scotch gambit style, a rather thematic move. White sacrifices a pawn to speed up development and get the attack going quicker! } ) ( 8. c3 { is likely not expected by your opponent as it has only been played in 46 games according to my online database, compared to } ) ( 8. Bxc6 { which has seen 400+ games. So with } ) ( 8. c3 { we surprise our opponent! They are likely out of preparation already, while our preparation is just getting started! Get ready to blow Black off of the board. } ) 8... dxc3 { The only real way to challenge this gambit is to accept it! } 9. Nxc3 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5,Gf3]Our pieces spring into action. We are ready to topple the Black position, as we have strong pressure in the center. Black has to react carefully. } 9... Nb6 $5 { [%cal Gb6d5,Gc8h3,Gd1d5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5]A very logical move, which was played against me by Grandmaster David Berzces of Hungary. You see, I practice what I preach - this line has been played by me before! } 10. a4 $1 { [%cal Ga4a5][%csl Ga4,Rb6]We aim to kick the Knight from the b6-square. The Knight solidly defends the d5-pawn, and we cannot allow that! } 10... a6 $5 { [%cal Ga6b5][%csl Rb5]Black decides to go after our Bishop and accept any fate. } 11. Bxc6+ { [%csl Rc6]We take the Knight without question. } 11... bxc6 { Now we arrive at a position in which it is very important to understand the ideas. } 12. a5 { [%cal Ga5b6,Gc6c5,Gc8h3][%csl Ga5,Rb6,Rc6,Rc7,Rd5]First of all, we will kick the b6-Knight back, which was our intention in the first place. Black has doubled c-pawns and the Bishop pair. However, if we are not fast enough with our aggressive/active play, Black's pawns can start advancing and become great central assets! As per usual in the Scotch gambit, we play aggressively and keep up the initiative on every move! } 12... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5][%csl Re5]} 13. Nd4 $5 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gd7e5,Gc1f4,Gf2f8][%csl Rc6,Gd4,Re5,Gf4]A crucial move! Our f-pawn, which is a stalwart of the Scotch gambit, is now ready to start moving forward. White attacks the c6-pawn and is ready to immediately show an aggressive intent with the advance of the f-pawn. If Black takes } 13... Nb8 { [%cal Gb8c6,Gc8h3][%csl Rc6]A sad move to make, but the only reasonable way to defend c6! } ( 13... Nxe5 $146 { , we simply have } 14. Bf4 { and the Black position is falling apart. } ) 14. f4 { [%csl Gf4]Another soldier is activated! We are ready to push through with f5 next. } 14... c5 $1 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Gc5,Rd4,Gd5]Black rightfully gets their own pawns going! f5 was on the agenda for White, so Black now wisely counterattacks in the center. A famous saying in chess goes 'an attack on the wing is best met by a counter-attack in the center'. } 15. Nc2 { [%cal Gd1d5,Gf4f5][%csl Gc2,Gc3,Rd5]The Knight humbly retreats. We are still ready to go f5 while we keep an eye on the d5-pawn. } 15... d4 { [%csl Rc3,Rd4]Black gets the central mass rolling! They do not want to give White a chance to breathe. } 16. Qf3 $1 { [%cal Gf3a8][%csl Ra8,Rc5,Rd4]A very cunning in-between move! White develops the Queen with tempo, attacking the exposed Rook on a8. [--] The position gets very crazy from here on. Black still has not castled and is still far from finishing their development. White is ready to even sacrifice some material for the attack! } 16... c6 17. f5 $3 { [%cal Gf5f6][%csl Re7,Rf6,Rg7,Re8][%cal Gc1h6][%csl Ge5]A true Scotch gambit move!! The f-pawn showcases its power. In the Scotch, it is always about the initiative and dynamic play, and one very important factor is time. We simply do not have time to move our c3-Knight... Otherwise Black will consolidate. [--] Instead, we act quickly and with force! We are ready to break through with f6 at any moment. We give up the Knight to get at the Black King! Check out the 6...Nd7 chapter (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where we will study this position in more depth! } * 

