1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]The traditional Scotch gambit! This gambit goes all the way back in time. For some reason unknown to me, it went out of fashion for a very long time, but I think it is time to bring it back! [--] The traditional Scotch gambit is just what we need: it's very dynamic, aggressive, cuts to the point, and goes for the full point. The engine has found many ways for Black to 'equalize', but I have found many ways to pose problems to Black, for instance with a very creative novelty that we will see in one of the mainlines. [--] Let us bring back the Romantic era of chess. No more boring slow Italians or Ruy Lopez, but let us play fighting chess! You have a very aggressive, swashbuckler's repertoire in front of you that is also backed by the strongest engines! Be ready for a journey and get ready to unlock your inner dragon, bringing out the fire on the board! } 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]Posing a very crucial question to Black. Now } 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5,Ge5,Rf6]} ( 5... d5 { has always been the most popular move, while } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { has risen greatly in popularity in recent years and is a very solid try to equalize. I believe that it is even stronger than the traditional } ) ( 5... d5 ) 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8][%csl Gb5,Rc6]On b5 the Bishop exerts great pressure on the c6-Knight, which is defending the Black d4-pawn and keeping an eye on e5. In most cases, we will later eliminate this Knight. } 6... Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 { Black develops the light-squared Bishop and awaits White's decision. } 8. Bxc6 { The traditional Scotch gambit move! White gives up the light-squared Bishop in order to double Black's pawns and to speed up our own development. The Black Knight on c6 was also targeting the e5-pawn, so it we were obligated to eliminate it. } 8... bxc6 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Gd4,Rd5,Ge1,Ge5]Black's c-pawns are now doubled. However, do not be fooled! If these pawns can get mobile and Black stabilizes their position, these pawns can wreak havoc in White's position. In the Scotch gambit, the aim is very clear: White either fights against the doubled c-pawns or tries to give mate. } 9. O-O { In Scotch gambit style, White finishes development and prepares for the attack! Now } 9... Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1,Ge4f2,Ge8g8,Gd8e7,Ge7e5,Gf7f6][%csl Gc5,Re5]Now we will consider the mainline of } ( 9... Bc5 { is clearly the mainline and the most-played move by Black. However, we should also be aware of } ) ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . } ) ( 9... c5 { is not so great, but } ) ( 9... Be7 { is a very solid move which, however, requires great precision from Black. } ) ( 9... Bc5 { With this move, Black brings out the dark-squared Bishop to its most active square. Black is ready to castle and can then put pressure on the e5-pawn. A lot of fun is ahead! } ) 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Re4]A traditional Scotch gambit move! We chase Black's Knight from the center and are ready to gain a tempo, bringing our f-pawn into the attack. } 10... Ng5 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Ge5,Gf4,Rg5]The most concrete move, attacking the Knight again and supporting our center. } 11... Ne4 { Black's main option. The Knight goes back to the square it came from in the center. } 12. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb1d2][%csl Gd4,Ge3]This is the traditional Scotch gambit move. White develops the Bishop to e3 before bringing the Knight out to d2. In most cases White wants to play Nd2 next, trying to trade our undeveloped Knight for Black's strong central e4-Knight. } 12... Bb6 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd5d4][%csl Gb6,Re3]This is the most played move in the position, but that does not mean that it is the best move! Black wishes to advance ...c5 immediately and let the central pawn mass trample over White! } 13. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Development! Staying true to the principles of the Scotch gambit! We are ready to combat Black's advances and seek to trade their strong Knight. } 13... Nxd2 { Black does not want us to destroy their pawn structure even further by allowing us to take on e4, so they willingly part with the strong central Knight. } 14. Qxd2 { [%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge3]We recapture with the Queen, finishing our development. Now we are ready to proceed with some action. } 14... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]Black kicks us back and gets the central pawn mass going. This position has been reached in a large number of games. } 15. Nf3 { [%cal Gd2d5,Gf3g5,Gf3e5,Ga1d1,Ga2a4][%csl Rb6,Rd5,Gf3]The Knight comes to f3 where it has prospects in the center as well as the Kingside. } 15... d4 { [%cal Gd4e3][%csl Rb6,Rc4,Gd4,Re3]Black kicks back our pieces, but they must beware as they are creating many weaknesses in their own position! } 16. Bf2 { [%csl Rb6,Ge5,Gf2,Gf4]First of all, I want to draw your attention to Black's Bishop on b6! Just look at it... It is like a pawn - it has no function now other than defending the c5-pawn. We will try to keep this Bishop out of the game, after which we will have an extra piece in the attack. } 16... Bc6 { [%cal Gc6f3][%csl Rb6,Rf3]Black puts the other Bishop on the long diagonal. This position has been reached in many games, but the computer strongly supports us: it gives White an advantage with many different moves here. This is because Black has a 'pawn' on b6, which is a great problem for them. } 17. Bh4 { [%cal Gh4d8][%csl Rd8,Gh4]Again we improve our Bishop to h4 and chase Black's Queen away! It is very important that our Bishop prevents the Black King from escaping to the Queenside! } 17... Qd7 { [%cal Gd7f5][%csl Rf5]Black takes control of the f5-square, not allowing White to advance the f-pawn. } 18. b3 $5 { [%cal Gb3c4][%csl Gb3,Rb6,Rc4]An important idea! White plays against Black's b6-Bishop by not allowing it to be freed with the ...c4 advance! We are trying to keep this Bishop out of the game for as long as we can. } 18... O-O { Black finally completes development by getting their King to 'safety'. } 19. a4 { [%cal Ga4a5][%csl Ga4,Rb6]We threaten to trap Black's Bishop while taking space on the Queenside. } 19... a5 { [%csl Ra5,Rb6,Rc5,Rc7,Rd4]The b6-Bishop is beginning to look more and more like a pawn! } 20. Qd3 $14 { [%csl Rb6,Rh7,Rg8,Ge4,Gc4][%cal Gf3d2,Gd2e4,Gd2c4,Ga1e1][%csl Ge1][%cal Gf4f5,Gh4g3,Gd3h7,Gd3c4,Gd3e4]White improves the Queen, keeping control over the c4-square while also supporting the f5-move and aiming at Black's King. Black has a very sad position. Their Bishop on b6 is totally out of the game while all of our pieces are working together. We have easy play with Rae1 coming next and then Nd2 (trying to transfer the Knight to c4 or e4). } * 

