1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]The traditional Scotch gambit! This gambit goes all the way back in time. For some reason unknown to me, it went out of fashion for a very long time, but I think it is time to bring it back! [--] The traditional Scotch gambit is just what we need: it's very dynamic, aggressive, cuts to the point, and goes for the full point. The engine has found many ways for Black to 'equalize', but I have found many ways to pose problems to Black, for instance with a very creative novelty that we will see in one of the mainlines. [--] Let us bring back the Romantic era of chess. No more boring slow Italians or Ruy Lopez, but let us play fighting chess! You have a very aggressive, swashbuckler's repertoire in front of you that is also backed by the strongest engines! Be ready for a journey and get ready to unlock your inner dragon, bringing out the fire on the board! } 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]Posing a very crucial question to Black. Now } 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5,Ge5,Rf6]} ( 5... d5 { has always been the most popular move, while } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { has risen greatly in popularity in recent years and is a very solid try to equalize. I believe that it is even stronger than the traditional } ) ( 5... d5 ) 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8][%csl Gb5,Rc6]On b5 the Bishop exerts great pressure on the c6-Knight, which is defending the Black d4-pawn and keeping an eye on e5. In most cases, we will later eliminate this Knight. } 6... Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 { Black develops the light-squared Bishop and awaits White's decision. } 8. Bxc6 { The traditional Scotch gambit move! White gives up the light-squared Bishop in order to double Black's pawns and to speed up our own development. The Black Knight on c6 was also targeting the e5-pawn, so it we were obligated to eliminate it. } 8... bxc6 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Gd4,Rd5,Ge1,Ge5]Black's c-pawns are now doubled. However, do not be fooled! If these pawns can get mobile and Black stabilizes their position, these pawns can wreak havoc in White's position. In the Scotch gambit, the aim is very clear: White either fights against the doubled c-pawns or tries to give mate. } 9. O-O { In Scotch gambit style, White finishes development and prepares for the attack! Now } 9... Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1,Ge4f2,Ge8g8,Gd8e7,Ge7e5,Gf7f6][%csl Gc5,Re5]Now we will consider the mainline of } ( 9... Bc5 { is clearly the mainline and the most-played move by Black. However, we should also be aware of } ) ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . } ) ( 9... c5 { is not so great, but } ) ( 9... Be7 { is a very solid move which, however, requires great precision from Black. } ) ( 9... Bc5 { With this move, Black brings out the dark-squared Bishop to its most active square. Black is ready to castle and can then put pressure on the e5-pawn. A lot of fun is ahead! } ) 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Re4]A traditional Scotch gambit move! We chase Black's Knight from the center and are ready to gain a tempo, bringing our f-pawn into the attack. } 10... Ng5 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Ge5,Gf4,Rg5]The most concrete move, attacking the Knight again and supporting our center. } 11... Ne4 { Black's main option. The Knight goes back to the square it came from in the center. } 12. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb1d2][%csl Gd4,Ge3]This is the traditional Scotch gambit move. White develops the Bishop to e3 before bringing the Knight out to d2. In most cases White wants to play Nd2 next, trying to trade our undeveloped Knight for Black's strong central e4-Knight. } 12... Qb8 $1 { [%cal Gb8b2][%csl Rb2]This move is considered the modern mainline and the 'refutation' of the Scotch gambit, and is clearly the best according to the computer. White has been unable to find a valid way to pose problems here - until now! Your saviour is here! [--] I have found a very rare move which is strongly backed by the engine which gives us the winning chances that we need. I have already crushed a strong International Master in a classical tournament with this idea, and now I am ready to pass on my secret knowledge! With } ( 12... Qb8 { Black attacks our b2-pawn and forces us to either weaken with } 13. b3 { or to sacrifice the pawn with } ( 13. Nc3 $146 { . Black's Queen is activated in a very curious way on the Queenside. } ) ) 13. Qd3 $5 { [%cal Gd3e4,Gb8b2][%csl Rb2,Gd3]This is one of the biggest moves of the course!! It has been played in only 4 games out of a few hundred games with 12...Qb8, one of the crucial games in this variation being my own! } ( 13. Qd3 { is a very mysterious move, as moving the Queen to d3 is not a move that comes to anyone's human mind I would argue! The main idea of the move is that we want to bring our Knight to d2 and force Black's e4-Knight to evacuate. [--] If we would start with } ) ( 13. Nd2 $146 { or } ) ( 13. Nc3 $146 { , Black takes } 13... Qxb2 { and we wouldn't have any reasonable way to increase the pressure on the e4-Knight. This Knight is the pride of Black's position and we are ready to give up the b2-pawn and continue with Nd2 next to get rid of it. } ) 13... Qxb2 { [%cal Gb2a1][%csl Ra1,Gb2]Why should Black not take the pawn? After all, that was the whole point behind the ...Qb8 maneuver. } 14. Nd2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Development! White is now ready to get rid of the strong e4-Knight. Black is yet to castle and their Queen is in an awkward position. } 14... Nxd2 { This has been played in all games so far, even against me by the strong International Master who I crushed with ease. } 15. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gf4f5][%csl Rb2,Rc5,Gd2,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4]We arrive at a very interesting position! White is down a pawn but Black's Queen is awkwardly placed and could easily be trapped if Black is not careful. Meanwhile, White can still carry out an assault on the Kingside with the move f5, which is a default move in the Scotch gambit. I would take White any day here. Black has only one plan... To survive! Whereas our goal is very clear: we try to harass Black's Queen and storm the Kingside! [--] There have been only 3 tournament games in this position, from which White has scored 2.5/3. In the game where Black made a draw, he actually had a losing position from the opening. This speaks volumes for the line. I was the real hero in this variation, as my game is a model game and it paved the way for this Scotch gambit line to be revived. } 15... Bb4 $6 { [%cal Gb4d2,Gc6c5][%csl Rd2]A strange move, but one that was played by IM N.Salimova against young Grandmaster Maurizzi from France. Black clears the way for the c-pawn to advance. } 16. Qf2 { [%cal Gf2c5,Gf2g3,Gg3g7][%csl Re8,Gg3,Rg7]We get out of the way of Bishop's attack, to the very nice square of f2, and possibly hint at coming to the Kingside! } 16... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]Black follows up with their plan! } 17. Nb3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb3c5][%csl Gb3,Rc5,Ge3,Gf2]Exerting great pressure on the c5-pawn. Now the Black Queen is feeling very short of squares. } 17... Bf5 { [%cal Gf5c2,Gf2c5,Gb3c5,Gb2c3][%csl Rc2,Rc5]This was how IM Salimova played against GM Maurizzi. Already White has a great advantage of over +1 in computer terms. However, we are much stronger than the computer, as we are powerful human beings with souls, hearts, spirits and brains unlike any other. We cannot trust these deceitful machines! [--] With 17...Bf5 Black is putting pressure on c2, but we have a very strong reply in store! } 18. a3 $3 { [%csl Ga3,Rb4]This move was missed by GM Maurizzi. However, if you have bought this course, you will most certainly not miss it! We pose a very crucial question to Black's Bishop which does not have many squares to go to! Also, our pawn on a3 is very much poisoned! } 18... Bxa3 19. Bc1 $3 { [%cal Gc1a3][%csl Ra3,Rb2][%cal Gb3a1,Ga1a3]With this backwards move we now win the Bishop and the game! } * 

