{ There are always those lazy opponents that we have to face that have no energy or time to study theory and will deviate with some stupid sideline. This chapter is dedicated to dealing with those guys. While these early sidelines are not critical in any way, shape or form, it is always good to have some knowledge on how to deal with them! } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { [%csl Gd4,Re5]The traditional Scotch Gambit move! White wages immediate war in the center. This opening is not for those that suffer from low blood pressure. } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7,Ge1g1][%csl Gc4,Ge1,Re8,Rf7]Development development! As we will learn in the Scotch gambit, development is a crucial theme. White is ready to castle as quickly as possible and is then ready to go after the Black King! } 4... Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1][%csl Gb4,Re1]A very greedy and computerish move. Black immediately wants to consolidate the extra pawn. They will be punished for their greed! } 5. c3 $1 { [%csl Gc3,Rd4]Here you go, Sir! We give you what you wanted, are you happy now? In the Scotch gambit development is key, even if that means giving up a pawn or two. } 5... dxc3 { [%csl Gc3]} 6. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7][%csl Gc4,Re8,Gg1]We have completed development while the Black King is still stuck in the center. } 6... d6 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gd6e5,Gc8h3][%csl Gc4,Rf7]The most played move. This is a logical move: Black takes control over e5 and opens up the c8-Bishop. } 7. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3f7][%csl Gb3,Gc4,Rf7]We do not give Black any space to breathe! } 7... Be6 { [%cal Ge6b3][%csl Rb3,Rc4,Re6]A desperate attempt to equalize. Black tries to get rid of our strong Bishop, even if it costs them a pawn. } 8. Bxe6 { We fear no ghosts! } 8... fxe6 9. bxc3 $40 { [%cal Gf3g5,Gf3d4,Gb3e6,Gb4b7][%csl Gb3,Rb4,Re6,Re8,Gf3]A very unusual occurrence in the Scotch gambit: we take the time to recapture a pawn. But notice that we recapture with tempo - we are attacking Black's Bishop! After the Bishop retreats, we can consider bringing our Knight to g5 to add great pressure on e6. The fight continues! } * 

