[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3e5][%csl Re5]On the second move we already create a threat to win a pawn. In this Scotch gambit repertoire, you will see that with almost every move we create threats for the opponent! } 2... Nc6 { The main move. Black defends the pawn. } 3. d4 { [%cal Gf1b5,Gd4e5][%csl Re5][%cal Gc1g5]Striking in the center and opening our two Bishops. We have a surprise coming for Black! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7][%csl Rf7]Ignoring the pawn and finishing our rapid development. The Scotch gambit begins! } 4... Bc5 { [%cal Gc6d4,Gc5d4]A very natural move and one of Black's main tries. Black develops the Bishop and defends their extra pawn. } 5. c3 { [%cal Gc3d4,Gd4c3,Gd1d5][%csl Rf7,Rc5][%cal Gc4f7,Gd5c5,Ge8f7]A key move! Black is unable to take the pawn due to the tactic } 5... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]Black counterattacks our center and tries to quickly finish development. This is the only serious move for Black. } ( 5... dxc3 6. Bxf7+ { followed by Qd5. Now we are ready to recapture on d4 and maintain a strong pawn center. } ) 6. cxd4 $5 { [%csl Gd4,Rc5]An old move that goes back ages! This line used to bring all kinds of fun gambits into the position, but ever since modern theory and computers had their say, people stopped playing this variation... Until now! I have prepared a surprise for your opponent which is backed up by the computer. It will be very likely that you opponent will be out of book. They will feel uncomfortable and we will crush them in great attacking style! } 6... Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1][%csl Re1,Re4]Again the only move. Black gives a check while our pawn on e4 is still hanging. } 7. Nbd2 $5 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Re4]The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! In this chapter, we will look at the move } 7... d5 { [%csl Gc4,Rd5,Ge4]Black is too cowardly to accept the pawn! This move indicates that our opponent has been shocked by our opening choice and is simply looking for a solid and risk-free game. They are in for a great surprise, as we will take the fight to them! } ( 7... d5 { , which is a very natural move that unprepared and cowardly opponents can play! } ) ( 7... d5 { is a very logical move by its nature. I would expect this move by the most unprepared opponents, and it should be studied very carefully. } ) 8. exd5 { We accept the isolated pawn with no regrets! } 8... Nxd5 9. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8,Gc6d4][%csl Rb4,Gc4,Gd4,Rd5,Re8]A move that requires no explanation. White gets the King out of the center and is ready to become active. } 9... O-O { [%cal Gf3e5,Gd2e4,Gc4d5,Gh2h3,Gc8g4][%csl Gc5,Rc6,Gd4,Rd5,Ge5,Rg4]Black follows. We now have a critical position on the board. It is very important for us to understand this position before trying to memorize any moves. [--] White has an isolated d-pawn which is a static weakness but also a dynamic strength. This pawn gives our pieces outposts on c5 and e5 and greatly helps in the central fight. [--] White also has a very strong Bishop on c4 and meanwhile, the Knights can think about coming to e4 or e5. The Black Knight on c6 is actually a bit misplaced - they would prefer to have the c-pawn there. [--] This position requires dynamic and quick play. If we give Black time to consolidate all of their forces, we would lose our advantage. We must keep up the initiative and pressure on Black's position. Always try to play actively in these types of positions. } 10. a3 $1 { [%csl Rb4]Immediately questioning the Bishop! Will Black give up the Bishop pair or not!? This move is very useful as we can also expand with b4 in the future, putting pressure on the Queenside. } 10... Be7 $5 { A very logical move. Black keeps the Bishop pair. We can expect our opponent to play like this. } 11. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e7][%csl Re7]Because of the isolated pawn we have open e- and c-files, so we better use them! } 11... Bg4 { [%cal Gg4d1,Gc6d4][%csl Rd1]} 12. h3 { [%cal Gh3g4,Gg4f3,Gd2f3,Gc1h6][%csl Rg4]The Bishop is an uninvited guest. We immediately ask it to leave! } 12... Bh5 13. Ba2 $14 { [%cal Gd1b3,Gd5b6,Gd4d5][%csl Gb3,Gb6,Rb7,Rd5]A very important prophylactic move. We avoid ...Nb6 and now we have a huge threat of Qb3, attacking Black's b7-pawn and d5 Knight! [--] There are many other ideas in this position if Qb3 does not work. For example, we have ideas such as g4 to kick the Bishop and then improve our Knight to e4. We have the simple Nf1 to open our c1-Bishop and think of Ne3 or Ng3 in the near future. It is a very rich position, and you should always be on high alert and compare different ideas! } 13... Nb6 14. g4 $1 { [%csl Gg4,Rh5]Because we are so active, we are not afraid to weaken our Kingside aggressively. In any case Black has no pieces near our King. } 14... Bg6 15. Ne4 $14 { [%cal Ga2g8,Gd4d5,Gc1f4,Gf3e5][%csl Gc5,Ge4,Ge5,Gf3]With Ideas such as Bf4 or d5 to come, White has a much more active game. Just look at our pieces and compare them to the Black ones. } * 

