 } ) ( 7... d5 { is a very logical move by its nature. I would expect this move by the most unprepared opponents, and it should be studied very carefully. } ) 8. exd5 { We accept the isolated pawn with no regrets! } 8... Nxd5 9. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7,Gf1e1,Ge1e8,Gc6d4][%csl Rb4,Gc4,Gd4,Rd5,Re8]A move that requires no explanation. White gets the King out of the center and is ready to become active. } 9... O-O { [%cal Gf3e5,Gd2e4,Gc4d5,Gh2h3,Gc8g4][%csl Gc5,Rc6,Gd4,Rd5,Ge5,Rg4]Black follows. We now have a critical position on the board. It is very important for us to understand this position before trying to memorize any moves. [--] White has an isolated d-pawn which is a static weakness but also a dynamic strength. This pawn gives our pieces outposts on c5 and e5 and greatly helps in the central fight. [--] White also has a very strong Bishop on c4 and meanwhile, the Knights can think about coming to e4 or e5. The Black Knight on c6 is actually a bit misplaced - they would prefer to have the c-pawn there. [--] This position requires dynamic and quick play. If we give Black time to consolidate all of their forces, we would lose our advantage. We must keep up the initiative and pressure on Black's position. Always try to play actively in these types of positions. } 10. a3 $1 { [%csl Rb4]Immediately questioning the Bishop! Will Black give up the Bishop pair or not!? This move is very useful as we can also expand with b4 in the future, putting pressure on the Queenside. } 10... Ba5 $6 11. Ne4 { [%cal Ge4c5,Gc1g5,Gb2b4][%csl Ra5,Gc5]After Black's dubious move, White now opens the c1-Bishop and eyes the c5-outpost. Black's Bishop on a5 is shooting into air. White can consider b4 or Bg5 on the next move, depending on Black's reply. } 11... Bg4 12. Nc5 $14 { [%cal Gc5b7,Gh2h3,Gd1f3,Gc4d5][%csl Rb7,Gc5,Rd5,Rg4]Occupying the c5-outpost and attacking the b7-pawn with tempo. Black is under pressure with moves such as h3 coming next. } * 

