ment Black has no pieces near the White King, so White has nothing to worry about. } 13... Bg6 14. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e8]Taking the open file. As we know already, the isolated pawn gives us the open c- and e-files! } 14... Qd6 $1 { Connecting the Rooks and keeping an eye on the f4-square that was weakened by g4. } 15. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3d5][%csl Gb3,Rb7,Gc4,Rd5]Developing with a double attack! } 15... Rad8 { [%cal Gb3b7,Gd8b8]Black brings the Rook into the game, defending the blockading Knight. } 16. Rac1 $14 { [%cal Gc1c6,Ge1e8]As we already know, the isolated pawn has given us the c- and e-files, so we take the remaining c-file! } 16... Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4][%csl Rc4]Again directly attacking the Bishop and the d4 pawn. } 17. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5c6,Gc1c6][%csl Rc6]A very interesting position with opposite-colored Bishops occurs now where White has the better pawn structure but must be on alert with the King. } 17... Nxd4 $2 18. Nxd4 Qxd4 19. Bb4 $18 { [%cal Gb4f8,Ge1e8,Gb5e8][%csl Rf8]Black again loses the exchange. } * 

