1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4g8,Ge1g1][%csl Rf7]} 4... Bc5 5. c3 { [%csl Gc3,Rd4]} 5... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]} 6. cxd4 Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl Ge1,Re4]} 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Bxd2+ $5 { [%csl Rd2]A move that seems weird, as Black willingly gives up the Bishop. However, things are more concrete. This is a serious line which we should be aware of. Unless they specifically prepared it, though, I do not expect your opponent to know this move. } ( 7... Bxd2+ { is the third most popular move, with } ) ( 7... d5 { being second and } ) ( 7... Nxe4 $146 { the main move. } ) 8. Bxd2 d5 $6 { [%csl Gc4,Rd5,Ge4]This is the usual cowardly move. Black still shies away from grabbing the pawn. } 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3f7,Gd2a5,Gc6a5][%csl Ra5,Rd5,Rf7]White immediately brings out the Queen to put pressure on the Black position. We have already seen in the previous chapter the advantages that the isolated pawn brings - we have more space, more freedom for our pieces and we carry the initiative. } 10... Nce7 { [%cal Ge7d5,Gd8d5][%csl Gd5]} 11. O-O $14 { [%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e8,Gh2h3,Gc8g4,Gb3b7][%csl Rb7,Rg4]} * 

