h3 $44 { [%cal Gc8g4,Gd1d2,Gd2d4,Gc4b3,Ga1c1,Rc7c6,Gd5c6,Gb7c6,Ga1d1][%csl Rg4]White takes away the g4-square from the Bishop and is ready to continue the game. We have no direct attack but great positional compensation: we have more space and very powerful Bishops, while Black's pieces have a hard time breathing. [--] There are very few games in this rare position but I encourage you to analyze this position further. White next intends to play either Qd2 or Qd4, bringing the Rook to the c-file is always a useful move, and prophylactic moves like Bb3 can also always be considered. [--] Eventually Black will break into the center with ...c6/...c5 when White will usually take on c6 and then pressure the d6-pawn and encourage Black to advance this pawn. After this, the d4 and c5-squares will be weakened and White will obtain many targets of attack. } * 

