1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4g8,Ge1g1][%csl Rf7]} 4... Bc5 5. c3 { [%csl Gc3,Rd4]} 5... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]} 6. cxd4 Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl Ge1,Re4]} 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Bxd2+ $5 { [%csl Rd2]A move that seems weird, as Black willingly gives up the Bishop. However, things are more concrete. This is a serious line which we should be aware of. Unless they specifically prepared it, though, I do not expect your opponent to know this move. } ( 7... Bxd2+ { is the third most popular move, with } ) ( 7... d5 { being second and } ) ( 7... Nxe4 $146 { the main move. } ) 8. Bxd2 Nxe4 { [%csl Re4]Black bites the bullet and accepts the 'free' pawn. } 9. d5 { [%csl Rc6,Gd5]Putting a bone in the throat of Black's position. The d5-pawn will cramp Black! } 9... Ne7 10. Bb4 $1 { [%cal Gb4e7][%csl Gb4,Re7]Not giving Black the chance to grab our Bishop anymore! The Knight on e4 will soon come under fire. It is not welcome on our side of the board. } 10... d6 { [%cal Gd6b4][%csl Rb4,Gd6]A smart move, immediately blunting our Bishop. } 11. O-O { [%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7,Gf1e1,Gd5c6,Gd5e6][%csl Rc7,Gd5]White finishes development and it is essential to understand this position. First, White is down a pawn so Black has a material advantage. White has no direct attack against the Black King; the compensation is in a much more positional form. White has the open c-file to pressure Black, and the e-file can be used as well. Because of the d5-pawn, Black is feeling very cramped. White also has the Bishop pair which could become a great asset when the position is opened. } 11... O-O 12. Re1 $1 { [%cal Ge1e7][%csl Re4,Re7]White immediately questions the Black Knight and forces a decision! } 12... f5 $6 { [%csl Re6]} 13. Nd4 $14 { [%cal Gd4e6,Gb4a3,Gb2b3,Ga3b2,Ga1c1,Gc1c7][%csl Rc7,Re6]The e6-square is greatly weakened. One very important idea to remember with White here is Ba3 with the idea to play b3-Bb2 to reposition the Bishop onto a better diagonal. } * 

