1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4g8,Ge1g1][%csl Rf7]} 4... Bc5 5. c3 { [%csl Gc3,Rd4]} 5... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]} 6. cxd4 Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl Ge1,Re4]} 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Bxd2+ $5 { [%csl Rd2]A move that seems weird, as Black willingly gives up the Bishop. However, things are more concrete. This is a serious line which we should be aware of. Unless they specifically prepared it, though, I do not expect your opponent to know this move. } ( 7... Bxd2+ { is the third most popular move, with } ) ( 7... d5 { being second and } ) ( 7... Nxe4 $146 { the main move. } ) 8. Bxd2 Nxe4 { [%csl Re4]Black bites the bullet and accepts the 'free' pawn. } 9. d5 { [%csl Rc6,Gd5]Putting a bone in the throat of Black's position. The d5-pawn will cramp Black! } 9... Ne7 10. Bb4 $1 { [%cal Gb4e7][%csl Gb4,Re7]Not giving Black the chance to grab our Bishop anymore! The Knight on e4 will soon come under fire. It is not welcome on our side of the board. } 10... d6 { [%cal Gd6b4][%csl Rb4,Gd6]A smart move, immediately blunting our Bishop. } 11. O-O { [%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7,Gf1e1,Gd5c6,Gd5e6][%csl Rc7,Gd5]White finishes development and it is essential to understand this position. First, White is down a pawn so Black has a material advantage. White has no direct attack against the Black King; the compensation is in a much more positional form. White has the open c-file to pressure Black, and the e-file can be used as well. Because of the d5-pawn, Black is feeling very cramped. White also has the Bishop pair which could become a great asset when the position is opened. } 11... O-O 12. Re1 $1 { [%cal Ge1e7][%csl Re4,Re7]White immediately questions the Black Knight and forces a decision! } 12... Nc5 { [%csl Gc5]The best square for the Knight. It stands very well on c5, supported firmly by the d6-pawn. } 13. Qd2 $13 { [%cal Gd2a5,Gc8g4,Gg4d1][%csl Ra5,Rg4]A very smart move, stopping ...a5 and also getting out of the Bg4 pin. It is hard to analyze everything in this position, but general guidelines and plans should be very helpful. [--] We already know that White has great compensation. We will try to use the c- and e-files to put pressure on the Black position. Moves such as h3 (to restrict Black's Bishop from g4), Rac1, and Bc3 (bringing the Bishop onto a better diagonal) can always be considered. [--] A very complex fight lies ahead. There was a very high-level game, between GM Gadir Guseinov vs GM Jonas Bjerre in this position, in which Guseinov obtained an advantage in the FIDE World Cup 2023. } 13... c6 $6 { Played by GM Bjerre. } 14. dxc6 { [%cal Gd2d8][%csl Rd8]} 14... Nxc6 { This position was reached in the game GM Guseinov vs GM Bjerre. } ( 14... bxc6 $2 15. Bxc5 { Black loses a piece. } 15... dxc5 16. Qxd8 { and the e7-Knight is hanging at the end. } ) 15. Ba3 $14 { [%cal Ga3d6,Gd2d6,Gc4f7][%csl Rd6,Gf7]White maintains very strong pressure with the Bishop pair in an open position and pressure on the weak d6-pawn. } * 

