1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4g8,Ge1g1][%csl Rf7]} 4... Bc5 5. c3 { [%csl Gc3,Rd4]} 5... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]} 6. cxd4 Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl Ge1,Re4]} 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Nxe4 { [%cal Ge4d2,Gb4e1][%csl Rd2]The most popular move and the most correct move. Black was offered a pawn, takes an important central pawn and waits for White to prove the compensation! } 8. d5 $1 { [%csl Rc6]Again establishing a bone in the throat of Black's position and kicking away the Knight. } 8... Ne7 { Black retreats the Knight without making any exchanges. } 9. O-O { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Re4]} 9... Nxd2 { Black seeks to trade pieces to relieve some pressure. } 10. Nxd2 $1 { [%cal Gb4e1][%csl Gc1]We take back with the Knight in order not to allow Black to trade off the Bishop pair! } 10... O-O 11. a3 { [%cal Ga3b4][%csl Rb4]Going after the Bishop. We are like the hunter in the forest hunting our prey at every turn. } 11... Bxd2 { The most popular move in the position. After } ( 11... Bd6 $2 12. Ne4 $16 $146 { Black's position falls apart - } 12... Be5 { is answered by } 13. f4 ) 12. Bxd2 { [%cal Gf1e1,Ga1c1,Gc1c7,Ge1e3,Ge3g3,Gd2c3,Gc3g7][%csl Rc7,Rc8,Ge1,Rg7]We get a position similar to what we have already seen. White is down a pawn but has the Bishop pair, more space thanks to the pawn on d5, and long-lasting positional compensation. We will use the c- and e-files to pressure Black and keep taking more space. } 12... d6 13. Re1 { Taking the open e-file first. Rc1 was also possible. } 13... Ng6 14. Rc1 $44 { [%cal Gc1c7,Gc4f1,Gd1b3,Ge1e3][%csl Rb7,Rc7,Ge1]White is ready for the middlegame. We have many ideas such as Bf1 to open the scope of the Rook, Re3 to transfer the Rook across to the Kingside or to possibly double on the c-file, and even Qb3 in some cases to keep Black's Bishop tied to b7. A complex fight lies ahead. } * 

