1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Bc5 5. c3 Nf6 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 $5 { The gambit that I recommend in the course! Perhaps it is not the first time you see this move, but there will be a huge twist and new idea later in the mainline! } 7... Nxe4 { [%csl Ge4]The brave move. Black accepts the challenge but we have a surprise waiting for him! } 8. d5 { [%cal Gd5c6][%csl Rc6,Gd5]Kicking the Knight back and establishing a bone in the throat of Black's position. } 8... Nxd2 $5 { It is not the most played move but the mainline. Black seeks to trade pieces while having less space to relieve some pressure. After all Black is up a pawn, so the more pieces that they trade is favorable for them. We have a nasty surprise waiting for Black, though. Your opponent will likely be totally clueless here and have no idea what is waiting for them. Get ready to blow your opponent off the board! } 9. Bxd2 { [%csl Rc6,Gd2,Gd5]Simply recapturing. } 9... Qe7+ $2 { [%cal Ge7e1][%csl Rc6,Gd5,Re7]A terrible move! To show how rare this position is, GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda from Poland, a 2700+ Grandmaster, played this move in this position, which means that he likely never saw this position before. These days it is very hard to surprise your opponent with a sound line, but the 7.Nbd2 line is engine- approved and still carries all the surprise. } 10. Kf1 $1 { [%csl Rc6,Gd5,Re7,Gf1]The King simply steps away, keeping all the threats alive. } 10... Qc5 { An in-between move, attacking the c4-Bishop before moving the c6-Knight. } ( 10... Bxd2 11. Qxd2 Qc5 { Counter-attacking the Bishop. } 12. Qc3 { The Knight and the g7-pawn are now under attack. } 12... Ne7 $146 13. b4 { ± Kicking the Queen away from the Bishop and then taking the g7-pawn on the next move. } ) 11. Qe2+ { [%cal Ge2c4,Ge2e8,Gd2b4,Ga1e1][%csl Rc6,Gd5,Ge2,Re8]Defending the Bishop with tempo! After Black plays } 11... Ne7 $146 { we can simply reply } 12. Re1 { and the Black King has a hard time getting out of the center. } * 

