 zone and are coming out for the opponent. I am very sure our opponent will be completely shocked and likely has never seen this position in their life! [--] Remember our mindset here: we have the initiative and have to play fast and dynamic, and always pose questions to our opponent. Our advantage is not a static advantage, it requires us to always be proactive and put pressure to Black, in the great style of Garry Kasparov. } ) 11... d6 { [%cal Gc8h3][%csl Gd6]The most natural and obvious reply. Black opens the scope of their Bishop and keeps an eye on the g4-square. } 12. h5 $1 { [%csl Rg7,Gh5]We are ready to advance the h-pawn and destroy the Black King's cover. Black must be very careful now. } 12... h6 { The most logical move. Black stops the h-pawn in its tracks. } 13. O-O-O $1 { White castles long. We show our aggressive caveman-like intentions. This is how chess should be played, and this line reminds me of the Romantic era of chess - of all the gambits where White would be very aggressive and go all in! However, this line has all of that and is at the same time engine approved! } 13... O-O 14. Rdg1 { [%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5]A self-explanatory move. White is ready to play g4 and go for mate. When was the last time that you got a position like this? Flip the board for one second and you will see how scary it is for Black! } 14... b5 $5 { [%csl Gb5,Rc4]Played by GM Nakamura against GM Caruana. Black tries to open up the Queenside immediately and get counterplay. } 15. Bb3 $5 { [%cal Gg2g4]A smart move, keeping the Queenside closed. } 15... Bg4 { [%csl Rf3,Rg2,Gg4]Black physically stops g4, but White is not deterred! } 16. Nh4 $1 { [%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4][%csl Rg4]White is ready to push the pawns forward with f3 next to kick the Bishop! } 16... c5 $2 { A blunder, played by GM Nakamura. Now let us see how we take down a 2700 world class Grandmaster! } 17. f3 { [%csl Gf3,Rg4]Kicking away the uninvited guest! } 17... Bxh5 18. g4 { [%csl Gg4,Rh5]We get through with brute force! } 18... Bg6 19. Nf5 $18 { [%cal Gg1g7,Gh1h6][%csl Re7,Gf5,Rg7,Rh6]Caruana 2792 vs Nakamura 2736, 2022. Grandmaster Caruana made easy work of Grandmaster Nakamura here in this winning position. } * 

