 zone and are coming out for the opponent. I am very sure our opponent will be completely shocked and likely has never seen this position in their life! [--] Remember our mindset here: we have the initiative and have to play fast and dynamic, and always pose questions to our opponent. Our advantage is not a static advantage, it requires us to always be proactive and put pressure to Black, in the great style of Garry Kasparov. } ) 11... d6 { [%cal Gc8h3][%csl Gd6]The most natural and obvious reply. Black opens the scope of their Bishop and keeps an eye on the g4-square. } 12. h5 $1 { [%csl Rg7,Gh5]We are ready to advance the h-pawn and destroy the Black King's cover. Black must be very careful now. } 12... h6 { The most logical move. Black stops the h-pawn in its tracks. } 13. O-O-O $1 { White castles long. We show our aggressive caveman-like intentions. This is how chess should be played, and this line reminds me of the Romantic era of chess - of all the gambits where White would be very aggressive and go all in! However, this line has all of that and is at the same time engine approved! } 13... O-O 14. Rdg1 { [%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5]A self-explanatory move. White is ready to play g4 and go for mate. When was the last time that you got a position like this? Flip the board for one second and you will see how scary it is for Black! } 14... c6 $2 { [%cal Gc6d5][%csl Rd5]A logical move but a terrible one! Already the computer gives a huge evaluation for White. This move was played against me by an Indian 2380 FIDE Master, and I obtained a winning position from the opening. Black tries to open the c-file and contest the center. } 15. g4 { [%cal Gg1g7][%csl Gg4,Rg7]Let there be war!!! White goes for the Black King's throat. } 15... cxd5 { This move was played against me by the Indian FIDE master in a serious classical tournament. Already the computer gives White a winning advantage. } 16. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3h7,Gd3b1][%csl Gd3,Rg6,Rh7]} 16... f6 { [%cal Gf6g5][%csl Rg5,Rh7]Black stops g5 but weakens the light squares around the King even more. } 17. Kb1 $16 { [%cal Gb1a1,Gd3b1,Gf3h4][%csl Rg8]A very important move. White moves the King to a much more secure place, away from the open c-file, and is now ready to continue with attacking ideas such as Bc2-Qd3 and can look forward to mating the Black King. } * 

