 zone and are coming out for the opponent. I am very sure our opponent will be completely shocked and likely has never seen this position in their life! [--] Remember our mindset here: we have the initiative and have to play fast and dynamic, and always pose questions to our opponent. Our advantage is not a static advantage, it requires us to always be proactive and put pressure to Black, in the great style of Garry Kasparov. } ) 11... d6 { [%cal Gc8h3][%csl Gd6]The most natural and obvious reply. Black opens the scope of their Bishop and keeps an eye on the g4-square. } 12. h5 $1 { [%csl Rg7,Gh5]We are ready to advance the h-pawn and destroy the Black King's cover. Black must be very careful now. } 12... h6 { The most logical move. Black stops the h-pawn in its tracks. } 13. O-O-O $1 { White castles long. We show our aggressive caveman-like intentions. This is how chess should be played, and this line reminds me of the Romantic era of chess - of all the gambits where White would be very aggressive and go all in! However, this line has all of that and is at the same time engine approved! } 13... O-O 14. Rdg1 { [%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5]A self-explanatory move. White is ready to play g4 and go for mate. When was the last time that you got a position like this? Flip the board for one second and you will see how scary it is for Black! } 14... Bg4 $1 { [%csl Rg2,Gg4]The best move! Black physically stops our g-pawn from advancing. If Black has gotten this far they have done well! However, we still have many problems to pose to Black. } 15. Rh4 { [%cal Gh4g4][%csl Rg4]} 15... Qd7 $1 { [%csl Gd7,Gg4]Black rightfully maintains the physical blockade of the g-pawn! } 16. Qf4 $5 { [%cal Gh4g4,Gf4g4][%csl Gf4,Rg4]At all costs White continues to try to remove the g4-Bishop so that we can push our g-pawn further forward. If } 16... Bf5 { The recommendation of GM Jan Werle in his 1...e5 LTR. He does not go too deep in this position, but he points out this line for White. Black intends to meet g4 by tucking the Bishop away on h7. } ( 16... Bf5 { , we have } 17. g4 { starting the Kingside storm and if } ) ( 16... f5 { , we have } 17. Nd4 $146 { exploiting the e6-square. In ONLY 2 GAMES did Black arrive at the correct defense, which is saying a lot! } ) 17. g4 $1 { [%cal Gg4f5,Gg1g7][%csl Gf4,Gg4]An obligatory move. We continue our attack! } 17... Bh7 18. g5 $1 { [%cal Gg1g7][%csl Gf4,Gg5,Rg7,Rg8]As in the Scotch gambit, we continue fiercely and boldy use our initiative to take the challenge to Black! } 18... Qf5 $1 { [%cal Gf5b1][%csl Rb1,Gf5,Gh7]GM Werle reached this position in his course and ended his analysis here, saying “The position remains complex, but at least we managed to exchange Queens and our Knight will land on f5 and guard the g7-pawn. Hopefully, this position will be tested more in practice.” [--] While the position is by no means better for us, we will be better prepared, we will look further in the position and have a much better idea of what to do than our opponent. } 19. Qxf5 { We are forced to trade Queens. } 19... Nxf5 20. Re4 $36 { [%cal Gg5g6][%csl Rh7]I believe that White has a lot of play here. Even in the endgame being down a pawn, the initiative continues. The engine still gives the = evaluation, which means that we have full compensation and more for the pawn. Black can easily go wrong. I believe that from here onwards, GM Werle's followers are already out of book. } 20... hxg5 21. Nxg5 $36 { [%cal Gg1g8,Gg5h7,Gc4d3,Gc1d2,Ge4c4,Gc4c7,Gg1c1][%csl Rc7,Gg5,Rh7]White has the huge threat of Bd3 which would undermine the Knight on f5. Black still has many problems to solve. We have an active Rook on g1, a strong Knight on g5 which is ready to capture Black's Bishop at any moment, and our Bishop ready to drop back to d3. In addition, White can always centralize the King with Kd2 in the future. } * 

