ES did Black arrive at the correct defense, which is saying a lot! } ) 17. gxf3 { [%cal Gg1g7,Gf4h6][%csl Rg7,Rh6]The g-file is open, but with precise play Black is able to defend. } 17... Kh8 $3 { The best defense! Black rightfully steps away from the g-file and is soon out of trouble. Here I suggest a way for White to pose one last question before agreeing to a draw. Remember that this position is very rare... } 18. Rxg7 $5 { [%csl Rg7]Bringing the Black King into the open! } 18... Kxg7 19. Rg4+ { [%cal Gg4g7][%csl Rg7]} 19... Ng6 { [%cal Gf6g7][%csl Gg4,Gg6,Rg7]Black correctly gives back the Knight to protect their King. } 20. Qd4+ { [%cal Gd4g7][%csl Rg7]} 20... Kg8 { The best move. Black is is navigating the complications very well! } 21. Qf6 { [%cal Gh5g6,Gg4g8][%csl Gf6,Gg4,Rg6,Rg8]We are ready to give mate with hxg6 next! } 21... Qd8 $1 { The final test! Black had to play perfect 21 moves just to make a meager draw, what a patzer... Now we unfortunately have to force a draw. But, as you can see, the line was very fun and exciting - this is how chess should really be played. Real romantic chess in the style of Tal and Morphy! } 22. Rxg6+ { [%cal Gf7g6][%csl Gg6,Rg8]} 22... fxg6 23. Qxg6+ $10 { [%cal Gg6h6][%csl Gg6,Rg8]We take on h6 next and make a draw. What to do? In life we cannot always win. [--] You have survived to the end of this chapter, fly and be free!! Crush the opponents with this novel line! } * 

