cal Gc6d4,Gd6h2,Gg4h2][%csl Rc6,Rd4]Black is up a pawn, ready to castle and keep their material advantage, so we have to act quickly! } 9. b3 { [%cal Gc1a3][%csl Rd6,Re7,Re8]The Bishop is ready to come to a3 with deadly effect! } 9... O-O { Black simply finishes their development! } 10. Ba3 { [%cal Ga3e7,Ge1e8][%csl Rd6,Re7]} 10... Qd8 11. Bxe7 { [%csl Rd8,Ge7,Rf8]With this move White regains the pawn on d4. } 11... Nxe7 12. Qxd4 { [%cal Gd4d8,Ge1e7][%csl Gd4,Rd8,Re7,Rg4]White seeks to take Black into the endgame where we can hope for an advantage due to our small lead in development and Black's awkwardly placed Knights. } 12... Nc6 $2 { [%cal Gc6d4][%csl Rd4]} 13. Qf4 $16 { [%cal Gf4f7,Gc4f7][%csl Gf4,Rf7]We trade the Queens only on our terms! } 13... Qf6 $2 { [%cal Gf6a1,Gf6f4][%csl Ra1,Rf4]Played in a blitz game by a serious Grandmaster. This is a huge blunder, but GM Chigaev did not find the best move! } 14. Qxc7 $1 { [%cal Gf6a1][%csl Ra1]Oh no, we have blundered our Rook! :((( } 14... Qxa1 15. Qxf7+ $3 { [%cal Gc4g8][%csl Rf7,Rg8]} 15... Rxf7 16. Re8# { [%cal Ge8g8,Gc4g8][%csl Rg8]What a very nice mate in 16 moves! :-) } * 

