1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]The traditional Scotch gambit! This gambit goes all the way back in time. For some reason unknown to me, it went out of fashion for a very long time, but I think it is time to bring it back! [--] The traditional Scotch gambit is just what we need: it's very dynamic, aggressive, cuts to the point, and goes for the full point. The engine has found many ways for Black to 'equalize', but I have found many ways to pose problems to Black, for instance with a very creative novelty that we will see in one of the mainlines. [--] Let us bring back the Romantic era of chess. No more boring slow Italians or Ruy Lopez, but let us play fighting chess! You have a very aggressive, swashbuckler's repertoire in front of you that is also backed by the strongest engines! Be ready for a journey and get ready to unlock your inner dragon, bringing out the fire on the board! } 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]Posing a very crucial question to Black. Now } 5... Ng4 { [%cal Gg4e5,Gc6e5][%csl Re5,Gf3]Black goes directly for a counter-attack, fighting hard to get rid of our strong e5-pawn! } ( 5... d5 { has always been the most popular move, while } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { has risen greatly in popularity in recent years and is a very solid try to equalize. I believe that it is even stronger than the traditional } ) ( 5... d5 { In this chapter we shall disarm } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { and } ) ( 5... Ng4 $146 { , and then } ) ( 5... d5 { will be tackled in the following chapters! } ) 6. O-O { We know that the Scotch gambit relies on solid chess principles of development, the activity of pieces and keeping up the initiative! } 6... d6 { Black immediately gets rid of the e5-pawn. } 7. exd6 { [%cal Ge1e8][%csl Re8]} 7... Bxd6 { Black is now ready to castle. } 8. Re1+ { [%cal Ge1e8][%csl Re8]Bringing the Rook onto the open e-file with tempo. } 8... Kf8 $5 { [%cal Gd6h2,Gg4h2,Gf3d4,Gd1d4,Gd8d4][%csl Rd4,Rf8,Rh2,Rh8]Black is a greedy person! They give up the right to castle and try to hold on to the extra pawn. Black will have a hard time organizing their forces and getting the King to safety. Despite being down a pawn, White will enjoy pressure against the Black King while the h8-Rook also stays totally out of the game. } 9. h3 $5 { [%cal Gh3g4][%csl Rg4]A forcing move! White kicks back the Black Knight and puts Black in the hot seat! This is the second most popular move in the position. } 9... Nge5 $1 { [%cal Ge5c4,Ge5f3][%csl Rc4,Ge5,Rf3]The Knight occupies a stronghold in the center, hitting our c4-Bishop with tempo. } 10. Nxe5 { Clearing the way with a very cunning idea in mind! } 10... Nxe5 { [%cal Ge5c4,Ge1e5][%csl Rc4]White now has a crucial choice to make. } ( 10... Bxe5 $2 { is a dubious move. Black is being too greedy and forgets the King. We can answer with } 11. Nd2 $2 $146 { → , bringing more fuel to the fire! White is in no rush as the Black King is sitting out in the open. We have ideas such as Ne4 and Qh5 next. The Black Rook is blocked in on h8, while we are ready to bring out our dark-squared Bishop and Queen. } ) 11. Bd5 $3 { [%cal Gb1d2,Gd5b7,Gd1d4][%csl Rb7,Rd4,Gd5]A very deep move!! We want to provoke Black into playing ...c6, as the pawn on c7 is a key defender of the d6-Bishop. This point is very easy to miss or misunderstand, but in the following variation it will become clear. } 11... c6 { [%cal Gc6d5,Gd1d4][%csl Rd4,Rd5]Black cannot hold it anymore, they kick the d5-Bishop away and take a defender away from their own d6-Bishop. } 12. Bb3 $5 { [%cal Gb3f7,Ge1e5,Gd6e5,Gc1f4,Gb1d2][%csl Gb3,Re5,Rf7]After provoking ...c6 we happily retreat. No games have been reached with this position - it's totally new. } 12... Qf6 { [%cal Gc8h3,Gf6f2,Gd6h2,Gd1d4,Ge5f3][%csl Rh3]Black brings the Queen out and gives White a reminder to be very careful. } 13. Nd2 $40 { [%cal Gd2e4,Ge4f6,Ge4d6,Gc7d6][%csl Rc6,Rc7,Rf6]The point of provoking ...c6 can be seen now: White wants to bring the Knight to the strong central post on e4, from where it will come with great threats against Black's Queen and Bishop. Notice how the Black position is more loose without the c7-pawn. } 13... Qg6 { [%cal Gg6g2,Gc8h3][%csl Rg2,Rh3]Black is ready to play ...Bxh3 and stir up some Kingside play. The immediate } ( 13... Bxh3 $2 { transposes to 13...Qg6 after } 14. Ne4 $146 { . If we capture the Bishop with } ( 14. gxh3 { , Black will be able to set up a draw via a repetition of moves: } 14... Qg6+ 15. Kh1 { and then } 15... Qf5 { , forcing the White King to move back and forth. So we should play 14.Ne4 when pieces are hanging and flying all over the board - the fun begins! } ) ) 14. Ne4 { [%cal Ge4d6,Gc1h6,Gd1d4,Gb3f7][%csl Rd4,Rd6,Ge4,Rf7]Ignoring the h3-pawn. We again see the point of how the c6-pawn is unable to defend Black's dark-squared Bishop. This Bishop, the d4-pawn and the weak King really keep Black under serious pressure. } 14... Bxh3 { [%cal Gg6g2,Gh3g2][%csl Rg2]Black goes ahead and grabs the h3-pawn, threatening mate. } 15. Ng5 $40 { [%cal Gg5h3,Gd1d4][%csl Rd4,Rd6,Rf8,Gg5,Rh3]With no King safety and so many pieces hanging, Black is in great trouble. We can soon regain the d4-pawn and continue the hunt for the Black King. } * 

