1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4][%csl Re4]The traditional Scotch gambit! This gambit goes all the way back in time. For some reason unknown to me, it went out of fashion for a very long time, but I think it is time to bring it back! [--] The traditional Scotch gambit is just what we need: it's very dynamic, aggressive, cuts to the point, and goes for the full point. The engine has found many ways for Black to 'equalize', but I have found many ways to pose problems to Black, for instance with a very creative novelty that we will see in one of the mainlines. [--] Let us bring back the Romantic era of chess. No more boring slow Italians or Ruy Lopez, but let us play fighting chess! You have a very aggressive, swashbuckler's repertoire in front of you that is also backed by the strongest engines! Be ready for a journey and get ready to unlock your inner dragon, bringing out the fire on the board! } 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]Posing a very crucial question to Black. Now } 5... Ne4 { A very modern move! We must be well aware of this possibility and can expect this move from younger players who work with engines. However, we still will pose Black a great challenge! } ( 5... d5 { has always been the most popular move, while } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { has risen greatly in popularity in recent years and is a very solid try to equalize. I believe that it is even stronger than the traditional } ) ( 5... d5 { In this chapter we shall disarm } ) ( 5... Ne4 $146 { and } ) ( 5... Ng4 $146 { , and then } ) ( 5... d5 { will be tackled in the following chapters! } ) 6. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2e4][%csl Ge2,Re4]Immediately challenging the e4-Knight! Please note that the move } ( 6. O-O $2 { looks 'logical', but it does not work for White as Black gets an improved version of the 5...d5 6.Bb5 Ne4 mainline where they don't need to waste time on playing ...Bd7. For example } 6... d5 { and if White now takes } 7. exd6 { , Black just recaptures with the knight } 7... Nxd6 $146 { and is ready to continue with developing moves like ...Bg4 and ...Be7. If instead White tries 7... d5 7.Bb5 to get a similar position to the Scotch gambit mainline, Black does not have to answer 7...Bd7 but instead can play 7...Bg4 after which Black will slowly gain the advantage. } ) 6... Nc5 7. c3 $5 { [%cal Gc3d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4]A typical move in Scotch gambit style! White is ready to give a pawn to speed up the development, and Black has to be very careful! } 7... Ne6 $6 { [%cal Ge6d4,Gc6d4][%csl Rd4]Black firmly holds onto the pawn. This suspicious move has been played 2 times by 2700 Grandmaster Andrey Esipenko. } 8. cxd4 { Clarifying the situation in the center. } 8... Nexd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. Qe4 $1 { [%cal Ge4d4][%csl Rd4,Ge4]Centralizing the Queen and forcing the Knight back! } 10... Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1][%csl Re1]Black develops with tempo. } 11. Nc3 { [%cal Ge4d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4]We don't mind bringing our Knight out. } 11... Nc6 { Black retreats from danger. } 12. O-O { [%cal Gc3d5,Ge8g8,Gc4d3,Gc1h6][%csl Rc8,Gd5,Ge4,Ge5,Re8,Rh7]We are ready to move our Knight to d5 next with great effect. Black has less space and is cramped and we have powerful pieces and great attacking prospects. } * 

