eady to continue with developing moves like ...Bg4 and ...Be7. If instead White tries 7... d5 7.Bb5 to get a similar position to the Scotch gambit mainline, Black does not have to answer 7...Bd7 but instead can play 7...Bg4 after which Black will slowly gain the advantage. } ) 6... Nc5 7. c3 $5 { [%cal Gc3d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4]A typical move in Scotch gambit style! White is ready to give a pawn to speed up the development, and Black has to be very careful! } 7... d3 $1 { [%cal Gc5d3][%csl Gc4,Rd3,Re2]A very smart move by Black! They want to win our light-squared Bishop without making any concessions! } 8. Qe3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Ge3e8][%csl Rc5]We don't give up our light-squared Bishop that easily! } 8... Ne6 { [%cal Gd7d5]Black makes it possible to play ...d6 or ...d5 now that the e-file is blocked! } 9. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7,Gc4d3,Ge3d3][%csl Rd3,Ge5,Gf3]We get our King to safety and are ready to win back the d3-pawn with interest. } 9... d6 { [%cal Gd6e5,Gc6e5][%csl Re5]A very common idea! Our pawn on e5, the traditional Scotch gambit pawn, is so strong that Black always tries to get rid of it! } 10. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e5][%csl Re5]We have no fear and simply defend the e5-pawn. Black will now try to trade pieces so that they can finish their development. } 10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Qxe5 { [%cal Ge1e5,Gc4e6][%csl Ge5,Re6]} 12... Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8]} 13. Nd2 $5 { [%cal Gd2e4,Gd2f3]A very cunning move. We are ready to bring the Knight into the game and only later worry about getting back the d3-pawn. } 13... O-O 14. Qe4 $5 { [%cal Ge4d3,Ge1e7,Ge6c5,Gc4d3][%csl Rc5,Rd3,Re7]Now we simply regain the d3-pawn. } * 

