eady to continue with developing moves like ...Bg4 and ...Be7. If instead White tries 7... d5 7.Bb5 to get a similar position to the Scotch gambit mainline, Black does not have to answer 7...Bd7 but instead can play 7...Bg4 after which Black will slowly gain the advantage. } ) 6... Nc5 7. c3 $5 { [%cal Gc3d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4]A typical move in Scotch gambit style! White is ready to give a pawn to speed up the development, and Black has to be very careful! } 7... d3 $1 { [%cal Gc5d3][%csl Gc4,Rd3,Re2]A very smart move by Black! They want to win our light-squared Bishop without making any concessions! } 8. Qe3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Ge3e8][%csl Rc5]We don't give up our light-squared Bishop that easily! } 8... Ne6 { [%cal Gd7d5]Black makes it possible to play ...d6 or ...d5 now that the e-file is blocked! } 9. O-O { [%cal Gc4f7,Gc4d3,Ge3d3][%csl Rd3,Ge5,Gf3]We get our King to safety and are ready to win back the d3-pawn with interest. } 9... d5 { [%csl Gd5]Black takes their share of the center, but we are happy to give it to them without any issues, as we simply recapture the d3-pawn. } 10. Bxd3 $14 { [%cal Gf1d1,Ge3e2,Gf8c5][%csl Gd3]We are very happy here. We still have our strong e5 pawn which is a bone in the throat of Black's position, and our very powerful light-squared Bishop still points towards Black's King. [--] One thing you should notice: in the Scotch gambit, the e5-pawn is often a big problem for Black, while in the 7.Nbd2 line against 4...Bc5, it is the d5-pawn which ties up Black's position! } * 

