eady to continue with developing moves like ...Bg4 and ...Be7. If instead White tries 7... d5 7.Bb5 to get a similar position to the Scotch gambit mainline, Black does not have to answer 7...Bd7 but instead can play 7...Bg4 after which Black will slowly gain the advantage. } ) 6... Nc5 7. c3 $5 { [%cal Gc3d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4]A typical move in Scotch gambit style! White is ready to give a pawn to speed up the development, and Black has to be very careful! } 7... d3 $1 { [%cal Gc5d3][%csl Gc4,Rd3,Re2]A very smart move by Black! They want to win our light-squared Bishop without making any concessions! } 8. Qe3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Ge3e8][%csl Rc5]We don't give up our light-squared Bishop that easily! } 8... Be7 { The best move. Black is ready to just complete their development, and also to play ...d6/...d5. } 9. O-O { Instead, } ( 9. b4 { is a very complicated try, but I think there is no need to play like that. Let us keep things simple... Our opponent already has to know a lot of theory just to get to this point. } ) 9... O-O $6 { This is a small inaccuracy which allows White to put Black under some pressure! } 10. b4 { [%csl Gb4,Rc5]Now we kick the Knight back! } 10... Ne6 11. Rd1 { [%cal Gd1d8][%csl Rd8]Sneakily lining up the Rook against the Black Queen. } 11... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5]Black strikes back in the center but misses White's next move! } 12. Rxd3 $14 { [%cal Gc4d5,Gd3d8][%csl Gc4,Gd3,Rd5,Rd8]} * 

