eady to continue with developing moves like ...Bg4 and ...Be7. If instead White tries 7... d5 7.Bb5 to get a similar position to the Scotch gambit mainline, Black does not have to answer 7...Bd7 but instead can play 7...Bg4 after which Black will slowly gain the advantage. } ) 6... Nc5 7. c3 $5 { [%cal Gc3d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4]A typical move in Scotch gambit style! White is ready to give a pawn to speed up the development, and Black has to be very careful! } 7... d3 $1 { [%cal Gc5d3][%csl Gc4,Rd3,Re2]A very smart move by Black! They want to win our light-squared Bishop without making any concessions! } 8. Qe3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Ge3e8][%csl Rc5]We don't give up our light-squared Bishop that easily! } 8... Be7 { The best move. Black is ready to just complete their development, and also to play ...d6/...d5. } 9. O-O { Instead, } ( 9. b4 { is a very complicated try, but I think there is no need to play like that. Let us keep things simple... Our opponent already has to know a lot of theory just to get to this point. } ) 9... d5 $1 { [%csl Rc4]The most accurate move, Black forces us to take on d6. } 10. exd6 { [%cal Gd6e7][%csl Re7]} 10... cxd6 { [%csl Rd6]Not an easy decision to make for Black, but the best decision! } 11. Bxd3 { Now that White has an advantage in pawn structure we give up the Bishop, allowing Black to trade it off for their Knight. Black will have the Bishop pair while White has the more solid and better pawn structure. } 11... Nxd3 { Black finally nabs the Bishop. } 12. Qxd3 { [%csl Gd3,Gf3]} 12... O-O 13. Bf4 $10 { [%cal Gf4d6,Gd8b6,Gb1a3,Gb1d2,Gf1e1,Ge1d1][%csl Ra3,Rb6,Gd3,Rd6]Only one game has reached this position!! If Black plays } 13... Qb6 { next, the move } 14. Na3 $146 { is especially strong. Otherwise we would continue with Nbd2. [--] The computer gives the = evaluation here, but I believe that this position is easier to play with White, as we have a clear plan: to target the d6-pawn. We also have the d4 outpost to work with for one of our Knights. [--] Black has played the best moves, but we still have an easier position to play. We should not be disappointed as we can still continue to put pressure on Black. [--] With that we have seen 5...Ng4 and 5...Ne4. 5...Ne4 is a modern trend, and you can definitely expect to see that move in your games, but I believe that we have many ideas here to challenge Black! } * 

