1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]This is the signal move of the classical Scotch gambit. The e5-pawn is one of our greatest friends in the Scotch Gambit, it points us towards a Kingside attack and poses a lot of problems to black. [--] In this chapter, we will check the exciting and trendy 6...Nd7, which is actually a great option if Black wants to play for the win. I would seriously consider this option with the Black pieces. However I will propose to you a very aggressive Scotch gambit-style way for White to continue to fight without backing down! } 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5,Ge5,Rf6]This has been the mainline for a very long time. Black strikes back in the center, gaining a tempo on our Bishop! } 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8][%csl Gb5,Rc6]On b5 the Bishop exerts great pressure on the c6-Knight, which is defending the Black d4-pawn and keeping an eye on e5. In most cases, we will later eliminate this Knight. } 6... Nd7 $5 { [%cal Gb5c6,Gb7c6,Gd7e5,Gc6e5,Gc6d4,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Re8]A very interesting move! Black is preventing us from immediately taking on d4 and claims that their Kingside Knight is much better on d7 rather than e4, where it can become exposed at times. Black is inviting us to take the c6-Knight after which they will accept doubled pawns, which can be used as a dynamic asset. [--] The older classical players most likely won't know this move - I would expect this move from the younger generation of players, as they believe that they are surprising us with this move. However, lucky for you, International Master Alan-Safar Ramoutar is a seasoned openings veteran and leaves no stone left unturned... } 7. O-O $1 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Rd4,Ge5]Development is key in the Scotch! Always remember the principles of the Scotch gambit: development, active play, not being afraid to give some material for the initiative and going for the kill! } 7... Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8]Black hurries to finish development and castle. They are waiting for us to take on c6. } 8. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gb1c3][%csl Gc3,Rd4]The most aggressive idea and my suggestion. I do not like the mainline with } ( 8. Bxc6 { as Black gets very good play and it is not clear for us in many variations. I have always found the arising positions very hard to play. Now } ) ( 8. c3 { This is a move in real Scotch gambit style, a rather thematic move. White sacrifices a pawn to speed up development and get the attack going quicker! } ) ( 8. c3 { is likely not expected by your opponent as it has only been played in 46 games according to my online database, compared to } ) ( 8. Bxc6 { which has seen 400+ games. So with } ) ( 8. c3 { we surprise our opponent! They are likely out of preparation already, while our preparation is just getting started! Get ready to blow Black off the board. } ) 8... d3 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gb5d3,Gc6e5,Gd7e5][%csl Gb5,Rc6,Rd3,Ge5]This is a coward's move!! Black is too scared to accept the sacrifice, they are desperate to get out of danger and simply wish to give back the pawn to complete their development. This move says a lot about your opponent: if they play this move, they are a coward, a chessplayer without any substance, a weakling, a person never to be feared, a joke, a clown, I could go on... We must crush Black now! [--] This move has actually been played by some Grandmasters. they may have the Grandmaster title, but they are without any salt. } 9. Re1 { [%cal Ge1e5,Gf3e5][%csl Ge5]The d3-pawn is not going anywhere. First White secures the e5 stronghold. } 9... O-O { Black finishes their development and sets a small trap for us! After } ( 9... Nc5 $2 $146 10. b4 Ne4 $146 11. Bxd3 $16 { Black's position is already collapsing. } ) 10. h3 $1 { [%cal Gh3g4,Gb5d3][%csl Rd3,Rg4]A very important move, taking away the g4-square. Now we are ready to take on d3! The immediate } ( 10. Bxd3 $2 { would be an inaccuracy! } 10... Nc5 $10 $146 { is a very important detail. We have to move our Bishop and then Black has the g4-square for their own Bishop! Black finishes developing their pieces with ease. } ) 10... f6 $5 { [%cal Gf8f2,Gf6e5][%csl Re5,Gf6]Black forces us to open the position. } 11. exf6 { [%cal Ge1e7][%csl Rf6]} 11... Bxf6 12. Bxd3 { [%cal Gd3h7,Gd1d5][%csl Gd3,Gd5,Rh7]The Bishop recaptures the pawn and takes up a prime position, pointing directly at the Black King! } 12... Nc5 { [%cal Gc5d3,Gc8h3][%csl Gc5,Rd3]A logical move, opening the c8-Bishop while attacking ours. } 13. Bc2 { [%cal Gd1d5,Gc2h7][%csl Gc2,Rd5,Rh7]Preserving our Bishop. Now Black will try to exchange some pieces. } 13... d4 { [%cal Gf6d4,Gc6d4,Gd1d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4,Gf3]Black tries to simplify matters and aim for a draw! } 14. cxd4 { [%cal Gf3d4,Gd1d4][%csl Rc6,Gd4,Gf3,Rf6]We have no problem with trading pieces, as we will continue with pressure in the endgame. } 14... Nxd4 15. Nxd4 { [%cal Gf6d4,Gc1e3,Ge3c5,Gd1d8][%csl Rc5]} 15... Qxd4 16. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gd4d1,Gc2h7][%csl Rd4,Rh7]Developing with tempo and forcing the trade of Queens. } 16... Qxd1 17. Rxd1 { [%cal Gd1d8,Ge3c5][%csl Rc5]} 17... b6 { [%cal Gb6c5,Ge3c5][%csl Rc5]} 18. Nc3 $14 { [%cal Gc3b5,Gc3d5,Gc2h7,Gd1d8][%csl Gc3,Rc7]We finish our development and can hope to apply pressure. We can look forward to attacking moves such as Nb5 or Nd5. White has the much more active pieces while Black has not finished their development yet. } * 

