Black strikes back and tries to create some play in the center. If Black waits, we can simply continue our agenda with f5! } 13. Nc2 $5 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gd1d5,Gc8b7,Gd1g4,Gg4g7][%csl Ga2,Ra5,Rd5,Rg7]We will see almost this exact position in the mainline of this chapter! The only difference is that here our pawn is on a2 instead of a5! The position can be played in almost exactly the same way, as the pawn being on a5 does not make a big difference! You see that the Scotch can be very thematic, we can see many reccurring ideas! } 13... d4 { [%csl Rc3,Rd4]Pushing back our Knight and advancing in the center. } 14. Qf3 $1 { [%cal Gf3a8,Gc7c6,Gf4f5][%csl Ra8,Gf3]A strong in-between move!! If Black plays } 14... Ra7 { [%cal Gc7c6,Ga7h7,Gf3a8][%csl Ga7,Rc3]Black chooses to move the Rook away and waits for us to move our Knight. They can perhaps bring the Rook into the defense after playing ...c6. } ( 14... c6 { , we answer } 15. f5 { and continue in the same fashion as in the 9...Nb6 line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) where Black plays 10...a6. It is the same exact position except our pawn is on a2 instead of a5. } ) 15. f5 $3 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gf1f7][%csl Rc3,Ge5,Gf5]In typical Scotch gambit style! We continue the attack even at the cost of a piece. I keep saying that we should play dynamically, use the momentum and initiative to just springboard our position. We have no time to sit still and play around, we go for the throat! } 15... dxc3 16. f6 { [%cal Gf6g7][%csl Re7,Re8,Gf6,Rg7,Rh8]Crashing through on the Kingside! } 16... gxf6 17. Rd1 $3 { [%cal Gd1d8,Gf3d1][%csl Gd1,Rd8,Ge5,Gf3,Rf6]After } ( 17. exf6 $2 Bd6 $19 { the Black Bishop is firmly placed, holding together the position, and White's attack runs out of fuel. } ) 17... Bd6 $2 { [%cal Ge5d6,Gd1d8][%csl Rd6,Ge5]A horrible move played by Grandmaster S. Zilka. Black willingly gives up the strong dark-squared Bishop. I have no idea what this GM smoked before playing such a move... } 18. exd6 { [%cal Gd1d8,Gf3f6,Gc7d6,Gc1f4][%csl Gd6,Re8,Rf6]We thank Black for the piece and Black remains with all the weaknesses in their position. } * 

