ting for us to take on c6. } 8. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gb1c3][%csl Gc3,Rd4]The most aggressive idea and my suggestion. I do not like the mainline with } ( 8. Bxc6 { as Black gets very good play and it is not clear for us in many variations. I have always found the arising positions very hard to play. Now } ) ( 8. c3 { This is a move in real Scotch gambit style, a rather thematic move. White sacrifices a pawn to speed up development and get the attack going quicker! } ) ( 8. c3 { is likely not expected by your opponent as it has only been played in 46 games according to my online database, compared to } ) ( 8. Bxc6 { which has seen 400+ games. So with } ) ( 8. c3 { we surprise our opponent! They are likely out of preparation already, while our preparation is just getting started! Get ready to blow Black off the board. } ) 8... dxc3 { The only real way to challenge this gambit is to accept it! } 9. Nxc3 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5,Gf3]Our pieces spring into action. We are ready to topple the Black position, as we have strong pressure in the center. Black has to react carefully. } 9... O-O $6 { Black ignores the pawn and just wants to finish development. This move gives White a good advantage. It has been played by a few not so smart Grandmasters. } 10. Qxd5 { [%cal Gd7e5,Gf3e5,Gc3d5,Gb5d7][%csl Rc6,Gd5,Rd7,Re7]White takes back the pawn and has dominating pieces! } 10... Nc5 { [%cal Gd8d5,Gc8h3][%csl Gd5]Black opens the c8-Bishop and offers a Queen trade. } 11. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5][%csl Rc5]} 11... Be6 12. Qd1 $14 { [%cal Gb5c6,Gf3e5,Ge3c5,Gc3d5,Gc3e4,Gd1e2,Ga1d1,Gb7c6][%csl Gb5,Gc5,Rc6,Rc7,Gd1,Ge5]This novelty leads to comfortable plus for White. It's a very important move: we want to trade the Queens, but only on our terms! We do not want to trade Queens on d8 and allow Black to activate a Rook with tempo. [--] White has more space, more active pieces and the Black Queen has few squares, so sooner or later Black will trade. We can consider moving our Queen to e2 to bring a Rook on the d-file to expose the Black Queen if they do not initiate the Queen trade soon. } * 

