1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]This is the signal move of the classical Scotch gambit. The e5-pawn is one of our greatest friends in the Scotch Gambit, it points us towards a Kingside attack and poses a lot of problems to black. [--] In this chapter, we will check the exciting and trendy 6...Nd7, which is actually a great option if Black wants to play for the win. I would seriously consider this option with the Black pieces. However I will propose to you a very aggressive Scotch gambit-style way for White to continue to fight without backing down! } 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5,Ge5,Rf6]This has been the mainline for a very long time. Black strikes back in the center, gaining a tempo on our Bishop! } 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8][%csl Gb5,Rc6]On b5 the Bishop exerts great pressure on the c6-Knight, which is defending the Black d4-pawn and keeping an eye on e5. In most cases, we will later eliminate this Knight. } 6... Nd7 $5 { [%cal Gb5c6,Gb7c6,Gd7e5,Gc6e5,Gc6d4,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Re8]A very interesting move! Black is preventing us from immediately taking on d4 and claims that their Kingside Knight is much better on d7 rather than e4, where it can become exposed at times. Black is inviting us to take the c6-Knight after which they will accept doubled pawns, which can be used as a dynamic asset. [--] The older classical players most likely won't know this move - I would expect this move from the younger generation of players, as they believe that they are surprising us with this move. However, lucky for you, International Master Alan-Safar Ramoutar is a seasoned openings veteran and leaves no stone left unturned... } 7. O-O $1 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Rd4,Ge5]Development is key in the Scotch! Always remember the principles of the Scotch gambit: development, active play, not being afraid to give some material for the initiative and going for the kill! } 7... Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8]Black hurries to finish development and castle. They are waiting for us to take on c6. } 8. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gb1c3][%csl Gc3,Rd4]The most aggressive idea and my suggestion. I do not like the mainline with } ( 8. Bxc6 { as Black gets very good play and it is not clear for us in many variations. I have always found the arising positions very hard to play. Now } ) ( 8. c3 { This is a move in real Scotch gambit style, a rather thematic move. White sacrifices a pawn to speed up development and get the attack going quicker! } ) ( 8. c3 { is likely not expected by your opponent as it has only been played in 46 games according to my online database, compared to } ) ( 8. Bxc6 { which has seen 400+ games. So with } ) ( 8. c3 { we surprise our opponent! They are likely out of preparation already, while our preparation is just getting started! Get ready to blow Black off the board. } ) 8... dxc3 { The only real way to challenge this gambit is to accept it! } 9. Nxc3 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5,Gf3]Our pieces spring into action. We are ready to topple the Black position, as we have strong pressure in the center. Black has to react carefully. } 9... Nb6 $5 { [%cal Gb6d5,Gc8h3,Gd1d5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5]A very logical move, which was played against me by Grandmaster David Berzces of Hungary. You see, I practice what I preach - this line has been played by me before! } 10. a4 $1 { [%cal Ga4a5][%csl Ga4,Rb6]We aim to kick the Knight from the b6-square. The Knight solidly defends the d5-pawn, and we cannot allow that! } 10... a5 { [%csl Ra4,Ga5]This was played by Grandmaster Berzces against me. I personally know this Grandmaster and he is a very well prepared openings expert, so it is clear that he knew this line. Black stops the White a-pawn in its tracks. } 11. Be3 $5 { [%cal Ge3b6,Gc7b6][%csl Rb6,Rb7]Now we are targeting the defender of the d5-pawn. It was important to provoke Black's a-pawn to a5 as Black will have to recapture with the c-pawn when we take on b6 now. } 11... Be6 { Black holds on firmly to the extra pawn! } 12. Nd4 { [%cal Gd8d7,Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gd4c6,Gb5c6][%csl Gb5,Rc6,Gd4,Rd7,Re6]Forcing the Bishop to go back to d7. If After } 12... Qd7 { we have the typical } ( 12... Bd7 { , if you are not in a fighting mood you can simply play } 13. Nf3 $146 { and Black has nothing better than to repeat moves with } ( 13. Qf3 { and play on, pressuring the d5-pawn in a different way. } ) 13... Be6 { , or you can try } ) 13. f4 { , threatening f5 to trap Black's Bishop. } * 

