ting for us to take on c6. } 8. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gb1c3][%csl Gc3,Rd4]The most aggressive idea and my suggestion. I do not like the mainline with } ( 8. Bxc6 { as Black gets very good play and it is not clear for us in many variations. I have always found the arising positions very hard to play. Now } ) ( 8. c3 { This is a move in real Scotch gambit style, a rather thematic move. White sacrifices a pawn to speed up development and get the attack going quicker! } ) ( 8. c3 { is likely not expected by your opponent as it has only been played in 46 games according to my online database, compared to } ) ( 8. Bxc6 { which has seen 400+ games. So with } ) ( 8. c3 { we surprise our opponent! They are likely out of preparation already, while our preparation is just getting started! Get ready to blow Black off the board. } ) 8... dxc3 { The only real way to challenge this gambit is to accept it! } 9. Nxc3 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5,Gf3]Our pieces spring into action. We are ready to topple the Black position, as we have strong pressure in the center. Black has to react carefully. } 9... Nb6 $5 { [%cal Gb6d5,Gc8h3,Gd1d5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5]A very logical move, which was played against me by Grandmaster David Berzces of Hungary. You see, I practice what I preach - this line has been played by me before! } 10. a4 $1 { [%cal Ga4a5][%csl Ga4,Rb6]We aim to kick the Knight from the b6-square. The Knight solidly defends the d5-pawn, and we cannot allow that! } 10... a5 { [%csl Ra4,Ga5]This was played by Grandmaster Berzces against me. I personally know this Grandmaster and he is a very well prepared openings expert, so it is clear that he knew this line. Black stops the White a-pawn in its tracks. } 11. Be3 $5 { [%cal Ge3b6,Gc7b6][%csl Rb6,Rb7]Now we are targeting the defender of the d5-pawn. It was important to provoke Black's a-pawn to a5 as Black will have to recapture with the c-pawn when we take on b6 now. } 11... O-O { Played by Grandmaster Berzces. Black simply gives back the pawn to finish their development. } 12. Bxb6 { Doubling Black's pawns and regaining the pawn on d5. } 12... cxb6 { [%csl Rb6,Rb7]} 13. Qxd5 { [%cal Ge7c5,Gd5e4][%csl Rb6,Rb7,Gd5,Ge5,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2]Recapturing the pawn and activating the Queen. First of all, White has a 4v3 pawn majority on the Kingside while Black has doubled pawns on the Queenside. Black has the Bishop pair, which gives them compensation for their crippled pawn majority, but White has the more pleasant game. I quickly agreed to a draw in my game as I was not feeling well that day, but I strongly suggest you play on in this position! Not every player is ready to battle to the 100th move. If Black plays } 13... Bc5 $5 { [%csl Rb6,Gc5]Recommended by GM Gawain Jones in his 1...e5 LTR. No games have reached this position. Black is ready to give up a pawn, allowing us to take on c6, in exchange getting great activity with the Bishop pair. } ( 13... Bc5 { , we should play } 14. Qe4 { , keeping the Queens on the board and aiming for some action on the Kingside. } ) 14. Qe4 $5 { [%cal Ga1d1][%csl Ga1,Gd1,Rd8,Ge4]Wisely keeping the Queens on the board. We are ready to bring our a1-Rook to d1 and force the Black Queen to a funny position. } 14... Nd4 { [%cal Gd4f3,Gd4b5][%csl Gd4,Rf3]GM Jones suggested this idea if White retreats the Queen and I believe he did not go any further than that. Again, we will go deeper and have the upper hand on all of his followers. [--] Black positions the Knight firmly in the center and is eager to trade pieces, which would give them more space for their remaining troops. } 15. h4 $5 { [%cal Ga1d1,Gf1d1,Gd1d8,Ge4h7,Gh4g5][%csl Rd8,Gf3,Gh4]This is a wild alternative which is equal according to the engine. The positions get very wild. White shows his aggressive intent, smelling blood! } 15... Nxf3+ { [%cal Gd8h4][%csl Rh4]Black is happy, thinking that we are now forced to ruin our pawn structure. } 16. gxf3 $40 { [%cal Ga1d1,Gf1d1,Gc3d5,Gb5d3,Gg1g7,Gg1g2][%csl Ga1,Ge4,Ge5,Gh4]We arrive at a very messy position and one that is hard to understand! This position is evaluated with all zeros by the computer, but it is a fighting position! We are ready to start play against Black's King. Our pieces are very well centralized and our next few moves are very easy to play. [--] We are ready to bring a Rook to d1, the Knight can come to d5, perhaps the Bishop to d3 to attack h7 and our King can be improved to g2 at some point. [--] The position is very tense and in full fighting spirit, GM Jones' followers definitely would not be ready for this. You are welcome to investigate this position more for yourself! } * 

