ting for us to take on c6. } 8. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gb1c3][%csl Gc3,Rd4]The most aggressive idea and my suggestion. I do not like the mainline with } ( 8. Bxc6 { as Black gets very good play and it is not clear for us in many variations. I have always found the arising positions very hard to play. Now } ) ( 8. c3 { This is a move in real Scotch gambit style, a rather thematic move. White sacrifices a pawn to speed up development and get the attack going quicker! } ) ( 8. c3 { is likely not expected by your opponent as it has only been played in 46 games according to my online database, compared to } ) ( 8. Bxc6 { which has seen 400+ games. So with } ) ( 8. c3 { we surprise our opponent! They are likely out of preparation already, while our preparation is just getting started! Get ready to blow Black off the board. } ) 8... dxc3 { The only real way to challenge this gambit is to accept it! } 9. Nxc3 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5,Gf3]Our pieces spring into action. We are ready to topple the Black position, as we have strong pressure in the center. Black has to react carefully. } 9... Nb6 $5 { [%cal Gb6d5,Gc8h3,Gd1d5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5]A very logical move, which was played against me by Grandmaster David Berzces of Hungary. You see, I practice what I preach - this line has been played by me before! } 10. a4 $1 { [%cal Ga4a5][%csl Ga4,Rb6]We aim to kick the Knight from the b6-square. The Knight solidly defends the d5-pawn, and we cannot allow that! } 10... a6 $5 { [%cal Ga6b5][%csl Rb5]Black decides to go after our Bishop and accept any fate. } 11. Bxc6+ { [%csl Rc6]We take the Knight without question. } 11... bxc6 { Now we arrive at a position in which it is very important to understand the ideas. } 12. a5 { [%cal Ga5b6,Gc6c5,Gc8h3][%csl Ga5,Rb6,Rc6,Rc7,Rd5]First of all, we will kick the b6-Knight back, which was our intention in the first place. Black has doubled c-pawns and the Bishop pair. However, if we are not fast enough with our aggressive/active play, Black's pawns can start advancing and become great central assets! As per usual in the Scotch gambit, we play aggressively and keep up the initiative on every move! } 12... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5][%csl Re5]} 13. Nd4 $5 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gd7e5,Gc1f4,Gf2f8][%csl Rc6,Gd4,Re5,Gf4]A crucial move! Our f-pawn, which is a stalwart of the Scotch gambit, is now ready to start moving forward. White attacks the c6-pawn and is ready to immediately show an aggressive intent with the advance of the f-pawn. If Black takes } 13... Nb8 { [%cal Gb8c6,Gc8h3][%csl Rc6]A sad move to make, but the only reasonable way to defend c6! } ( 13... Nxe5 $146 { , we simply have } 14. Bf4 { and the Black position is falling apart. } ) 14. f4 { [%csl Gf4]Another soldier is activated! We are ready to push through with f5 next. } 14... c5 $1 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Gc5,Rd4,Gd5]Black rightfully gets their own pawns going! f5 was on the agenda for White, so Black now wisely counterattacks in the center. A famous saying in chess goes 'an attack on the wing is best met by a counter-attack in the center'. } 15. Nc2 { [%cal Gd1d5,Gf4f5][%csl Gc2,Gc3,Rd5]The Knight humbly retreats. We are still ready to go f5 while we keep an eye on the d5-pawn. } 15... Bb7 { Black chooses to keep a stable center and puts the Bishop on the long diagonal. } 16. Qg4 $40 { [%cal Gg4g7,Gf4f5,Gc1h6][%csl Gg4,Rg7]Black is in grave danger. If they castle they get rolled over after } 16... O-O ( 16... Kf8 { we still proceed with } 17. f5 { anyway. Be on the lookout always for future f6-breaks which would totally destroy the Black King's cover. } ) 17. f5 { , and after a move such as } * 

