{ [%cal Gc1h6,Gf5f6][%csl Ge5,Re7,Re8,Gf5,Rf6,Rg7]A true Scotch gambit move!! The f-pawn showcases its power. In the Scotch, it is always about the initiative and dynamic play, and one very important factor is time. We simply do not have time to move our c3-Knight... Otherwise Black will consolidate. [--] Instead, we act quickly and with force! We are ready to break through with f6 at any moment. We give up the Knight to get at the Black King! } 17... dxc3 { Black had no choice but to accept our sacrifice. } 18. f6 $1 { [%cal Gc3b2,Gc1b2,Gf6g7,Gf6e7][%csl Ge5,Re7,Gf6,Rg7]We storm through as planned, breaking the Black King's pawn cover! We are ready to capture something next if Black does not take on f6. } 18... gxf6 19. exf6 { [%cal Gf1f7][%csl Re7,Re8,Gf6,Rg7]} 19... Bxf6 $2 20. Bg5 $1 { [%cal Gf1f7,Gg5d8,Ga1e1][%csl Rd8,Rf6,Rf7]The Bishop is brought out with decisive effect - } 20... Bxg5 21. Qxf7# { Just look at the Black King and Black's pieces - this is true Scotch gambit style. } * 

