1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 { [%csl Ge5,Rf6]This is the signal move of the classical Scotch gambit. The e5-pawn is one of our greatest friends in the Scotch Gambit, it points us towards a Kingside attack and poses a lot of problems to black. [--] In this chapter, we will check the exciting and trendy 6...Nd7, which is actually a great option if Black wants to play for the win. I would seriously consider this option with the Black pieces. However I will propose to you a very aggressive Scotch gambit-style way for White to continue to fight without backing down! } 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5,Ge5,Rf6]This has been the mainline for a very long time. Black strikes back in the center, gaining a tempo on our Bishop! } 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8][%csl Gb5,Rc6]On b5 the Bishop exerts great pressure on the c6-Knight, which is defending the Black d4-pawn and keeping an eye on e5. In most cases, we will later eliminate this Knight. } 6... Nd7 $5 { [%cal Gb5c6,Gb7c6,Gd7e5,Gc6e5,Gc6d4,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Re8]A very interesting move! Black is preventing us from immediately taking on d4 and claims that their Kingside Knight is much better on d7 rather than e4, where it can become exposed at times. Black is inviting us to take the c6-Knight after which they will accept doubled pawns, which can be used as a dynamic asset. [--] The older classical players most likely won't know this move - I would expect this move from the younger generation of players, as they believe that they are surprising us with this move. However, lucky for you, International Master Alan-Safar Ramoutar is a seasoned openings veteran and leaves no stone left unturned... } 7. O-O $1 { [%cal Gc1g5,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Rd4,Ge5]Development is key in the Scotch! Always remember the principles of the Scotch gambit: development, active play, not being afraid to give some material for the initiative and going for the kill! } 7... Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8]Black hurries to finish development and castle. They are waiting for us to take on c6. } 8. c3 $5 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gb1c3][%csl Gc3,Rd4]The most aggressive idea and my suggestion. I do not like the mainline with } ( 8. Bxc6 { as Black gets very good play and it is not clear for us in many variations. I have always found the arising positions very hard to play. Now } ) ( 8. c3 { This is a move in real Scotch gambit style, a rather thematic move. White sacrifices a pawn to speed up development and get the attack going quicker! } ) ( 8. c3 { is likely not expected by your opponent as it has only been played in 46 games according to my online database, compared to } ) ( 8. Bxc6 { which has seen 400+ games. So with } ) ( 8. c3 { we surprise our opponent! They are likely out of preparation already, while our preparation is just getting started! Get ready to blow Black off the board. } ) 8... dxc3 { The only real way to challenge this gambit is to accept it! } 9. Nxc3 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5,Gf3]Our pieces spring into action. We are ready to topple the Black position, as we have strong pressure in the center. Black has to react carefully. } 9... Nb6 $5 { [%cal Gb6d5,Gc8h3,Gd1d5,Gb5e8][%csl Gc3,Rd5]A very logical move, which was played against me by Grandmaster David Berzces of Hungary. You see, I practice what I preach - this line has been played by me before! } 10. a4 $1 { [%cal Ga4a5][%csl Ga4,Rb6]We aim to kick the Knight from the b6-square. The Knight solidly defends the d5-pawn, and we cannot allow that! } 10... a6 $5 { [%cal Ga6b5][%csl Rb5]Black decides to go after our Bishop and accept any fate. } 11. Bxc6+ { [%csl Rc6]We take the Knight without question. } 11... bxc6 { Now we arrive at a position in which it is very important to understand the ideas. } 12. a5 { [%cal Ga5b6,Gc6c5,Gc8h3][%csl Ga5,Rb6,Rc6,Rc7,Rd5]First of all, we will kick the b6-Knight back, which was our intention in the first place. Black has doubled c-pawns and the Bishop pair. However, if we are not fast enough with our aggressive/active play, Black's pawns can start advancing and become great central assets! As per usual in the Scotch gambit, we play aggressively and keep up the initiative on every move! } 12... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5][%csl Re5]} 13. Nd4 $5 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gd7e5,Gc1f4,Gf2f8][%csl Rc6,Gd4,Re5,Gf4]A crucial move! Our f-pawn, which is a stalwart of the Scotch gambit, is now ready to start moving forward. White attacks the c6-pawn and is ready to immediately show an aggressive intent with the advance of the f-pawn. If Black takes } 13... Nb8 { [%cal Gb8c6,Gc8h3][%csl Rc6]A sad move to make, but the only reasonable way to defend c6! } ( 13... Nxe5 $146 { , we simply have } 14. Bf4 { and the Black position is falling apart. } ) 14. f4 { [%csl Gf4]Another soldier is activated! We are ready to push through with f5 next. } 14... c5 $1 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Gc5,Rd4,Gd5]Black rightfully gets their own pawns going! f5 was on the agenda for White, so Black now wisely counterattacks in the center. A famous saying in chess goes 'an attack on the wing is best met by a counter-attack in the center'. } 15. Nc2 { [%cal Gd1d5,Gf4f5][%csl Gc2,Gc3,Rd5]The Knight humbly retreats. We are still ready to go f5 while we keep an eye on the d5-pawn. } 15... d4 { [%csl Rc3,Rd4]Black gets the central mass rolling! They do not want to give White a chance to breathe. } 16. Qf3 $1 { [%cal Gf3a8][%csl Ra8,Rc5,Rd4]A very cunning in-between move! White develops the Queen with tempo, attacking the exposed Rook on a8. [--] The position gets very crazy from here on. Black still has not castled and is still far from finishing their development. White is ready to even sacrifice some material for the attack! } 16... c6 { [%cal Gf3a8][%csl Rc6]This position has been reached in 2 games. One of them was played in a Budapest Grandmaster event between two International Masters. In that game, White was not even as closely prepared as you will be - he plays the Scotch gambit in almost all of his games, but not like how you will play it! } 17. f5 $3 { [%cal Gc1h6,Gf5f6][%csl Ge5,Re7,Re8,Gf5,Rf6,Rg7]A true Scotch gambit move!! The f-pawn showcases its power. In the Scotch, it is always about the initiative and dynamic play, and one very important factor is time. We simply do not have time to move our c3-Knight... Otherwise Black will consolidate. [--] Instead, we act quickly and with force! We are ready to break through with f6 at any moment. We give up the Knight to get at the Black King! } 17... dxc3 { Black had no choice but to accept our sacrifice. } 18. f6 $1 { [%cal Gc3b2,Gc1b2,Gf6g7,Gf6e7][%csl Ge5,Re7,Gf6,Rg7]We storm through as planned, breaking the Black King's pawn cover! We are ready to capture something next if Black does not take on f6. } 18... gxf6 19. exf6 { [%cal Gf1f7][%csl Re7,Re8,Gf6,Rg7]} 19... Bd6 { Black moves the Bishop away from the attack and gets away from danger. } 20. Bf4 $3 { [%cal Gf4d6,Ga1d1,Gd1e1,Gc3b2][%csl Rb2,Rd6,Re8,Gf4]A very important move, and actually the only move to continue the attack. The International Master I mentioned earlier went wrong here, playing } ( 20. Bh6 { , but it is very important to play } ) ( 20. Bf4 { to eliminate Black's dark-squared Bishop. This Bishop on d6 is holding together the entire position, and White should realize that it needs to be exchanged. We are down a piece and the position is very messy, but getting rid of this Bishop is a very important concept, eliminating a defender. } ) 20... Qxf6 $6 { Black decides to take the strong f6-pawn without worry. } 21. Qe3+ $14 { [%cal Ge3e8,Gf1f6,Ge8f8,Gf4h6,Gf1f8,Gc8e6,Gf4d6,Ge8d8,Ge8d7,Ga1d1,Gd6e7][%csl Ge5,Re8,Rf6,Gg5,Rh8]Black faces material losses: • if } 21... Be7 { we have } ( 21... Qe7 { we can simply take } 22. Bxd6 { due to the pin; • if 21. Qe3+ 21...Kf8 , we have 22.Bh6+ , winning the Queen with check; • finally, if 21...Kd7 we answer 22.Rad1 . What a move 21.Qe3+ is! } ) 22. Be5 { winning the h8-Rook; • if } * 

