 a mistake. This was played by a GM from the Netherlands. Black is now able to bring out the Knight to d7 and White does not have any blows to continue the attack. He is actually losing now, being down a piece. We have to act boldy and bravely each move! } 22... Nd7 $19 $146 { and eventually 0-1 (43) Beerdsen, T (2511)-Durarbayli, V (2625) Chess.com INT 2023. } ) 22... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f6,Gd8f6][%csl Rf6]A very logical move. Black develops the remaining Knight. } 23. Qd6 $1 { [%cal Gd6f8,Ge1e6,Gf6f7,Gd6c6][%csl Rc6,Re6,Ge7,Re8]Now the deadly threat is 23...-- 24.Rxe6+ followed by 24...fxe6 25.f7 mate! The Queen is deep in the enemy camp. } ( 23. Rxe6+ { does not work in this position as Black's Knight helps defend. However, White has another move, which was made possible by Black's last move. } ) 23... Nxf6 { [%cal Gd8d6][%csl Rd6,Gf6]The only move. Black gets rid of the f6-pawn which was a bone in Black's throat. } 24. Qxc6+ { [%cal Gc6e8,Gc6a8,Ge1e8,Gf1f7][%csl Ra8,Re6,Re8]Forcing Black to make a decision about their exposed King. } 24... Kf8 { The Black King steps away from the center. } 25. Qxc5+ $40 { [%cal Gc5f8,Gd8e7,Gc5e5,Gf1f6,Ge1e8][%csl Rc3,Gc5,Ge1,Gf1,Rf6,Rf8]Capturing a pawn with check and continuing the attack on the Black King. After } 25... Qe7 { we have the very powerful } 26. Qe5 { , pressuring the f6-Knight. } * 

