{ [%cal Gc1h6,Gf5f6][%csl Ge5,Re7,Re8,Gf5,Rf6,Rg7]A true Scotch gambit move!! The f-pawn showcases its power. In the Scotch, it is always about the initiative and dynamic play, and one very important factor is time. We simply do not have time to move our c3-Knight... Otherwise Black will consolidate. [--] Instead, we act quickly and with force! We are ready to break through with f6 at any moment. We give up the Knight to get at the Black King! } 17... dxc3 { Black had no choice but to accept our sacrifice. } 18. f6 $1 { [%cal Gc3b2,Gc1b2,Gf6g7,Gf6e7][%csl Ge5,Re7,Gf6,Rg7]We storm through as planned, breaking the Black King's pawn cover! We are ready to capture something next if Black does not take on f6. } 18... gxf6 19. exf6 { [%cal Gf1f7][%csl Re7,Re8,Gf6,Rg7]} 19... Bd6 { Black moves the Bishop away from the attack and gets away from danger. } 20. Bf4 $3 { [%cal Gf4d6,Ga1d1,Gd1e1,Gc3b2][%csl Rb2,Rd6,Re8,Gf4]A very important move, and actually the only move to continue the attack. The International Master I mentioned earlier went wrong here, playing } ( 20. Bh6 { , but it is very important to play } ) ( 20. Bf4 { to eliminate Black's dark-squared Bishop. This Bishop on d6 is holding together the entire position, and White should realize that it needs to be exchanged. We are down a piece and the position is very messy, but getting rid of this Bishop is a very important concept, eliminating a defender. } ) 20... Bxf4 { Rad1 was coming with an imminent pin, so Black trades Bishops. } 21. Qxf4 { [%cal Gf1f4,Ga1e1,Ga1d1][%csl Rd8,Re8]The Black King is bare in the open now. Black has only one move to keep the game going! } 21... Be6 $1 { [%cal Ge1e8][%csl Ge6]Black blocks the e-file in advance from any checks and is ready to bring the Knight out next. } 22. Rae1 $1 { [%cal Ge1e6,Gf6f7,Gf1f7][%csl Re6,Re8,Gf7]With the threat of Rxe6+, blowing open the Black King, followed by advancing the f-pawn with f7+, putting the Black King out in the open! } ( 22. Rad1 $2 { would be a mistake. This was played by a GM from the Netherlands. Black is now able to bring out the Knight to d7 and White does not have any blows to continue the attack. He is actually losing now, being down a piece. We have to act boldy and bravely each move! } 22... Nd7 $19 $146 { and eventually 0-1 (43) Beerdsen, T (2511)-Durarbayli, V (2625) Chess.com INT 2023. } ) 22... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f6,Gd8f6][%csl Rf6]A very logical move. Black develops the remaining Knight. } 23. Qd6 $1 { [%cal Gd6f8,Ge1e6,Gf6f7,Gd6c6][%csl Rc6,Re6,Ge7,Re8]Now the deadly threat is 23...-- 24.Rxe6+ followed by 24...fxe6 25.f7 mate! The Queen is deep in the enemy camp. } ( 23. Rxe6+ { does not work in this position as Black's Knight helps defend. However, White has another move, which was made possible by Black's last move. } ) 23... Nxf6 { [%cal Gd8d6][%csl Rd6,Gf6]The only move. Black gets rid of the f6-pawn which was a bone in Black's throat. } 24. Qxc6+ { [%cal Gc6e8,Gc6a8,Ge1e8,Gf1f7][%csl Ra8,Re6,Re8]Forcing Black to make a decision about their exposed King. } 24... Nd7 { [%cal Ge1e8,Gf1f8,Gh8f8][%csl Gc6,Ge6]Black blocks the check and it looks as if all of White's threats have been parried. This does not look good for us anymore, what should we do?! Black has managed to find 24 perfect computer moves and now we have to make a draw. [--] Firstly, keep in mind that it's highly unlikely for Black to find all these moves, and it is also good to know that the worst result for us is a draw. There have been 0 games in this position so it is likely that you opponent will never get here, but we aim for brilliance so we should know this position in advance! } 25. Rxf7 $1 { [%cal Gc6e6,Ge1e6][%csl Re6,Re8,Gf7]Bringing the Black King out into the open and forcing a perpetual check! } 25... Kxf7 26. Qxe6+ { [%cal Ge6f7,Gf7f8,Ge1f1][%csl Ge1,Rf1,Rf7,Rf8]} 26... Kg7 27. Qg4+ { [%cal Gg4g7][%csl Rg7]} 27... Kf8 { This is a small try to avoid direct checks. } 28. Qf3+ { [%cal Gf8g7,Gf3g4,Gf8g8,Gd8f6,Gf3a8][%csl Ra8,Gg4,Rg7]We follow the Black King while keeping an eye on the a8-Rook, not allowing } 28... Nf6 ( 28... Qf6 { . } ) 29. Rd1 $10 { [%cal Gf3f6,Gf3a8][%csl Gd1,Rd8,Rf6]The Black Queen is overworked - it cannot defend both the a8-Rook and the f6-Knight at the same time. } * 

