1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 { [%cal Ge5f6,Gc4f7][%csl Ge5,Rf6]} 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5]} 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6]} 7... Bc5 $5 { [%cal Gc5f2,Gd4c6,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Rd4,Ge4,Rf2]Black neglects defending the c6-Knight and instead counter-attacks. Their Bishop and Knight take aim at our f2-pawn if we move our d4-Knight. [--] This move is a very modern try and a move that we should be very well aware of. As per usual with me as your author, you have absolutely nothing to worry about: we will crush this line! } 8. Be3 { [%cal Ge3b6,Gd4c6,Gb5e8,Ge3d4,Ge3f2][%csl Rc6,Ge3]We defend our Knight, defend f2 and now we are ready to take on c6! } 8... Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6,Gd4c6,Gb5e8][%csl Rd7]Black chickens out and decides to defend the c6-Knight after all. } 9. Bxc6 { [%cal Gb7c6,Ga8b8,Gb8b1][%csl Gc6,Ge5]White gives up the Bishop to destroy the Black pawn structure. As you will see in the the coming Scotch gambit chapters, this is a very thematic idea. We have our strong e5-pawn while Black has weak doubled pawns. The e5-pawn signifies that we have a hold on the Kingside, while Black is stronger on the Queenside as they have the open b-file and a pawn majority on the Queenside. } 9... bxc6 10. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]We immediately challenge the strong Black Knight on e4 with our undeveloped Knight! } 10... Nxd2 { Black parts way with the e4-Knight, not letting their pawn structure be ruined even further. } 11. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gd4c6,Gd4b3,Gd2e3][%csl Rc5,Rc6,Gd2,Gd4,Rd7,Ge3,Ge5]Our pieces are working quite harmoniously. Black's light-squared Bishop on d7 is quite a bad piece as it is only defending for the moment. The Bishop on c5, on the other hand, is a very strong piece and we should definitely seek to get rid of it! } 11... Bb6 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd5d4][%csl Gb6,Ge1]Black gets the Bishop out of the way and is now ready to play ...c5 to get the central pawns going! Black would not want to allow the trade of Bishops after } ( 11... O-O 12. Nb3 $146 { , as this would lead to weak dark squares. After } 12... Bb6 { we would probably transpose to the current line. } ) 12. Nb3 $14 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb3c5,Gd2c3,Ge1g1,Gf2f4][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Rc5,Ge3,Re8]White takes control of the c5-square and offers a trade to Black's most powerful piece. Why is it important to blockade the c5-square? The c5-square is very crucial as it keeps Black's doubled pawns at bay, keeping them weak and unable to move. [--] White will first secure the situation on the Queenside then proceed with the Kingside onslaught! Qc3 is often a very useful move which both defends the e5-pawn and eyes the c5-square. White will castle next, keep an eye on c5 and advance the f-pawn to f4 at the right moment. } * 

