1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 { [%cal Ge5f6,Gc4f7][%csl Ge5,Rf6]} 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5]} 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6]} 7... Bc5 $5 { [%cal Gc5f2,Gd4c6,Gb5e8][%csl Rc6,Rd4,Ge4,Rf2]Black neglects defending the c6-Knight and instead counter-attacks. Their Bishop and Knight take aim at our f2-pawn if we move our d4-Knight. [--] This move is a very modern try and a move that we should be very well aware of. As per usual with me as your author, you have absolutely nothing to worry about: we will crush this line! } 8. Be3 { [%cal Ge3b6,Gd4c6,Gb5e8,Ge3d4,Ge3f2][%csl Rc6,Ge3]We defend our Knight, defend f2 and now we are ready to take on c6! } 8... O-O { Black prioritizes development and is ready to give up a pawn. Complications follow! This line can get very concrete, so we should be aware of everything that is going on! } 9. Nxc6 $1 { [%cal Gc6d8,Ge3c5,Gb5c6][%csl Rc6]White accepts the challenge and grabs the pawn! } 9... bxc6 10. Bxc5 $1 { [%cal Gc5f8,Gb5c6][%csl Gb5,Rc5,Rc6,Rf8]This in-between move is crucial, not allowing Black to take on e3. } 10... Nxc5 11. Bxc6 { [%cal Gc6a8,Gc6d5,Gd1d5][%csl Ra8,Gc6,Rd5]White has won a pawn and it seems that Black's concept has failed. However, White is greatly behind in development - we are yet to castle and bring out our Queenside Knight. If White can finish developing and maintain the material advantage, then Black can soon resign. [--] Now, for several moves we must take care and defend precisely. } 11... Rb8 { Black moves the Rook out of danger, targeting our b2-pawn. } 12. Qxd5 $1 { [%cal Gd5d8][%csl Gd5,Rd8]We grab a second pawn! After all, the d5-pawn was a strong central pawn, why should we not take it? } 12... Qe7 $1 { [%cal Gf8d8,Gb8b2,Ge7c5][%csl Rb2]Black keeps the Queens on the board and is ready to bring more pieces into the game. } 13. O-O { We cannot be too greedy! We finish our development and humbly give back a pawn. } 13... Rxb2 { [%cal Gb2c2,Gf8d8,Gc8a6][%csl Rc2]Black takes back one of the sacrificed pawns and puts pressure on c2! They are ready to bring out their remaining forces. } 14. Nc3 $1 { [%cal Gd5d4,Gd4a7,Gc3d5,Gc6e8,Gc6a4,Gf1e1,Ge1e8][%csl Gc3,Rc5]We are not greedy! Development is key, we cannot hold on to our extra pawns while our pieces are sleeping. We bring the Knight into the game and are ready to make use of our active pieces. } 14... Rxc2 { Black fearlessly takes back the 2nd sacrificed pawn.This line is given by GM Sethuraman in his 1...e5 LTR. } 15. Qd4 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gd4a7,Gd4e5,Gd4c3,Gd4c5][%csl Gc3,Rc5]Defending our Knight while clearing the d5-square for one of our pieces to pounce on. } 15... Ne6 { [%cal Ge6d4][%csl Rd4,Ge6]Chasing our Queen back. } 16. Qd3 { [%cal Gd3c2,Gc3d5,Ga1c1,Gc1c7,Gc6e8,Gc6a4,Gc6f3,Gc6a8][%csl Rc2,Gc6,Gd3,Re8]We attack Black's Rook on c2, and after it moves to b2 we are ready to play Nd5 and take control over the c-file. The position is very complex, but I prefer White's chances with our more active pieces. } 16... Rb2 { Black moves the Rook from where it is under fire. We are still following Sethu's recommendation. } 17. Qe3 $5 { [%cal Ge3a7,Gc3d5,Ga1b1][%csl Rb2]A move not covered by GM Sethuraman. We are keeping an eye on the a7-pawn and are ready to play Nd5. } 17... Qc5 { [%cal Ge3c5][%csl Rc5,Ge3]A very logical move. Black seeks to trade Queens. I can see this move being played by the Sethuraman fans. } 18. Qxc5 { We are happy to oblige. } 18... Nxc5 19. Nd5 $5 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gf1b1,Gf1d1,Gd5c7][%csl Rb2,Rc7]White will be able to apply some pressure in this endgame. We have an eye on the c7-pawn, we can consider trading Rooks with Rfb1, and f4 to support the e5-pawn is another idea. White is not short on plans or ideas. } * 

