 Rc2]Black takes back one of the sacrificed pawns and puts pressure on c2! They are ready to bring out their remaining forces. } 14. Nc3 $1 { [%cal Gd5d4,Gd4a7,Gc3d5,Gc6e8,Gc6a4,Gf1e1,Ge1e8][%csl Gc3,Rc5]We are not greedy! Development is key, we cannot hold on to our extra pawns while our pieces are sleeping. We bring the Knight into the game and are ready to make use of our active pieces. } 14... Rd8 { Black activates the f8-Rook, pushing our Queen back. } 15. Qf3 { [%cal Gf3c6][%csl Gc6,Gd5,Gf3]The Queen heads back to f3 where it keeps an eye on both the c3-Knight and the c6-Bishop, while of course also helping in the fight for the d5-square. } 15... Rxc2 { [%cal Gc2c3][%csl Gc2,Rc3]Black evens out the material odds and is now ready to get some sort of piece coordination going. } 16. Rad1 $14 { [%cal Gd1d8,Gf3c6,Gc3d5][%csl Rc2,Gc3,Rc8,Gd1,Rd8,Re7]White brings the remaining Rook into the game. Pay close attention - material may be equal and nothing much may seem to be going on, but Black's pieces do not work well together! One of Black's Rooks is on d8 while the other one is somewhere in Timbuktu. Their Bishop is sleeping on c8 while our Bishop on c6, helping immoblize Black's position. In the only game that was played from this position, Black immediately made a huge blunder with } 16... Rcd2 $4 { Played by a 2100 FIDE elo player! } ( 16... Rcd2 { and after } 17. Nd5 $146 { he could resign. This shows how difficult the position is for Black. } ) 17. Nd5 $1 { [%cal Gc6d5,Gf3d5,Gd5e7,Gd1d2][%csl Rd2,Gd5,Re7,Gf3]Disturbing the connection between Black's Rooks! } 17... Qg5 { [%cal Gg5d2][%csl Rd2]} 18. Rxd2 { White trades Rooks with a strong idea in mind! } 18... Qxd2 19. Rd1 { [%cal Gd1d8,Gf3c6][%csl Gc6,Gd1,Rd2,Rd8,Gf3]Now the d8-Rook is exposed to a discovered check. Black loses material! } 19... Qg5 { [%cal Gg5d8]} 20. Nf6+ { [%cal Gd1d8,Gg7f6][%csl Rd8,Gf6,Rg8]POW! The final blow, the game is over! } * 

