1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 { Black develops the light-squared Bishop and awaits White's decision. } 8. Bxc6 $1 { The traditional Scotch gambit move! White gives up the light-squared Bishop in order to double Black's pawns and to speed up our own development. The Black Knight on c6 was also targeting the e5-pawn, so it we were obligated to eliminate it. } 8... bxc6 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Gd4,Rd5,Ge1,Ge5]Black's c-pawns are now doubled. However, do not be fooled! If these pawns can get mobile and Black stabilizes their position, these pawns can wreak havoc in White's position. In the Scotch gambit, the aim is very clear: White either fights against the doubled c-pawns or tries to give mate. } 9. O-O { In Scotch gambit style, White finishes development and prepares for the attack! Now } 9... c5 $6 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Gc5,Rd4,Gd5]Black kicks our Knight and advances the doubled pawn. However, these pawns can easily be targeted. } ( 9... Bc5 { is clearly the mainline and the most-played move by Black and will be discussed in the next chapter. However, we should be aware of } ) ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . } ) ( 9... c5 { is not so great, but } ) ( 9... Be7 { is a very solid move which, however, requires great precision from Black. } ) 10. Nb3 { [%cal Gd1d5][%csl Rd5]} 10... c4 $2 { [%cal Gc4b3][%csl Rb3,Gc4]Black tries to keep advancing, but misses something! } 11. Qxd5 $16 { [%cal Gd5e4,Gd5a8,Gc4b3,Ge4c2][%csl Ra8,Gc2,Gd5,Re4]White grabs a free pawn! } * 

