1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 { Black develops the light-squared Bishop and awaits White's decision. } 8. Bxc6 $1 { The traditional Scotch gambit move! White gives up the light-squared Bishop in order to double Black's pawns and to speed up our own development. The Black Knight on c6 was also targeting the e5-pawn, so it we were obligated to eliminate it. } 8... bxc6 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Gd4,Rd5,Ge1,Ge5]Black's c-pawns are now doubled. However, do not be fooled! If these pawns can get mobile and Black stabilizes their position, these pawns can wreak havoc in White's position. In the Scotch gambit, the aim is very clear: White either fights against the doubled c-pawns or tries to give mate. } 9. O-O { In Scotch gambit style, White finishes development and prepares for the attack! Now } 9... c5 $6 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Gc5,Rd4,Gd5]Black kicks our Knight and advances the doubled pawn. However, these pawns can easily be targeted. } ( 9... Bc5 { is clearly the mainline and the most-played move by Black and will be discussed in the next chapter. However, we should be aware of } ) ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . } ) ( 9... c5 { is not so great, but } ) ( 9... Be7 { is a very solid move which, however, requires great precision from Black. } ) 10. Nb3 { [%cal Gd1d5][%csl Rd5]} 10... c6 { [%csl Rc5,Rc6,Rd5]Black solidly defends their pawn center. White must now decide on a course of action. } 11. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Re4,Gf3]Kicking the Knight away. This is a typical Scotch gambit idea - the whole point of this move is that it wins a tempo in the attack. The Black Knight usually has nowhere to go except for g5, and after ...Ng5 White again advances with f4, attacking the Knight and forcing it back to e4. } 11... Ng5 12. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Gf4,Rg5]Chasing the Knight again! Now it has to return to e4 after which we have gained a tempo bringing our f-pawn into the attack. } 12... Ne4 13. Nc3 $1 { [%cal Gc3e4][%csl Gc3,Re4]A very thematic idea in the Scotch gambit! What is White doing??? Black already has doubled pawns and now we willingly allow them to double our own pawns, are we crazy? [--] No! By doubling our pawns, we actually slow down Black's central pawn mass and get more control over the center. After the Black center is slowed down, we will proceed with a full Kingside onslaught. } 13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 { [%cal Gc3d4,Gc2d3,Gd5d4,Gf4f5,Gc1e3,Ge3c5][%csl Gc3,Rc5,Re8]Now we see White's idea: the Black center is slowed down and White can freely continue with the Kingside onslaught with f5. } 14... c4 { [%cal Gc4b3][%csl Rb3,Rc4]Black tries to get going... } 15. Nd4 { [%csl Gd4]Moving the Knight to the center of the board, getting ready to transfer this soldier to the Kingside. } 15... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 16. Ne2 $16 { [%cal Gf4f5,Gc3d4,Ge2d4][%csl Gc2,Gc3]The Knight has completed its journey while Black's pawns have been halted. f5 is coming next. } * 

