s in order to slow down Black's central pawn mass and get our own pawns going on the Kingside! } 12... Nxc3 { After } ( 12... c5 13. Nb3 $146 { Black has to take on c3, which will transpose to 12...Nxc3. } ) 13. bxc3 { [%cal Gf4f5,Gc6c5,Gc3d4][%csl Gc2,Gc3]White is ready to continue the Kingside assault with f5! } 13... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]'An attack on the wing is best met by an attack in the center'. Therefore Black starts their central counterplay. } 14. Nb3 { [%cal Gc1e3,Gc1a3,Ga3e7][%csl Gb3,Gc5,Re7]We get the Knight out of the way. White is ready to storm through with f5, and we even have ideas such as Ba3 or Be3 in some scenarios. Therefore Black is forced to keep advancing in the center. } 14... c4 { [%cal Gc4b3][%csl Rb3,Rc4]Black keeps pushing their agenda. } 15. Nd4 { [%cal Gf4f5,Ge5e6][%csl Gd1,Gd4]White transfers the Knight back to the center, anticipating a shift to the Kingside! } 15... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]} 16. Ne2 { [%cal Ge2g3,Gf4f5,Gd1d5][%csl Rd5,Ge2]Black's antics have come to an end. Our Knight is now ready to be transferred to the Kingside, perhaps to g3 and then to f5. Black's pawn mass is kept at bay for now. } 16... Bc6 { [%cal Gc6h1][%csl Gc6]Black defends the d5-pawn and places the Bishop on a key diagonal. } 17. Ng3 $14 { [%cal Gg3f5,Gg7g6,Gd1e2,Gf4f5][%csl Rf5,Rg6]The Knight is coiled and ready to pounce on the f5 square with great effect. We have a very complex battle where Black has a lot of space in the center and, at the same time, White has a dangerous Kingside initiative. If Black plays } 17... g6 { , to prevent our Knight from coming to f5, we can proceed with } 18. Qe2 { , keeping an eye on the c4-pawn (in case Black wants to play ...d4). Then we can seek to break open the position with a timely f5. } * 

