e these two great assets in the position! We are playing real Barbaric chess here, we just want to crash through and bulldoze Black's position. } 12... Ne4 13. Nb3 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd1d5][%csl Gb3,Ge5,Gf5]A rare move, which will come as a surprise for our opponent! This is the third most popular move and it is no worse than the main move } ( 13. Nc3 $146 { . I may even argue that it is stronger! [--] With } ) ( 13. Nb3 $146 { we anticipate Black's ...c5 and already move the Knight out of the way and are ready to proceed with our development! } ) 13... a5 $5 { This move has not been played in any human games. This has only been seen in correspondence chess, so I would not be worried about this at all. It is not expected from your opponent, but we should still be aware of it. } 14. a4 { [%csl Ga4]We stop the a-pawn right in its tracks! } 14... Re8 { [%cal Ge8e5][%csl Re5]Black brings the Rook out, ready to put pressure on our e5-pawn! } 15. N1d2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]The Black Knight on e4 is too strong. We use our undeveloped Knight to trade it off! } 15... Bc5+ $1 { [%cal Gc5g1][%csl Rg1]This strange-looking move, giving up the strong dark-squared Bishop, has been played in all of the 9 correspondence games that have reached this position. Again we have the element of surprise! } 16. Nxc5 { [%csl Gc5]Of course we take the Bishop. } 16... Nxc5 17. b3 $40 { [%cal Ge8e5,Gf5f6,Gc1a3,Gc1b2][%csl Rc6,Rc7,Gd2,Rd7]I would recommend this move. The position is very rare and unique and requires some deeper exploration, but there is no need to dive too deep as the chances of getting this on the board are extremely small. Regardless, for a sense of completeness: if Black takes our e5-pawn with } 17... Rxe5 { , we continue with } 18. f6 { which breaks though on Black's Kingside. Afterwards we develop our Bishop to a3 or b2, exploiting the weak dark squares. A very complex fight lies ahead. } * 

