1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 { Black develops the light-squared Bishop and awaits White's decision. } 8. Bxc6 $1 { The traditional Scotch gambit move! White gives up the light-squared Bishop in order to double Black's pawns and to speed up our own development. The Black Knight on c6 was also targeting the e5-pawn, so it we were obligated to eliminate it. } 8... bxc6 { [%csl Rc6,Rc7,Gd4,Rd5,Ge1,Ge5]Black's c-pawns are now doubled. However, do not be fooled! If these pawns can get mobile and Black stabilizes their position, these pawns can wreak havoc in White's position. In the Scotch gambit, the aim is very clear: White either fights against the doubled c-pawns or tries to give mate. } 9. O-O { In Scotch gambit style, White finishes development and prepares for the attack! Now } 9... Be7 { [%cal Ge8g8,Gc6c5][%csl Rd4]Black humbly develops their Bishop and leaves room for the c6-pawn to advance. This is the second most popular move in the position and a very reasonable one! } ( 9... Bc5 { is clearly the mainline and the most-played move by Black and will be discussed in the next chapter. However, we should be aware of } ) ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . } ) ( 9... c5 { is not so great, but } ) ( 9... Be7 { is a very solid move which, however, requires great precision from Black. } ) 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Gd4,Re4,Gf3]A thematic Scotch gambit idea. We need to get our f-pawn going and use it as a battering ram against the Black King. } 10... Nc5 { Black keeps the Knight flexible on c5. } 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4f5][%csl Ge5,Gf4]The White pawn mass gets going! } 11... O-O { Black cooly castles and finishes their development. Here } ( 11... Ne4 $2 $146 12. Nc3 $146 { would transpose to the line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) 10...Ng5. } ) 12. f5 $1 { [%csl Ge5,Gf5,Rg8]The pawns are getting closer and closer! We have two bones in the throat of Black's position: e5 and f5. Black is feeling the pressure as we have these two great assets in the position! We are playing real Barbaric chess here, we just want to crash through and bulldoze Black's position. } 12... Ne4 13. Nb3 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd1d5][%csl Gb3,Ge5,Gf5]A rare move, which will come as a surprise for our opponent! This is the third most popular move and it is no worse than the main move } ( 13. Nc3 $146 { . I may even argue that it is stronger! [--] With } ) ( 13. Nb3 $146 { we anticipate Black's ...c5 and already move the Knight out of the way and are ready to proceed with our development! } ) 13... Re8 { [%cal Ge7f8,Ge8e5][%csl Re5]The expected move here and played by GM Le Quang Liem against Magnus Carlsen. Black is ready to go after the e5-pawn. } 14. N1d2 { [%cal Gd2e4,Gf1f5][%csl Gd2,Re4,Ge5,Gf5]Here we do not want to get doubled pawns with } ( 14. Nc3 $146 { as Black will simply take } 14... Nxc3 $146 15. bxc3 { and play } 15... Bf8 { . In that scenario the doubled pawns do not benefit us at all. Instead, we want to preserve our pawn structure while eliminating the powerful e4-Knight. } ) 14... Nxd2 $2 { Black cannot withstand the pressure and decides to immediately release the tension. } 15. Bxd2 $40 { [%cal Gd1g4,Gf5f6][%csl Gd2,Rf6,Rg7]Our development is now complete and we are ready to crash through on the Kingside, whether it be with f6 or with Qg4. } * 

