e these two great assets in the position! We are playing real Barbaric chess here, we just want to crash through and bulldoze Black's position. } 12... Ne4 13. Nb3 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd1d5][%csl Gb3,Ge5,Gf5]A rare move, which will come as a surprise for our opponent! This is the third most popular move and it is no worse than the main move } ( 13. Nc3 $146 { . I may even argue that it is stronger! [--] With } ) ( 13. Nb3 $146 { we anticipate Black's ...c5 and already move the Knight out of the way and are ready to proceed with our development! } ) 13... Re8 { [%cal Ge7f8,Ge8e5][%csl Re5]The expected move here and played by GM Le Quang Liem against Magnus Carlsen. Black is ready to go after the e5-pawn. } 14. N1d2 { [%cal Gd2e4,Gf1f5][%csl Gd2,Re4,Ge5,Gf5]Here we do not want to get doubled pawns with } ( 14. Nc3 $146 { as Black will simply take } 14... Nxc3 $146 15. bxc3 { and play } 15... Bf8 { . In that scenario the doubled pawns do not benefit us at all. Instead, we want to preserve our pawn structure while eliminating the powerful e4-Knight. } ) 14... Bf8 { [%cal Ge8e5][%csl Re5]Black opens the Rook and puts pressure on the e5-pawn. This was seen in the game of Magnus. } 15. Nxe4 { [%csl Ge4]Getting rid of the stupid e4-Knight - it was not welcome anymore! } 15... dxe4 16. Qd4 $5 { [%cal Gd4e5,Gd4e4,Gb3c5,Gd4c5][%csl Gd4,Re4,Ge5]A multi-functional move! We defend the e5-pawn and attack the e4-pawn. Black is now in the hot seat. } 16... Qe7 $5 { [%cal Ge8e5][%csl Re5]This was played by Le Quang Liem against Magnus. Black adds another attacker to the e5-pawn. } 17. f6 $1 { [%csl Re7,Rg7]White crashes through! Black is obliged to take. } 17... gxf6 18. exf6 { [%csl Gf6,Rg8]The pawn on f6 is a huge bone in the throat of Black! Their King is out in the open while their dark squares are screaming. } 18... Qd6 { [%cal Gd6d4][%csl Rd4,Gd6,Rg8]Black desperately begs to trade the Queens. However, with Black's open King and all their weaknesses, we keep the Queens on the board! } 19. Qf2 { [%cal Gf1f6]Like Tal, keep the Queens on the board for the attack! } 19... Qe5 { [%cal Ge4e3][%csl Ge5,Ge8]GM Carlsen - GM Liem, 2022. Black is ready to advance their only asset: the advanced e-pawn. } 20. Bf4 $1 { [%cal Ge5f6][%csl Re5,Gf4,Rf6]What? We are giving up our strong pawn on f6?? YES! As in the Scotch gambit, development is key! We cannot allow our Bishop on c1 to keep sleeping, we have to ring the Bishop out and the a1-Rook as well! Black's dark squares still remain weakened. Black's King is left for dead. } 20... Qxf6 21. Rae1 $14 { [%cal Ge1e3,Gb3c5,Ge3h3,Gf1f7,Gf4c7][%csl Gc5,Gf4,Rf7,Gg3,Rg8]Bringing our final piece into the game! The Rook can possibly swing to the Kingside with Re3 and we have other ideas such as Nc5. Black is on the edge and has to be very precise, while we get to enjoy the initiative. } * 

