1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1,Ge4f2,Ge8g8,Gd8e7,Ge7e5,Gf7f6][%csl Gc5,Re5]In the previous chapter we considered the sidelines } ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . Now we will consider the mainline of } ) ( 9... Bc5 { With this move, Black brings out the dark-squared Bishop to its most active square. Black is ready to castle and can then put pressure on the e5-pawn. A lot of fun is ahead! } ) 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Re4]By now we know this idea. It's a traditional Scotch gambit move! We chase Black's Knight from the center and are ready to gain a tempo, bringing our f-pawn into the attack. } 10... Ng5 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Ge5,Gf4,Rg5]The most concrete move, attacking the Knight again and supporting our center. } 11... Ne6 $6 { [%cal Ge6d4,Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]Black chooses another route. Instead of putting the Knight back on the strong e4 outpost, Black now pressures us on d4. } 12. c3 { [%cal Gc3d4,Gf4f5][%csl Gc3,Gc5,Rd4,Re6]A very cunning move! If Black takes on d4, our pawn will be firmly placed in the center. We are now ready to break Black with f5! } 12... O-O $4 { Black ignores our threat. } 13. f5 { [%cal Gf5e6,Ge6d4,Gc3d4,Gc5d4][%csl Gc3,Rd4,Re6,Gf5]After } 13... Nxd4 $146 14. cxd4 { our d4-pawn occupies a key central square. We have a free hand on the Kingside and our pawns serve as bones in the throat of Black's position! } * 

