1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1,Ge4f2,Ge8g8,Gd8e7,Ge7e5,Gf7f6][%csl Gc5,Re5]In the previous chapter we considered the sidelines } ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . Now we will consider the mainline of } ) ( 9... Bc5 { With this move, Black brings out the dark-squared Bishop to its most active square. Black is ready to castle and can then put pressure on the e5-pawn. A lot of fun is ahead! } ) 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Re4]By now we know this idea. It's a traditional Scotch gambit move! We chase Black's Knight from the center and are ready to gain a tempo, bringing our f-pawn into the attack. } 10... Ng5 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Ge5,Gf4,Rg5]The most concrete move, attacking the Knight again and supporting our center. } 11... Ne4 { Black's main option. The Knight goes back to the square it came from in the center. } 12. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb1d2][%csl Gd4,Ge3]This is the traditional Scotch gambit move. White develops the Bishop to e3 before bringing the Knight out to d2. In most cases White wants to play Nd2 next, trying to trade our undeveloped Knight for Black's strong central e4-Knight. } 12... Bb6 $5 { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd5d4][%csl Gb6,Re3]This is the most played move in the position, but that does not mean that it is the best move! Black wishes to advance ...c5 immediately and let the central pawn mass trample over White! } 13. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Development! Staying true to the principles of the Scotch gambit! We are ready to combat Black's advances and seek to trade their strong Knight. } 13... Nxd2 { Black does not want us to destroy their pawn structure even further by allowing us to take on e4, so they willingly part with the strong central Knight. } 14. Qxd2 { [%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge3]We recapture with the Queen, finishing our development. Now we are ready to proceed with some action. } 14... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]Black kicks us back and gets the central pawn mass going. This position has been reached in a large number of games. } 15. Nf3 { [%cal Gd2d5,Gf3g5,Gf3e5,Ga1d1,Ga2a4][%csl Rb6,Rd5,Gf3]The Knight comes to f3 where it has prospects in the center as well as the Kingside. } 15... d4 { [%cal Gd4e3][%csl Rb6,Rc4,Gd4,Re3]Black kicks back our pieces, but they must beware as they are creating many weaknesses in their own position! } 16. Bf2 { [%csl Rb6,Ge5,Gf2,Gf4]First of all, I want to draw your attention to Black's Bishop on b6! Just look at it... It is like a pawn - it has no function now other than defending the c5-pawn. We will try to keep this Bishop out of the game, after which we will have an extra piece in the attack. } 16... O-O { [%csl Rg8]Black decides to castle, believing that their King will be safe on the Kingside. However, we will rain terror on them! } 17. Bh4 { [%cal Gh4d8][%csl Rd8]We transfer the Bishop to the Kingside and chase Black's Queen! } 17... Qc8 { [%cal Gc8h3]} 18. a4 $5 { [%cal Ga4a5][%csl Ra5,Rb6]We threaten to trap the 'Bishop' on b6, even though it looks like a pawn already! } 18... a5 { [%csl Ra5,Rb6]Black stops the a-pawn in its tracks. } 19. c4 $14 { [%cal Gd4c3,Gd2c3,Gb2c3][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Gc4,Rc5,Rc7]With this move we seek to bury the b6-Bishop permanently! After Black takes } 19... dxc3 { we can capture with either the Queen or the pawn. In both cases Black is left with these awful doubled c-pawns which we can freely apply pressure to. } * 

