1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1,Ge4f2,Ge8g8,Gd8e7,Ge7e5,Gf7f6][%csl Gc5,Re5]In the previous chapter we considered the sidelines } ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . Now we will consider the mainline of } ) ( 9... Bc5 { With this move, Black brings out the dark-squared Bishop to its most active square. Black is ready to castle and can then put pressure on the e5-pawn. A lot of fun is ahead! } ) 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Re4]By now we know this idea. It's a traditional Scotch gambit move! We chase Black's Knight from the center and are ready to gain a tempo, bringing our f-pawn into the attack. } 10... Ng5 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Ge5,Gf4,Rg5]The most concrete move, attacking the Knight again and supporting our center. } 11... Ne4 { Black's main option. The Knight goes back to the square it came from in the center. } 12. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb1d2][%csl Gd4,Ge3]This is the traditional Scotch gambit move. White develops the Bishop to e3 before bringing the Knight out to d2. In most cases White wants to play Nd2 next, trying to trade our undeveloped Knight for Black's strong central e4-Knight. } 12... Qe7 $6 { A very strange move which has been played in more than 100 games! Instead of castling or making a strong threat, Black brings the Queen to e7... } 13. Nd2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Our typical move move. If Black castles then we will take on e4 and simply play Qe2, finishing our development. } 13... Nxd2 { Black releases the tension in the center. } 14. Qxd2 { [%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge3,Ge5,Gf4]Just look at how harmoniously our pieces are working together! } 14... O-O { Black finishes their development. } 15. Nb3 $16 { [%cal Ge3c5,Ga1e1,Gd2c3][%csl Gb3,Rc5,Gd2,Ge3]A thematic idea which gives White a decent advantage! We seek to trade the dark-squared Bishops and take control over the c5-square. After the Bishops are traded, the weakness of Black's doubled c-pawns will truly be felt as they are static and unable to move while White will strike on the Kingside. Black is best advised to keep the Bishops on the board with } 15... Bb6 { . In that scenario, White can simply bring the Queenside Rook into the game with } 16. Rae1 { , possibly followed by Qc3 to continue the fight for the c5-square. } * 

