is one of the biggest moves of the course!! It has been played in only 4 games out of a few hundred games with 12...Qb8, one of the crucial games in this variation being my own! } ( 13. Qd3 { is a very mysterious move, as moving the Queen to d3 is not a move that comes to anyone's human mind I would argue! The main idea of the move is that we want to bring our Knight to d2 and force Black's e4-Knight to evacuate. [--] If we would start with } ) ( 13. Nd2 $146 { or } ) ( 13. Nc3 $146 { , Black takes } 13... Qxb2 { and we wouldn't have any reasonable way to increase the pressure on the e4-Knight. This Knight is the pride of Black's position and we are ready to give up the b2-pawn and continue with Nd2 next to get rid of it. } ) 13... O-O { This is not the most natural move, and it has not been played in any game so far. The idea of 12...Qb8 was to snatch the pawn on b2 - what is the point if White offered that pawn and Black did not accept it? The move } ( 13... O-O { shows that Black is not a real chess player, he is a coward and not a man of his word. However, } ) ( 13... O-O { is not a bad move, and we should still be aware of what to do. } ) 14. Nc3 $5 { [%cal Gc3e4][%csl Gc3,Gd3,Re4]I would say that this move is more accurate than } ( 14. Nd2 $146 { because with } ) ( 14. Nc3 $146 { we give Black less options. If we play } ) ( 14. Nd2 $146 { , Black would be able to take on d2. However, after } ) ( 14. Nc3 $146 { , exchanging on c3 is not favorable for Black at all! } ) 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 $5 { [%cal Gf4f5,Gf7f6,Gg1h1,Gf1e1][%csl Rb8,Gc2,Gc3]A great dynamic decision! Now the Queen on b8 really feels misplaced as it has no target on the b-file, while White is ready to proceed with f5 next and start the Kingside onslaught. If Black plays } 15... f6 { we have a different way to proceed: } 16. Rfe1 { supporting the future passed pawn is one idea, or even } ( 16. Kh1 { , simply getting out of the pin. } ) * 

