es but it is impossible to cover everything. Not to mention, we can always continue with our typical ideas: Kh1, stepping out of the pin, Nb3 trying to trade Bishops, f5 to continue the Kingside attack, and we can bring our Rooks to any of the open files. We should always keep these ideas in mind and decide move by move which one is the best. } 17. Bxd4 { [%cal Gd4b2][%csl Rb2,Gd4]It seems that Black is in great trouble now as their Queen is under fire. } 17... Bf5 $1 { [%cal Gf5e4,Gb2c2][%csl Rc2,Re4]The key point. This is a great deflection tactic that keeps Black in the game! } 18. Qxf5 { Allowing the trade. } 18... Qxd4+ { [%cal Gd4g1][%csl Rg1]} 19. Kh1 $14 { [%cal Gh2h3,Gd4g1][%csl Gc2,Rc6,Rc7,Ge5,Gf4,Rf7,Gg2,Rg7,Gh2,Rh7]Objectively Black is very close to equality. However, we have a much more pleasant position to play as Black is left with the doubled c-pawns while we have a 4v3 situation on the Kingside and still some chances to stir up an attack on that side of the board. Next we can perhaps continue with h3, making some space for our King, and then bring the Rooks into the game. } * 

