is one of the biggest moves of the course!! It has been played in only 4 games out of a few hundred games with 12...Qb8, one of the crucial games in this variation being my own! } ( 13. Qd3 { is a very mysterious move, as moving the Queen to d3 is not a move that comes to anyone's human mind I would argue! The main idea of the move is that we want to bring our Knight to d2 and force Black's e4-Knight to evacuate. [--] If we would start with } ) ( 13. Nd2 $146 { or } ) ( 13. Nc3 $146 { , Black takes } 13... Qxb2 { and we wouldn't have any reasonable way to increase the pressure on the e4-Knight. This Knight is the pride of Black's position and we are ready to give up the b2-pawn and continue with Nd2 next to get rid of it. } ) 13... Qxb2 { [%cal Gb2a1][%csl Ra1,Gb2]Why should Black not take the pawn? After all, that was the whole point behind the ...Qb8 maneuver. } 14. Nd2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Development! White is now ready to get rid of the strong e4-Knight. Black is yet to castle and their Queen is in an awkward position. } 14... Nxd2 { This has been played in all games so far, even against me by the strong International Master who I crushed with ease. The move } ( 14... O-O { is something we've already seen. After } 15. Nxe4 $146 { we transpose to the line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) 13...O-O 14.Nc3 Qxb2 15.Nxe4. } ) 15. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gf4f5][%csl Rb2,Rc5,Gd2,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4]We arrive at a very interesting position! White is down a pawn but Black's Queen is awkwardly placed and could easily be trapped if Black is not careful. Meanwhile, White can still carry out an assault on the Kingside with the move f5, which is a default move in the Scotch gambit. I would take White any day here. Black has only one plan... To survive! Whereas our goal is very clear: we try to harass Black's Queen and storm the Kingside! [--] There have been only 3 tournament games in this position, from which White has scored 2.5/3. In the game where Black made a draw, he actually had a losing position from the opening. This speaks volumes for the line. I was the real hero in this variation, as my game is a model game and it paved the way for this Scotch gambit line to be revived. } 15... Bb4 $6 { [%cal Gb4d2,Gc6c5][%csl Rd2]A strange move, but one that was played by IM N.Salimova against young Grandmaster Maurizzi from France. Black clears the way for the c-pawn to advance. } 16. Qf2 { [%cal Gf2c5,Gf2g3,Gg3g7][%csl Re8,Gg3,Rg7]We get out of the way of Bishop's attack, to the very nice square of f2, and possibly hint at coming to the Kingside! } 16... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]Black follows up with their plan! } 17. Nb3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb3c5][%csl Gb3,Rc5,Ge3,Gf2]Exerting great pressure on the c5-pawn. Now the Black Queen is feeling very short of squares. } 17... d4 $5 { [%csl Gd4,Re3]This was not played in the mentioned game, but it is a very logical continuation! Black kicks our Bishop and advances their central pawn. } 18. Bc1 { [%cal Gc1b2][%csl Rb2,Gc1]Kicking Black's Queen with tempo and forcing it to the c3-square where it can later run into a timely Bd2. } 18... Qc3 19. a3 { [%cal Ga3b4][%csl Rb4]Black's Bishop is short of squares! The move } ( 19. f5 { is slightly preferred by the engine, but it is very complex and Black has a lot of chances to lead us astray there. Meanwhile, after } ) ( 19. a3 { Black has to find a difficult defense and still has to stay on their toes! } ) 19... c4 { [%cal Gc4b3,Gc3a1][%csl Ra1,Rb3,Gc4,Gd4]Black finds the best reply, counter-attacking our Knight and opening up the diagonal for their Bishop! } ( 19... Ba5 { would of course lose a piece after } 20. Bd2 { . } ) 20. Bd2 $5 { [%cal Gd2b4][%csl Rb4,Gd2]This forces Black's Queen to take on c2. Now a forcing sequence follows which Black has to calculate from afar. I can see all of your opponents at this point shaking at fear! I mean, come on: Black's Bishop is hanging, the Queen is in no-man's land, and Black's King is yet to castle. Chess should not be played this way. } 20... Qxc2 21. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4c2,Ga3b4][%csl Ga3,Rb4,Rc2,Gd4]We take Black's key central pawn and invite them to take on d2. } 21... Qxd2 22. axb4 { [%csl Gb4]We capture Black's strong dark-squared Bishop. } 22... Qxf2+ $6 { Black follows the age-old rule of trading while being up in material. However, this is a grave mistake. } 23. Kxf2 $14 { [%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c4,Ga1a7,Gb4a5,Gb4c5][%csl Ra7,Gb4,Gc1,Rc4,Rc7,Gf2]Our King is nicely centralized. We will bring our Rook to c1 next and win the c4-pawn. Our Knight is nicely centralized as well, and we will have pleasant pressure on a7 and c7. } * 

