 should not be played this way. } 20... Qxc2 21. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4c2,Ga3b4][%csl Ga3,Rb4,Rc2,Gd4]We take Black's key central pawn and invite them to take on d2. } 21... Qxd2 22. axb4 { [%csl Gb4]We capture Black's strong dark-squared Bishop. } 22... Qxb4 { Black fearlessly grabs the pawn. } 23. f5 $40 { [%cal Gf1f8,Ga1a8,Gb1b8][%csl Ga1,Rc4,Rc7,Gd4,Ge5,Re8,Gf5]We are down two pawns here, but the computer gives an equal evaluation. What does that mean? To be down 2 pawns, which are usually worth 2 points but being given an equal evaluation means that our dynamic factors and our attack are too strong! We are ready to crack open Black's King with ideas such as e6 or f6. After Black castles with } 23... O-O { we will proceed with } 24. f6 { and try to mate Black on the dark squares. My students, play valiantly, fearlessly and go out to war! } * 

