draw, he actually had a losing position from the opening. This speaks volumes for the line. I was the real hero in this variation, as my game is a model game and it paved the way for this Scotch gambit line to be revived. } 15... Bb4 $6 { [%cal Gb4d2,Gc6c5][%csl Rd2]A strange move, but one that was played by IM N.Salimova against young Grandmaster Maurizzi from France. Black clears the way for the c-pawn to advance. } 16. Qf2 { [%cal Gf2c5,Gf2g3,Gg3g7][%csl Re8,Gg3,Rg7]We get out of the way of Bishop's attack, to the very nice square of f2, and possibly hint at coming to the Kingside! } 16... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]Black follows up with their plan! } 17. Nb3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb3c5][%csl Gb3,Rc5,Ge3,Gf2]Exerting great pressure on the c5-pawn. Now the Black Queen is feeling very short of squares. } 17... Bf5 { [%cal Gf5c2,Gf2c5,Gb3c5,Gb2c3][%csl Rc2,Rc5]This was how IM Salimova played against GM Maurizzi. Already White has a great advantage of over +1 in computer terms. However, we are much stronger than the computer, as we are powerful human beings with souls, hearts, spirits and brains unlike any other. We cannot trust these deceitful machines! [--] With 17...Bf5 Black is putting pressure on c2, but we have a very strong reply in store! } 18. a3 $3 { [%csl Ga3,Rb4]This move was missed by GM Maurizzi. However, if you have bought this course, you will most certainly not miss it! We pose a very crucial question to Black's Bishop which does not have many squares to go to! Also, our pawn on a3 is very much poisoned! } 18... Bxa3 19. Bc1 $3 { [%cal Gc1a3,Gb3a1][%csl Ga1,Ra3,Rb2]With this backwards move we now win the Bishop and the game! } * 

