is one of the biggest moves of the course!! It has been played in only 4 games out of a few hundred games with 12...Qb8, one of the crucial games in this variation being my own! } ( 13. Qd3 { is a very mysterious move, as moving the Queen to d3 is not a move that comes to anyone's human mind I would argue! The main idea of the move is that we want to bring our Knight to d2 and force Black's e4-Knight to evacuate. [--] If we would start with } ) ( 13. Nd2 $146 { or } ) ( 13. Nc3 $146 { , Black takes } 13... Qxb2 { and we wouldn't have any reasonable way to increase the pressure on the e4-Knight. This Knight is the pride of Black's position and we are ready to give up the b2-pawn and continue with Nd2 next to get rid of it. } ) 13... Qxb2 { [%cal Gb2a1][%csl Ra1,Gb2]Why should Black not take the pawn? After all, that was the whole point behind the ...Qb8 maneuver. } 14. Nd2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Development! White is now ready to get rid of the strong e4-Knight. Black is yet to castle and their Queen is in an awkward position. } 14... Nxd2 { This has been played in all games so far, even against me by the strong International Master who I crushed with ease. The move } ( 14... O-O { is something we've already seen. After } 15. Nxe4 $146 { we transpose to the line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) 13...O-O 14.Nc3 Qxb2 15.Nxe4. } ) 15. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gf4f5][%csl Rb2,Rc5,Gd2,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4]We arrive at a very interesting position! White is down a pawn but Black's Queen is awkwardly placed and could easily be trapped if Black is not careful. Meanwhile, White can still carry out an assault on the Kingside with the move f5, which is a default move in the Scotch gambit. I would take White any day here. Black has only one plan... To survive! Whereas our goal is very clear: we try to harass Black's Queen and storm the Kingside! [--] There have been only 3 tournament games in this position, from which White has scored 2.5/3. In the game where Black made a draw, he actually had a losing position from the opening. This speaks volumes for the line. I was the real hero in this variation, as my game is a model game and it paved the way for this Scotch gambit line to be revived. } 15... Rb8 { [%cal Gb8b2][%csl Gb8,Re8]This stupid move was played by a 2100-rated player in a serious tournament. You see: Black was surprised by the move 13.Qd3 and immediately blunders a few moves later. The computer gives an eval of over +1 already. } 16. f5 $1 { [%cal Ge5e6][%csl Rb2,Rb8,Gd2,Gd4,Ge3,Ge5,Re8,Gf1,Gf5]The household Scotch gambit move! We want to break open the entire position with e6 and catch Black's King in the center! } 16... O-O { [%csl Rg8]Black decided to get their King to 'safety'. There is no safety in the Scotch gambit - the Black King is condemed to death! } 17. a3 $1 { [%cal Ga3b4,Gb8e8,Gf1b1][%csl Rb2,Rb4]A move that is worth remembering! This is a very subtle move and perhaps not so easy to understand. [--] Now that Black has castled, ...Rb4 might very well be an idea on Black's agenda, and the b4-square is very crucial in general as the Black Queen can later escape via b4. [--] The a3-pawn takes away some crucial squares from Black's pieces and it is ill advised for Black to take that pawn! } 17... Bxa3 18. Qf2 $18 { [%cal Gf5f6,Gf2g3][%csl Ra3,Rb2,Rb8,Gf2,Rg7,Rg8]Black will soon get mated with all of their pieces on the wrong side of the board while we are coming for the King! The main threat is f6, followed by trying to give mate on g7. } * 

