1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1,Ge4f2,Ge8g8,Gd8e7,Ge7e5,Gf7f6][%csl Gc5,Re5]In the previous chapter we considered the sidelines } ( 9... c5 { and } ) ( 9... Be7 { . Now we will consider the mainline of } ) ( 9... Bc5 { With this move, Black brings out the dark-squared Bishop to its most active square. Black is ready to castle and can then put pressure on the e5-pawn. A lot of fun is ahead! } ) 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4][%csl Re4]By now we know this idea. It's a traditional Scotch gambit move! We chase Black's Knight from the center and are ready to gain a tempo, bringing our f-pawn into the attack. } 10... Ng5 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Ge5,Gf4,Rg5]The most concrete move, attacking the Knight again and supporting our center. } 11... Ne4 { Black's main option. The Knight goes back to the square it came from in the center. } 12. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb1d2][%csl Gd4,Ge3]This is the traditional Scotch gambit move. White develops the Bishop to e3 before bringing the Knight out to d2. In most cases White wants to play Nd2 next, trying to trade our undeveloped Knight for Black's strong central e4-Knight. } 12... Qb8 $1 { [%cal Gb8b2][%csl Rb2]This move is considered the modern mainline and the 'refutation' of the Scotch gambit, and is clearly the best according to the computer. White has been unable to find a valid way to pose problems here - until now! Your saviour is here! [--] I have found a very rare move which is strongly backed by the engine which gives us the winning chances that we need. I have already crushed a strong International Master in a classical tournament with this idea, and now I am ready to pass on my secret knowledge! With } ( 12... Qb8 { Black attacks our b2-pawn and forces us to either weaken with } 13. b3 { or to sacrifice the pawn with } ( 13. Nc3 $146 { . Black's Queen is activated in a very curious way on the Queenside. } ) ) 13. Qd3 $5 { [%cal Gd3e4,Gb8b2][%csl Rb2,Gd3]This is one of the biggest moves of the course!! It has been played in only 4 games out of a few hundred games with 12...Qb8, one of the crucial games in this variation being my own! } ( 13. Qd3 { is a very mysterious move, as moving the Queen to d3 is not a move that comes to anyone's human mind I would argue! The main idea of the move is that we want to bring our Knight to d2 and force Black's e4-Knight to evacuate. [--] If we would start with } ) ( 13. Nd2 $146 { or } ) ( 13. Nc3 $146 { , Black takes } 13... Qxb2 { and we wouldn't have any reasonable way to increase the pressure on the e4-Knight. This Knight is the pride of Black's position and we are ready to give up the b2-pawn and continue with Nd2 next to get rid of it. } ) 13... Qxb2 { [%cal Gb2a1][%csl Ra1,Gb2]Why should Black not take the pawn? After all, that was the whole point behind the ...Qb8 maneuver. } 14. Nd2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Development! White is now ready to get rid of the strong e4-Knight. Black is yet to castle and their Queen is in an awkward position. } 14... Nxd2 { This has been played in all games so far, even against me by the strong International Master who I crushed with ease. The move } ( 14... O-O { is something we've already seen. After } 15. Nxe4 $146 { we transpose to the line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) 13...O-O 14.Nc3 Qxb2 15.Nxe4. } ) 15. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gf4f5][%csl Rb2,Rc5,Gd2,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4]We arrive at a very interesting position! White is down a pawn but Black's Queen is awkwardly placed and could easily be trapped if Black is not careful. Meanwhile, White can still carry out an assault on the Kingside with the move f5, which is a default move in the Scotch gambit. I would take White any day here. Black has only one plan... To survive! Whereas our goal is very clear: we try to harass Black's Queen and storm the Kingside! [--] There have been only 3 tournament games in this position, from which White has scored 2.5/3. In the game where Black made a draw, he actually had a losing position from the opening. This speaks volumes for the line. I was the real hero in this variation, as my game is a model game and it paved the way for this Scotch gambit line to be revived. } 15... O-O { [%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge3]The mainline and the top engine choice! I am very proud to say that there are only 2 games here and only ONE HUMAN GAME WHICH IS MY OWN GAME!! I was up against a 2375 FIDE rated International Master, Bai Aderlad, and I crushed him with ease in just a couple of moves from this position! Just to be clear that I practice what I preach! This Chessable course was in the making for a long time, and before it was released to the public I had my fair share of striking down titled players with the Scotch gambit! } 16. a3 $3 { [%cal Gf1b1,Ga3b4,Gb2b4,Gd2a5][%csl Ga3,Rb2,Gd2,Ge3]This move sets Black an impossible choice! We threaten to trap Black's Queen with Rfb1, and Black now has to decide where to move the lady. Any Rook move to b8 will just be bad, as we storm through with the typical f5. } 16... Qb7 $5 { A very strange move to explain. What is the Queen doing on b7? } ( 16... Qb6 { is clearly more natural, and even b8 could be argued, but but b7?? [--] The whole point of } ) ( 16... Qb7 { is that Black actually wants to retreat the Bishop to b6 and then play ...c5. Their Queen on b7 can then come to life. [--] This move has just been played in one correspondence game, so it is highly unlikely that you'll ever see it... } ) 17. Nb3 $5 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gb3c5,Gd2e3][%csl Rd7,Ge3]Not the only move, but I believe this is a very logical path without taking unnecessary risks! We simply want to trade Black's strong dark-squared Bishop and contest their light-squared Bishop with our Knight! The move } ( 17. f5 { is also possible instead of } ) ( 17. Nb3 $146 { but it involves certain risks. You can explore it on your own. } ) 17... Bb6 $5 { [%cal Ga7b6,Ge3b6]Black only wishes to trade Bishops on their own terms. } 18. Nc5 $14 { [%cal Gc5d7,Gc5b7,Gh2h3,Gg2g4][%csl Rb7,Gc5,Gd2,Rd7,Ge3]Black will eventually have to take on c5, after which we will have a very strong dark-squared Bishop and a free hand to continue the attack on the Kingside. We can even consider ideas such as h3 to expand with g4 in these positions if our King is out of any sort of danger. } * 

