uter gives all zeros here, but it is a very complex position. It is much easier to play for White, as we have a clear goal: to give mate! Meanwhile, Black just has to find a way to survive and avoid being mated. [--] We are ready to continue with f5 and bring our Knight to the center. We are down a pawn but it is not felt, as Black's Queen is far from the action and we have a free hand on the Kingside. This seems like an excellent outcome to me: we can freely try to mate Black while they have to defend and if they are successful, they might achieve a draw. If Black plays } 18... Bf5 { , we have } 19. Nd4 $146 { , centralizing the Knight and then continuing with f5. If 18\. Qxe3 18...Qb6 , offering to trade Queens, we will keep Queens on the board with 19.Nc5 . } * 

