is one of the biggest moves of the course!! It has been played in only 4 games out of a few hundred games with 12...Qb8, one of the crucial games in this variation being my own! } ( 13. Qd3 { is a very mysterious move, as moving the Queen to d3 is not a move that comes to anyone's human mind I would argue! The main idea of the move is that we want to bring our Knight to d2 and force Black's e4-Knight to evacuate. [--] If we would start with } ) ( 13. Nd2 $146 { or } ) ( 13. Nc3 $146 { , Black takes } 13... Qxb2 { and we wouldn't have any reasonable way to increase the pressure on the e4-Knight. This Knight is the pride of Black's position and we are ready to give up the b2-pawn and continue with Nd2 next to get rid of it. } ) 13... Qxb2 { [%cal Gb2a1][%csl Ra1,Gb2]Why should Black not take the pawn? After all, that was the whole point behind the ...Qb8 maneuver. } 14. Nd2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Development! White is now ready to get rid of the strong e4-Knight. Black is yet to castle and their Queen is in an awkward position. } 14... Nxd2 { This has been played in all games so far, even against me by the strong International Master who I crushed with ease. The move } ( 14... O-O { is something we've already seen. After } 15. Nxe4 $146 { we transpose to the line (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) 13...O-O 14.Nc3 Qxb2 15.Nxe4. } ) 15. Qxd2 { [%cal Ge3c5,Gf4f5][%csl Rb2,Rc5,Gd2,Gd4,Ge5,Gf4]We arrive at a very interesting position! White is down a pawn but Black's Queen is awkwardly placed and could easily be trapped if Black is not careful. Meanwhile, White can still carry out an assault on the Kingside with the move f5, which is a default move in the Scotch gambit. I would take White any day here. Black has only one plan... To survive! Whereas our goal is very clear: we try to harass Black's Queen and storm the Kingside! [--] There have been only 3 tournament games in this position, from which White has scored 2.5/3. In the game where Black made a draw, he actually had a losing position from the opening. This speaks volumes for the line. I was the real hero in this variation, as my game is a model game and it paved the way for this Scotch gambit line to be revived. } 15... O-O { [%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge3]The mainline and the top engine choice! I am very proud to say that there are only 2 games here and only ONE HUMAN GAME WHICH IS MY OWN GAME!! I was up against a 2375 FIDE rated International Master, Bai Aderlad, and I crushed him with ease in just a couple of moves from this position! Just to be clear that I practice what I preach! This Chessable course was in the making for a long time, and before it was released to the public I had my fair share of striking down titled players with the Scotch gambit! } 16. a3 $3 { [%cal Gf1b1,Ga3b4,Gb2b4,Gd2a5][%csl Ga3,Rb2,Gd2,Ge3]This move sets Black an impossible choice! We threaten to trap Black's Queen with Rfb1, and Black now has to decide where to move the lady. Any Rook move to b8 will just be bad, as we storm through with the typical f5. } 16... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6a6,Gb6g1][%csl Gb6,Gc5]Played against me by IM Bai. Black moves the Queen to the most natural square, supporting the Bishop. The Queen can safely come to a6 in some positions. } 17. Qc3 $3 { [%cal Gc3c5,Gf1b1][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Rc5]A very powerful concept! With this move we paralyze Black's Bishop and Queen. Black cannot move the c5-Bishop as there will be a fatal discovered attack on their Queen, and they cannot move the Queen as it would drop the Bishop. With our Rook coming to b1, things are looking very grim for Black. } 17... a5 { [%cal Gb6a7][%csl Ga5,Ga7]Making space for the Queen to retreat to a7 to keep an eye on the Bishop. } 18. Kh1 $40 { [%cal Ge5e6,Gf7e6,Gd4e6,Gc3g7,Gg1b6][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Rc5,Rg7,Gh1]This is the move I found during my game! White is setting up the nasty threat of e6, so first our King safely steps away from any checks and pins on the a7-g1 diagonal. The move e6 is now threatened - when Black recaptures we will recapture on e6 with the Knight, attacking the c5-Bishop and threatening mate on g7 at the same time, while Black cannot take on e3 with check! This is a small but very important detail! [--] In the game, the International master immediately collapsed. Black parted with the powerful dark-squared Bishop as he did not see how to stop the e6 threat. } 18... Bxd4 { A very sad move to make, played against me by IM Bai. } 19. Bxd4 { [%cal Gc3g7,Gd4b6][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Gd4,Rg7]} 19... Qb5 20. e6 $18 { [%cal Gc3g7][%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rd7,Ge6,Rg7,Rg8]After this move we will take on g7 and then start a mating attack. Black's King will be out in the open and left for dead, all the dark squares will be weakened and their King's shelter will be destroyed. This happened in my game (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) and I made quick work of my opponent. } * 

