{ This game was played in a Grandmaster norm tournament in Hungary where I was up against IM Bai, Adelard, who was FIDE-rated 2375 at the time. Here the full fury of the Scotch gambit was released on him. I dropped my special recipe with the 13.Qd3 move and 12 moves after that... He had to resign. Ladies and gentlemen, this is simply what the Scotch gambit does! } 1. e4 { [%csl Ge4]The real warrior move. } 1... e5 { After this course you will have the biggest smile on your face when you see this move. } 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gf3e5][%csl Re5,Gf3]} 2... Nc6 { [%cal Gc6e5,Gf3e5][%csl Gc6]In this game, I chose another move order to reach the Scotch gambit. } 3. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7][%csl Rf7]} 3... Nf6 4. d4 $1 { [%cal Gd4e5][%csl Gd4,Re5]Getting back to the Scotch gambit! } 4... exd4 5. e5 { [%cal Ge5f6][%csl Ge5,Rf6]} 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4,Gd5,Ge5]The typical counter-attacking move. } 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8][%csl Rc6]} 6... Ne4 7. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd4c6][%csl Rc6,Gd4]} 7... Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6,Gb7c6]Black solidly defends his knight. } 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 { [%cal Gc5g1]This can be considered the mainline, which is covered in great detail in the course. } 10. f3 { [%cal Gf3e4,Gc5g1][%csl Re4,Ge5,Gf3]The standard routine, kicking the Knight and then gaining a tempo! } 10... Ng5 11. f4 { [%cal Gf4g5][%csl Gf4,Rg5]The Knight is forced back to the center while we have added strength to our e5-pawn. } 11... Ne4 12. Be3 { [%cal Ge3d4][%csl Gd4,Ge3]} 12... Qb8 { [%cal Gb8b2][%csl Rb2]The so called modern day 'refutation' of the Scotch gambit, but look here at this game! Only a dozen or so moves later, my opponent had to resign... I have revived the Scotch gambit, I have brought it back to life, the Scotch gambit stands tall once again! } 13. Qd3 $1 { [%csl Gd3]A hidden treasure of a move that is analyzed deeply in the course! } 13... Qxb2 14. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2e4,Gf4f5][%csl Rb2,Gd2,Gd4,Re4,Ge5,Re8,Gf4]We have sacrificed a pawn for better development and the initiative! } 14... Nxd2 15. Qxd2 { [%csl Gd2]} 15... O-O 16. a3 { [%cal Gf1b1,Ga3b4,Gb2a3][%csl Ra3]A very innovative move that puts Black's Queen in a hot spot! } 16... Qb6 17. Qc3 { [%cal Gc3c5][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Rc5]A supreme move! We prevent Black from moving either their Queen or their c5-Bishop. } 17... a5 18. Kh1 { [%cal Gc5e3,Ge5e6,Gf7e6,Gd4e6,Gc3g7,Ge3c5][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Rc5,Re3,Rg7,Gh1]The move of the game, which caused Black to immediately collapse! Now e6 is a very big threat! } 18... Bxd4 { A very sad move to make. } 19. Bxd4 { [%cal Gc3d4][%csl Rb6,Gc3,Gd4]} 19... Qb5 20. e6 { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Rd7,Ge6,Rg7,Rg8]Completely opening up the Black King. The rest of the game was just a murder scene. } 20... fxe6 21. Bxg7 $18 { [%csl Gc3,Gg7,Rg8]Black has an awful bishop on d7 while our bishop cuts all the squares around his king. Look at how I put my own suggested lines into practice! } 21... Rf7 22. Be5 c5 23. Qh3 Kf8 24. Rf3 Rb8 25. Rb3 1-0 

