{ This game was played by me in 2016, at which point I was a 1809 rated player. Of course, now I am an International Master. The point of this game is to show you that the Scotch gambit has been part of my career for a long time. Even from my club player days I used to play this opening. Unfortunately a lot of my games were never entered into the datasbase and I am not able to remember or find them, but this is one of the games that I could still retrieve. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { [%cal Gd4e5][%csl Gd4,Re5,Gf3]The real Scotch gambit move-order! } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7][%csl Gc4,Rf7]} 4... Bb4+ { [%cal Gb4e1][%csl Gb4,Re1]This is the computer's greedy approach. } 5. c3 { [%cal Gc3b4][%csl Rb4,Gc3]} 5... dxc3 6. bxc3 { [%cal Gc3b4][%csl Rb4,Gc3]In the course I recommend } ( 6. O-O { . I'm sure that at the time of the game I hadn't deeply analyzed the move 4...Bb4+ yet. } ) 6... Ba5 7. O-O { Following the principles of the gambit and speedily developing. } 7... Nge7 $2 { A very natural move and already a mistake. This shows the danger of the Scotch gambit! } 8. Ng5 { [%cal Gg5f7,Gc4f7,Ge8g8,Gd1h5][%csl Rf7]Pouncing on the attack! } 8... Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4,Ge5f7][%csl Rc4]Here my 1800-rated self missed a typical Scotch gambit tactic. } 9. Bb3 $6 { [%csl Gb3]Missing the chance! } ( 9. Nxf7 $3 $146 Nxf7 $146 10. Bxf7+ Kxf7 11. Qh5+ { wins back the piece while Black's King is out in the open. } ) 9... O-O { Another very natural move, but a huge mistake. The computer suggests the crazy move } ( 9... d5 { for Black to stay in the game. } ) 10. f4 $1 { [%cal Gf4e5][%csl Re5,Gf4]Kicking back the Knight! } 10... Bb6+ { [%cal Gb6g1]} 11. Kh1 N5g6 12. Qh5 $3 { [%cal Gb3f7,Gg5h7,Gh5h7][%csl Rf7,Gg5,Gh5,Rh7]Black's position completely falls apart now. } 12... h6 13. Nxf7 $1 { [%cal Gb3g8][%csl Rf7,Rg8]Blowing open the position. } 13... Rxf7 14. Bxf7+ Kxf7 15. f5 { [%cal Gf5g6,Gf1f7][%csl Rf7,Rg6]We win back the Knight and will be up the exchange. Black is totally lost. The rest of the game is not important. This game was to simply show you how the usual battle in the Scotch gambit goes between club-level players. And also that I have been playing the Scotch gambit for a very long time. } 15... Kg8 16. fxg6 Qe8 17. Ba3 d6 18. e5 Qb5 19. Nd2 Qd3 20. exd6 cxd6 21. Qf3 Qxf3 22. Nxf3 Nxg6 23. Bxd6 Be6 24. Ne5 Nxe5 25. Bxe5 Bd5 26. Bd4 Bxd4 27. cxd4 Rd8 28. a3 Bc4 29. Rfd1 Rd5 30. Rac1 b5 31. Kg1 Rf5 32. d5 Rf8 33. d6 Rd8 34. Kf2 Kf7 35. Rc3 Ke6 36. Re3+ Kd7 37. Re7+ Kc6 38. Rxa7 { Black resigned. } 1-0 

