{ In this game I was up against seasoned Grandmaster Michele Godena. I decided to bring the fight to him and try our special 7.Nbd2 line against 4...Bc5. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 $5 { Again, this move order is also possible to play the Scotch gambit, as you will see in the game. } 3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 { Approaching our pet line! } 5... exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 $3 { [%csl Gd2]We are back to business, and here we can see one of the main ideas of the entire course in action! Grandmaster Godena, being a seasoned veteran of the game, was definitely aware of this move, but already started to take a very long time to react. He pondered more than 20 minutes here. } 7... Bxd2+ { He decided to first take on d2. This move is analyzed in the course and in the game we transpose to the mainline of 4...Bc5 in our theory section. } 8. Bxd2 Nxe4 9. d5 { [%cal Gd5c6][%csl Rc6,Gd5]After studying the course we know that the d5-pawn is our best friend in this line. It cramps Black's entire army and sometimes selflessly sacrifices itself on d6. } 9... Nxd2 { [%cal Gd2f3][%csl Rf3]} 10. Qxd2 Ne7 { Perhaps the seasoned GM had seen this position before - after all, since he has played 1...e5 exclusively his entire life, he would definitely be aware of most or all of the Scotch gambit. However, perhaps he spent a lot of time trying to recall the theory, as I am sure he hadn't checked this gambit for a couple of years. [--] However, my next move he for certain had never seen before, as he started burning time on his clock and was looking troubled. } 11. h4 { [%cal Gh4h7][%csl Rg8,Gh4]The new idea in this 7.Nbd2 line! White shows his aggressive intent and keeps the position tense! } 11... d6 { [%cal Gc8h3]Now in the course I give } 12. O-O-O $5 ( 12. h5 { , which I believe gives Black less options. However, at the time of this game I was not yet fully aware of all the subtleties and chose to castle long first. } ) 12... c6 $6 { Two moves after the new idea 11.h4, the Grandmaster already goes wrong! Meanwhile, he has already spent more than one hour on his clock. } 13. dxc6 { [%cal Gd1d6,Gh1e1][%csl Rc6,Rd6,Re8]Taking the pawn, opening our Bishop, Queen and Rook. It looks like Black could not bear our strong d5-pawn. } 13... O-O 14. Qxd6 { A mistake, allowing Black to slip into an equal endgame. } ( 14. cxb7 { I don't know what ghosts I was afraid of during the game, but I did not take the free pawn... } 14... Bxb7 15. Qxd6 $14 { Now if Black plays } 15... Rc8 { , I am able to trade Queens and then simply play b3, defending my bishop. If he plays } ( 15... Qc8 { , keeping the Queens on the board, I can also play } 16. b3 { . Black would be fighting to stay in the game. In addition, White's pieces are all very active, and the White King's supposed weakness on the c-file is an illusion. } ) ) 14... Qxd6 15. Rxd6 Nxc6 16. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5c6][%csl Rc6]I had misjudged this endgame and the game soon ended in a draw. Yes, it was disappointing that I missed my chance, but I was never in danger to lose against the GM. He was on the ropes and If I had looked a bit deeper, I would have taken him down. } 16... Be6 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Rxc6 Bxa2 { Draw agreed. } 1/2-1/2 

