{ In this game I was up against a 2389 rated FIDE Master from India. It was a very disappointing game for me because I got a totally winning position from my opening preparation, playing a line I recommend in this course. However, in that tournament I was losing almost every game, and in this game too I did not convert my winning position. I have still included the game in the model game section, as it clearly shows that against such strong opposition the repertoire can be used to get you winning positions out of the opening. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 { Again this move order is also possible to reach our line! } 3... Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 { [%cal Gd4e5][%csl Rc5,Gd4,Re5]} 5... exd4 6. cxd4 { [%csl Rc5,Gd4,Ge4]} 6... Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 { [%cal Gb4e1,Gf6e4][%csl Rd2,Re4]Our pet line! } 7... Nxe4 8. d5 { [%cal Gd5c6,Gd2e4][%csl Gc4,Rc6,Gd5,Re4]Our signature blow. The d5-pawn is the backbone of this line. } 8... Nxd2 9. Bxd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Ne7 { We have arrived in the mainline again. In the course I recommend } 11. O-O-O ( 11. h4 { , but here I first castled long and then later tranposed to the course. } ) 11... d6 12. h4 { [%csl Gh4]Showing our aggressive intent! } 12... h6 13. h5 { [%csl Gh5]} 13... O-O 14. Rdg1 { [%cal Gg2g8,Gg2g4][%csl Gg1,Rg8]We are ready for the onslaught against Black's King. This position is deeply analyzed in chapter 4 (See the corresponding variation from the PGN) in the theory section! } 14... c6 $2 { [%cal Gc4f7][%csl Gc1,Gd2,Rd5]My opponent already had been burning alot of time and immediately blundered! } 15. g4 { [%csl Gg1,Gg4,Rg8]We take no prisoners. We go straight for mate! } 15... cxd5 { [%csl Rd5]Black seemingly wins a pawn. } 16. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3h7,Gg4g5,Gd2h6][%csl Gc1,Gd2,Gd3,Gg5,Rg8,Rh7]Despite being down 2 pawns, White's initiative is too strong. The computer already gives a +2 evaluation here. } 16... f6 { [%cal Gf6g5,Gd3h7][%csl Gd3,Rg5,Rg8,Rh7]Black stops g5 but forever weakens the light squares around his King. } 17. Kb1 { [%csl Gb1]White is in no rush! I take the time to bring my King to safety. } 17... Nc6 18. Bc2 { [%cal Gd2d5,Gd2d3,Gd3h7][%csl Gc2,Gd2,Rd5,Rg8,Rh7]Targetting the d5-pawn and also hinting at Qd3 ideas to give mate. } 18... Qe7 19. Nh4 { [%cal Gh4g6,Gg1e1,Gf2f4,Gd2d5][%csl Re7,Rf8,Rg8,Gh4]Another top move. With ideas such as Ng6 and Qxd5+ still in the air, and now our f-pawn can kick Black's Knight from e5. } 19... Ne5 20. Qxd5+ { [%cal Gd5g8][%csl Gd5,Rg8]Regaining a pawn. } 20... Be6 21. Qe4 { [%cal Gc2h7][%csl Gc2,Ge4,Rh7]Now I am ready to invade on h7. } 21... Rfc8 { Black allows it. } 22. Qh7+ { [%csl Gc2,Rg8,Gh7]Forcing the King out. The evaluation is already +4. } 22... Kf7 23. Nf5 $18 { [%cal Gf5e7,Gf5g7,Gh7g7,Gg4f5,Gg1g7][%csl Gc2,Re7,Gf5,Gg1,Rg7]Bringing the Knight into the game and forcing the Queen back. If Black takes } 23... Bxf5 { I would retake } 24. gxf5 { and open the Rook. White is completely winning, and the evaluation is almost +5. Just look how dangerous this opening is against titled players! This opening is not a one-off trick for blitz, but also gets you winning positions in classical chess. [--] Unfortunately I somehow went on to lose this game... At that point I was in terrible form and I played very badly and stupidly. I will not include the rest of the game because of how badly I played. I included part of this game in the model game section just to show how easily you can get winning positions from this repertoire, straight out of the opening. [--] I've played this repertoire against Grandmaster level opposition in tournaments with good results. This particular game I might have lost, but the opening was a success. May you all avenge me! } 0-1 

