{ Here we have Grandmaster Caruana championing our opening against GM Nakamura on the highest of levels! } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nbd2 $1 { [%cal Gd2e4,Gf6e4][%csl Gd2,Re4]Our move! } 7... Nxe4 8. d5 { [%cal Gd5c6][%csl Rc6,Gd5]The signature d5-pawn comes to play. } 8... Nxd2 9. Bxd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 { The mainline has been reached. Black has less space and is up a pawn, so he decides to trade pieces to 'relieve the pressure'. } 10... Ne7 11. h4 $3 { [%cal Gh4h6,Ge1c1][%csl Gd2,Gd5,Re8,Rg8,Gh1]This fresh idea keeps the fight going in this variation! Caruana easily crushed GM Nakamura in this line. } 11... d6 12. h5 { [%csl Gh5]Harry keeps going forward! } 12... h6 { [%csl Rh5,Gh6]} 13. O-O-O { [%csl Gc1,Gd1]White is playing bold chess. Again, by castling long, he signals his wicked intentions. } 13... O-O 14. Rdg1 $1 { [%cal Gg2g4][%csl Rg4]Not hiding his intentions - White clearly wants to play g4! } 14... b5 $5 { [%cal Gb5c4][%csl Rc4]A move that's covered in the course. This is an attempt at counterplay. } 15. Bb3 { [%cal Gb3d5][%csl Gb3]White wisely keeps the Queenside closed. } 15... Bg4 16. Nh4 { [%cal Gg4h5,Gf2f3,Gg2g4][%csl Gh4]White is ready to kick the Bishop and advance his pawns. } 16... c5 $6 { [%cal Gc5c4][%csl Gb5,Gc5]This is already a mistake. Black is too slow. As we explore in the theory section (See the corresponding variation from the PGN), } ( 16... c6 { is the best move for Black. } ) 17. f3 { [%cal Gf3g4][%csl Gf3,Rg4]Continuing our aggressive intent! } 17... Bxh5 $2 { Grabbing a fatal pawn. } 18. g4 { [%cal Gg4h5][%csl Gg1,Gg4,Gh1,Rh5]} 18... Bg6 19. Nf5 $3 { [%cal Gg1g8,Gh1h6,Gd2h6,Gf5g7][%csl Gf5,Rg7]Now all of White's forces are pointing at Black's King, and White is ready for all kinds of sacrifices. } 19... f6 20. Bc2 $1 { [%cal Gc2g6,Gf5e7][%csl Re7,Rg6]One final move! Bringing the Bishop into the attack and wanting to play Nxe7+, which would win a piece. } 20... Kf7 21. Nxg7 $3 { [%cal Gg6c2,Gg7e6,Ge6d8,Gd2h6,Gh1h6][%csl Rd8,Rg7]The final blow. After this Black is completely lost. He cannot recapture due to } 21... Rh8 ( 21... Kxg7 22. Qxh6+ { , and if he captures our Bishop with } ) ( 21... Bxc2 { we have the in-between move } 22. Ne6 $146 { , attacking his Queen. Look how easily GM Caruana took down GM Nakamura here with the line recommended in this repertoire. The rest of the game is not important, but until here it was very instructive! } ) 22. Ne6 Qg8 23. f4 Bxc2 24. Qxc2 Ke8 25. a4 a6 26. Qe2 Kd7 27. axb5 Qb8 28. Nxc5+ Kd8 29. Ne6+ Kd7 30. Nd4 Re8 31. Qe6+ Kc7 32. Kb1 Kb6 33. Rc1 axb5 34. Nc6 Qc7 35. Ne5 Nc6 36. Rxc6+ Qxc6 37. Nxc6 Rxe6 38. dxe6 Kxc6 39. Rxh6 Rg8 40. Rxf6 Rxg4 41. f5 Rg1+ 42. Kc2 Rg2+ 43. Kd3 Rxb2 44. Rf8 Rb3+ 45. Ke2 Rb4 46. Kf3 Rb3+ 47. Kf4 Rb4+ 48. Kg5 Re4 49. Kf6 1-0 

