{ This game saw IM Karacsonyi, Gellert vs 2600 Grandmaster Zilka Stepan. Let me tell you something: the guy with White is no ordinary IM, he is a Scotch gambit advocate. I have played against this guy with Black before, and while preparing I realized he only plays the Scotch gambit. I got so scared and decided to play the Caro-Kann and ended up winning. I knew that if I would have played 1...e5 vs a seasoned Scotch gambit player... It never would have ended well. See this game, for example. } 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { As we can tell from the move order, White is a real Scotch gambit ambassador. } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { [%cal Gc4f7][%csl Gc4,Rf7]} 4... Nf6 { Black enters the traditional mainline. } 5. e5 { [%cal Ge5f6][%csl Ge5,Rf6]} 5... d5 { [%cal Gd5c4][%csl Rc4]} 6. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8]} 6... Nd7 { A very modern move which is approved by the computer. However, White crushed it with the antidote that I worked out further in our repertoire! } 7. O-O { [%cal Gf3e5,Gb5e8][%csl Re8,Gf1,Gg1]} 7... Be7 8. c3 { [%cal Gc3d4,Gd1d5][%csl Gc3,Rd4]This is our move! We give up a pawn for quicker development. This way we make Black's life harder. } 8... dxc3 9. Nxc3 { [%cal Rd4d5,Gc3d5][%csl Gc3,Rd5]} 9... a6 { [%cal Ga6b5][%csl Rb5]Perhaps the main move, challenging our Bishop. } 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nd4 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gf2f4,Gf4f5][%csl Rc6,Gd4,Ge5,Re8]The Knight makes way for the f-pawn to get rolling! } 11... Nb8 12. f4 { [%csl Gd4,Ge5,Gf4]Here the pawn goes! } 12... c5 { [%cal Gc5d4][%csl Rd4]The best reaction to an attack on the Kingside is an attack in the center! Black is following all of these principles, but we are prepared for this very well in the course! } 13. Nc2 { [%cal Gc3d5,Gd1d5][%csl Rd5]} 13... d4 14. Qf3 { [%cal Gf3a8,Gd4c3][%csl Ra8,Rc3,Gf3]A strong in-between move, developing the Queen and attacking Black's Rook. } 14... Ra7 15. f5 $3 { [%cal Gd4c3][%csl Rc3,Ge5,Gf5]White is a true Scotch gambit player! White gives up a piece for the opening of Black's King. As we know in this opening, the initiative and development are very important, and at times we should not be afraid to give up material. } 15... dxc3 16. f6 { [%csl Re7,Gf6,Rg7]Going all in! } 16... gxf6 17. Rd1 $1 { [%cal Gd1d8][%csl Rd8]The Key in-between move that I give in the course! Black's Queen is now in a hot spot. } 17... Bd6 $4 { [%csl Rd6]Grandmaster Zilka blunders! He gives up the strong dark-squared Bishop that was holding his position together. } 18. exd6 { [%csl Gd6]We thank him. } 18... cxd6 19. bxc3 $18 { [%csl Gc3,Re8]} ( 19. Bf4 { was stronger here, but } ) ( 19. bxc3 { is also fine. Black's King is left for dead. Black has a destroyed pawn structure and terribly weak dark squares. White won this game without any problems. The rest of the game is not relevant to the opening, but please take a look for your own enjoyment! } ) 19... Rg8 20. Rb1 Be6 21. Bf4 Nd7 22. Rxd6 Qa8 23. Qe2 Ke7 24. Rd2 Qc6 25. Re1 Ne5 26. Bxe5 fxe5 27. Qxe5 Rd7 28. Rf2 Rd3 29. Qf5 $3 { [%cal Gf5d3,Gf5f7,Re1e7][%csl Rd3,Re6,Gf5,Rf7]} 29... Qd5 30. Qxf7+ Kd6 31. Qf4+ Kd7 32. Ne3 Qd6 33. Qe4 Kc7 34. Qxh7+ Qd7 35. Qe4 Re8 36. Rb2 Rb8 37. Reb1 Rxb2 38. Rxb2 Qd6 39. Rb7+ Kd8 40. Rb8+ Qxb8 41. Qxd3+ Kc7 42. Qxa6 Qb1+ 43. Kf2 Bxa2 44. c4 Qb2+ 45. Kf3 Kd7 46. Qa7+ Ke6 47. Qxc5 Qf6+ 48. Kg4 Qg6+ 49. Qg5 Qe4+ 1-0 

